    "Essentially, all models are wrong, but some are useful." (George Edward Pelham Box)

    Abstract‌

    Time series forecasting and analysis are helpful in the decision-making process. However, exogenous factors, nonlinearities, and seasonality make developing efficient forecasting models challenging. In this context, the use of machine learning approaches, especially ensemble learning models, becomes attractive. These approaches are based on the divide and conquer paradigm, where models are combined to generate an efficient model to solve regression (or time series forecasting), clustering, and classification tasks. This thesis aims to propose and evaluate the effectiveness of approaches based on ensemble learning models for time series forecasting problems. Four major contributions are presented in this thesis. The first one lies in applying and comparing bagging, boosting, and stacking ensemble learning methods with single models for the short-term forecasting of soybean and wheat prices for Parana state, Brazil. Also, the influence of exogenous variables to forecast these agricultural commodities is investigated. The second evaluates ensemble learning methods that consider the ensemble empirical mode decomposition, heterogeneous ensemble learning models, and multi-objective optimization to forecast the multi-step- ahead monthly incidence of meningitis cases in four Brazilian states. In the third, two time series pre-processing techniques are integrated with heterogeneous ensemble learning models to perform electricity energy load forecasting. Finally, a competitive ensemble model that combines bagging and stacking ensemble learning models is proposed for multi-step wind power generation forecasting. The forecasting performance of the proposed models is computed through different criteria measures such as mean absolute error, mean squared error, mean absolute percentage error, relative mean squared error, symmetrical mean absolute percentage error, and relative mean squared error. Also, the Diebold-Mariano test is adopted to evaluate the statistical difference between the forecasting errors of the compared models. With the results achieved in the case studies, it is possible to identify that the ensemble learning methods can reach lower forecasting errors when compared with single models, non-decomposed, non-optimized, and decomposed homogeneous ensemble learning models. The ensemble learning methods achieved a forecasting error lower than 1% for the first application concerning the percentage errors. To forecast meningitis cases, the proposed ensemble learning has an error that spans 4.52%â12.77%. For the third application, the proposed approach reached errors between 0.80% and 7.79%. Finally, concerning the fourth application, the cooperative and competitive ensemble learning model has errors that span 13.81%â21.20%. Therefore, the results indicate that using ensemble learning methods is promising to improve forecasting accuracy. Also, the models proposed in this thesis can be adapted for other areas and used to help the decision-making process.

    Keywords: Forecasting, Machine Learning, Mathematical Optimization, Time Series Analysis.

Chapter 1‌


Introduction



This chapter is designed to introduce the contextualization, justification of the research, research questions, and objectives of this thesis. Also, the contributions and document structure are presented.‌


    1. Contextualization

      The necessity of strategic planning development in the corporate world and the day- to-day makes the time series analysis and forecasting valuable tools to support the decision- making process in the short, medium, and long term. Due to nonlinearities, seasonality, trend, and cyclicity in the temporal data, the development of efficient forecasting models is a challenging task. In this thesis, an efficient forecasting model deals with the bias- variance trade-off while leading to high forecasting accuracy and errors with lower variance. In this context, competitions have already been proposed aiming to evaluate different approaches for time series forecasting, such as Kaggle (BOJER; MELDGAARD, 2020) and Makridakis (or M-competitions), (INGEL et al., 2020; MAKRIDAKIS et al., 2020a) forecasting competitions. According to Maldonado et al. (2019), a reduction of 1% in the forecast error can reduce the operational cost of the electric sector by US$ 10 million.

      The importance of forecasting accuracy permeates all fields of knowledge since the forecasting results are helpful in the decision-making process. Through the use of efficient forecasting models which reducing forecasting errors, managers can develop public policies to mitigate the effect of social problems, attract stakeholders, reduce losses, and leverage earnings. Indeed, forecasting is understood as the process to idealize the most probable result, assuming a set of premises inherent to several aspects regarding the analysis field.

      The approaches usually employed in the time series analysis and forecasting are related to statistical approaches. In this respect, Box & Jenkins (BOX et al., 2015) methodology through Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) and Seasonal Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (SARIMA) models, as well as Holt Winters,‌


      exponential smoothing, and its ensembles are usually adopted (CHATFIELD; XING, 2019). For these approaches, it is possible to observe applications in agriculture (SABU; KUMAR, 2020), electricity consumption (JIANG et al., 2020), healthcare (LIU et al., 2021), solar irradiation (GUREL et al., 2020), transport (ALZYOUT; ALSMIRAT, 2020) and, web traffic (ZHOU et al., 2020a), among others. Generally, most of the real data have a high degree of nonlinearity owing to speed changes in the pattern, which can lead the statistical model to achieve lower accuracy than other models. Through the use of this approach, high forecasting error signals tend to be obtained, since they cannot deal with some degrees of nonlinearity of the data.

      As an alternative to the use of statistical approaches, Artificial Intelligence (AI) methods have been used in the time series forecasting literature to obtain efficient fore- casting models, as observed in Mao et al. (2019) and Bonakdari et al. (2020), for example. AI is a tool able to recognize patterns of historical data and support the decision-making process by reproducing human intelligence. Based on this, in the field the data analysis, Machine Learning (ML) models become attractive approaches to perform time series forecasting. In fact, according to Mello and Ponti (2018), ML is interested in answering how a machine can learn specific tasks, as well as extracting features of the data. It makes these approaches attractive to conduct time series forecasting, since they are able to handle different kinds of data features. In Figure 1, the areas and subareas of ML can be seen. In this respect, it is possible to highlight that in this thesis, the focus is on supervised learning for regression problems and the subfield of time series forecasting.‌



      Fault Prediction

      Market Aggregation

      Regression

      Clustering

      Time Series Forecasting

      Supervised Learning

      Unsupervised Learning

      Group Segmentation

      Classification

      Machine Learning

      Dimentionality Reduction

      Bankrupcty Detection

      Feature Selection

      Disease Identification

      Reinforcement Learning

      Big Data Visualization

      Game AI

      Drone Monitoring

      Figure 1 â ML paradigm.

      Source: The author.


      According to Bates and Granger (1969), the combination of individual models provided satisfactory improvements in forecasting performance by averaging model errors, and thus reducing the forecasting uncertainty. Based on the ML field, one way to obtain accurate forecasting models is the use of regression ensembles (SAGI; ROKACH, 2018; DONG et al., 2020). An ensemble learning model is based on the divide and conquer paradigm which seeks to overcome the limitation of models that operate in isolation (REN et al., 2015b; DIVINA et al., 2018). Concerning this, different models or methods are combined to generate an efficient model to solve regression (or time series forecasting) (LEE et al., 2020), clustering (BAI et al., 2020), and classification (FENG et al., 2020) tasks. Bojer and Meldgaard (2021) reviewed the results of six forecasting competitions based on the online data science platform Kaggle. According to those authors, ML models are usually the winners of the aforementioned competitions since they can deal with the intermittency and they contained external information relevant to the forecasting task in the form of hierarchy information and predictive exogenous variables, such as holidays, events and promotions.

      Models featured as ensembles refer to multiple base models (base learners, or weak learners) combined to solve the same problem, where the aggregated decision is better than any of the individual models. This approach aims to obtain a robust system that incorporates the prediction from all base learners. In general, ensemble learning models achieve better results than single prediction models, since they have a better capacity to generalize and adapt in different scenarios (SOARES et al., 2018). The purpose of using regression ensembles is to combine a set of models to improve the forecasting accuracy, whose target variables are numerical (ALLENDE; VALLE, 2017). According to Atiya (2020), ensemble forecasting models work so well due to the diversity considered by this approach. However, it can be inaccurate if the data are rife with outliers, or have a very heavy-tailed distribution. The justification for the use of forecasting model combination is devoted to the three following factors: (i) through the use of a set of adequate forecasting methods, each model can deal with different data features, and when their results are aggregated, the forecasting accuracy is improved; (ii) there is a high uncertainty about which model is the most suitable for the forecasting task, independent of the field of application, and using several forecasting models in this context is attractive, and (iii) the combination of multiple forecasting models can reduce the forecasting errors by correcting different kinds of biases. Also, the use of ensemble learning methods can decrease the variance of the forecasts by reducing the uncertainty associated with selecting a particular model (HIBON; EVGENIOU, 2005).

      According to Opitz and Maclin (1999), an ensemble learning model can be classified as competitive or cooperative. Competitive ensemble learning methods have data, hyperparameters, and structural diversity. In this perspective, multiple predictors with different structures are used to construct the forecasting model as an ensemble


      learning model (REN et al., 2015a). The methods widely employed are bagging (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020) and boosting (KUMARI; TOSHNIWAL, 2021) for data diversity, stacking ensemble (FRACCANABBIA et al., 2020) for structure diversity, while the Kalman filter can be adopted to induce parameter diversity. On the other hand, cooperative ensembles integrate different methods designed to solve one task, aiming to maximize the forecasting systemâs performance in terms of error reduction. The final forecasts are obtained by aggregating the forecast values of all individual methods (REN et al., 2015a; HE; WANG, 2021). Moreover, pre-processing (MORENO et al., 2021), metaheuristics for hyperparameter tuning (SAHU et al., 2021), feature selection (IZIDIO et al., 2021), statistical methods (LIU et al., 2021a), and AI models (DUAN et al., 2021) can be used to compose this type of ensemble learning framework.

      Regarding cooperative ensemble learning models, time series pre-processing or decomposition methods are usually adopted for performance improvement. These methods divide the original series into different subseries called components. These components present high and low frequency, as well as trend and seasonality. In the modeling process, each component must be handled by one forecasting model. When the individual forecasts of each subseries are aggregated for obtaining the desired forecasting, the final model is featured as an ensemble. Alongside the use of time series decomposition methods, some choices are needed. The first is related to the selection of the forecasting method to handle the subseries. In this respect, when the same learning strategy is used for modeling all subseries, the final forecasting model can be featured as a cooperative homogeneous ensemble model. Otherwise, a cooperative heterogeneous ensemble model is defined if at least one subseries is handled by a different learning strategy from the remaining subseries. Moreover, the aggregation method plays a vital role in the efficiency of the forecasting model. In turn, Weight Integration (WI) and Direct Integration (DI) can be adopted. The first one refers to assigning weights to the subseries, and the second simply sums up the results of the subseries. From a broader perspective, choosing the correct strategy to compose an accurate forecasting ensemble learning model is a challenging task.‌

      In consideration of the aforementioned discussion, the main motivation of this thesis is the development of approaches based on efficient forecasting ensemble learning models to support the decision-making process. Therefore, the central hypothesis of this thesis is: the use of approaches based on ensemble learning methods can improve the accuracy of the forecasting models in one and multi-step-ahead forecasting time windows. Alongside that, to check this hypothesis, the Research Questions (RQs) and objectives are detailed in the section 1.2.‌‌


    2. Research Questions and Objectives

      To sum up, there are several gaps in the literature regarding the ensemble learning models for forecasting purposes such as those detailed in chapter 3. To fill these gaps, this thesis proposes to study and investigate the efficiency of forecasting ensemble learning models in the context of agribusiness prices, diseases incidence, electric energy demand, and wind power generation. Based on that, the following RQs are formulated:


      RQ 1 What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform price forecasting in agribusiness, epidemiology, load demand, and renewable energy?

      RQ 2 What are the appropriate price drivers to use as exogenous factors in the forecasting structure of agricultural commodities?

      RQ 3 Considering pre-processing methods in the composition of an ensemble learning models, what is the better choice between the heterogeneous and homogeneous ensemble for time series forecasting?

      RQ 4 What is the proper choice between weighted integration through Multi-Objective Optimization (MOO) and direct integration when time series pre-processing is used in the cooperative ensembles?‌

      RQ 5 What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?

      RQ 6 What gain is obtained by employing sequential decomposition methods over single decomposed methods for time series forecasting?

      RQ 7 What improvement is reached by combining bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods against the single stacking and statistical models?


      In order to answer the aforementioned RQs, the main objective of this thesis is to evaluate the effectiveness of approaches based on ensemble learning models for time series forecasting.

      The main objective is divided into specific objectives, which are defined as follows:


      1. To identify research gaps regarding ensemble learning methods for time series forecasting in the agribusiness, epidemiological, load demand, and renewable energy fields;

      2. To compare the performance of ensemble learning and non-ensemble models for time series forecasting based on the criteria Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Mean‌


        Absolute Percentual Error (MAPE), Symmetric Mean Absolute Percentual Error (sMAPE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), and Relative Root Mean Squared Error (RRMSE). Moreover, to use hypothesis tests to compare the forecasting errors;‌‌

      3. To measure the efficiency of signals pre-processing approaches coupled with ensemble learning models for time series decomposition;

      4. To discuss the advantages and disadvantages of Heterogeneous Ensemble Learn- ing (HTE) methods in relation to Homogeneous Ensemble Learning (HME) methods;‌

      5. To explore the potential of MOO in the aggregation of individual models to compose an ensemble learning model;

      6. To evaluate the accuracy based on the criteria defined in objective (b) of single decomposition methods regarding dual decomposition methods;


    3. Motivation‌

      The development of this thesis is justified owing to its contribution of evaluating the efficiency of different types of ensemble learning methods in the time series forecasting field. Also, through the identification of literature gaps regarding forecasting ensemble learning models, it is possible to develop accurate forecasting models and perform assertive decision-making in a range of applications.

      In this context, ensemble learning methods should be explored to perform time series forecasting. According to Dietterich (2000), there are three reasons to explore this technique, namely, statistical, computational, and representational. Also, the use of this approach is justified since it improves the inferences, increases the forecasting stability, and there is more tolerance for the data noise (VILLANUEVA, 2006).

      For these reasons, the use of ensemble learning methods can assist in the devel- opment of parsimonious models for forecasting and contribute to the strategic planning of companies and entities. The community will benefit from this research because when developing frameworks, refining or combining existing methodologies, it will be possible to make different applications that have a relevant appeal to society.‌


    4. Contributions

      Concerning the RQs and objectives formulated in subsection 1.2, this thesis has four major contributions validated by presenting four case studies. The first is devoted


      to performing price forecasting in the agribusiness area, and the second is related to the epidemiological field. The third contribution evaluates the efficiency of ensemble learning models for load demand forecasting. Finally, the last contribution is a cooperative ensemble model that combines bagging and stacking in an ensemble model for forecasting wind power generation. Moreover, some adjacent studies that are not detailed in this thesis are described. In the following, the four contributions of the thesis are summarized.

      The first contribution lies in the evaluation of ensemble learning method effi- ciency for short-term forecasting (one-month-ahead) in the agribusiness field. In fact, this contribution aims to address RQ 1 and RQ 2, as well as the specific objectives

      (a) and (b). The results of that proposal were published in Ribeiro and Coelho (2020). Specifically, the ensemble learning methods named bagging, boosting, and Stacked Gener- alized (STACK) were evaluated in the task of forecasting soybean and wheat prices for Parana (PR) state, Brazil. In the case of the bagging approach, Random Forest (RF) is adopted, while for boosting, Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) and eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) are used. The accuracy of these ensemble learning approaches were compared with non-ensemble models named K -Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Multilayer Perceptron Neural Network (MLP), and Support Vector Regression (SVR). The perfor- mance measures MAPE, MAE, RMSE, Mean Squared Error (MSE), and Diebold-Mariano test (DM) test were adopted.‌‌‌‌‌‌‌‌‌

      Additionally, it is well known that there are several exogenous variables such as supply and demand, exchange rate Exchange Rate (ER), Interaction Commodities Prices (ICP), and Foreign Market (FM) which affect the direction of agricultural commodity prices. In this respect, in addition the main objective of the first contribution, based on the related works regarding agricultural commodity price forecasting for the period of 2012 to 2018, the main price drivers for soybean and wheat prices were defined and their feature importance was computed. These price drivers are a 60 kg bag of soybean and wheat from the Center for Advanced Studies in Applied Economics (Centro de Estudos AvanÃ§ados em Economia Aplicada, in Portuguese) (CEPEA) â Luiz de Queiroz School of AgricultureâUniversity of Sao Paulo (Escola Superior de Agricultura Luiz de Queiroz â Universidade de SÃ£o Paulo, in Portuguese) (ESALQ-USP), the exchange rate (US$ for R$), average pump price (R$) per liter of ethanol PR, price of a 50 kg (R$) bag of wheat flour PR, and futures price of soybean and wheat contracts (US$) quoted on the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT).‌‌‌‌‌

      In the same direction of the first case study, it is possible to highlight the results published in Ribeiro et al. (2020), a study devoted to evaluate the efficiency of forecasting models in the context of New Coronavirus (COVID-19), which is not detailed in this document. In that paper, the objective was to develop efficient short-term forecasting models in order to help health managers to develop strategic planning in the public health


      system to avoid deaths. Some forecasting models, such as ARIMA, Cubist Regression (CR), RF, Ridge Regression (RR), SVR, and stacking ensemble learning, were considered to forecast the COVID-19 cumulative confirmed cases with one, three, and six-days-ahead in ten Brazilian states with a high daily incidence. In the stacking ensemble learning, CR, RF, RR, and SVR models are adopted as base models and Gaussian Process (GP) as a meta-model. The effectiveness of the models was evaluated based on Improvement Index (IP), MAE, and sMAPE criteria.‌‌‌

      In most of the cases, as pointed out in Ribeiro et al. (2020), SVR and stacking ensemble learning reached a better performance compared to the other models regarding adopted criteria. In general, the developed models can generate accurate forecasting, achieving MAPE in a range of 0.87% - 3.51%, 1.02% - 5.63%, and 0.95% - 6.90% in one, three, and six-days-ahead, respectively. The ranking of models in all scenarios is SVR, stacking ensemble learning, ARIMA, CR, RR, and RF models. The use of evaluated models is recommended to forecast and monitor the ongoing growth of COVID-19 cases, since these models can assist the managers in the decision-making support systems. This case study is related to specific objectives (a) and (b).

      As the second contribution presented in this thesis, the forecasting models for epidemiological time series were considered, and the results were published in Ribeiro et al. (2020a). This contribution aims to address RQ 1, RQ 3, RQ 4, and RQ 5, as well as the specific objectives (a) to (e). An ensemble learning framework was developed for multi-step-ahead (one, two and three-month-ahead) forecasting meningitis cases in four Brazilian states. The selected states are PR, Sao Paulo (SP), Rio de Janeiro (RJ), and Minas Gerais (MG). These states are selected on the basis of the high number of the cases reported in 2018. This ensemble learning method combines the pre-processing technique Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition (EEMD), HTE models of components, and MOO to aggregate the components and to obtain the final forecasting models. Specifically, the MOO approach is adopted to define weights and employ them in the signal aggregation. It was observed that the proposed ensemble learning model provided better results in terms of accuracy, wherein it simultaneously improves the forecasting accuracy and stability of meningitis cases compared to single, non-decomposed, and homogeneous forecasting models. In this regard, that case study seeks to add discussions in this field, taking into account that most of the discussions are regarding Single-Objective Optimization (SOO) for component aggregation.‌‌‌‌

      Concerning the field of decomposition and ensemble learning approaches adjacent to the last case study, in Ribeiro et al. (2020) an additional approach is described, which is an extension of Ribeiro et al. (2020). In that paper, HTE models are evaluated in the task of forecasting electricity price in the presence of some exogenous variables related to supply and demand. The forecasting horizon considered was one to three-months-ahead.


      The evaluated ensemble learning model was composed of the decomposition method, SOO, and HTE models regarding its forecasting structure. In fact, the Coyote Optimization Algorithm (COA) is adopted to tune the hyperparameters of Complementary Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition (CEEMD) in the pre-processing phase. Next, three ML models, including Extreme Learning Machine (ELM), GBM, and SVR models, as well as GP, are designed with the intent of handling the components obtained through the signal decomposition approach with focus on time series forecasting.‌‌

      Moreover, in the methodology adopted in Ribeiro et al. (2020), the individual forecasting models are DI in order to obtain the final forecasting prices one to three- months-ahead. In that case, a grid of forecasting models is obtained. The best forecasting model is the one that has better generalization out-of-sample. The empirical results show the efficiency of the proposed model. Additionally, it can achieve forecasting errors lower than 4.2% in terms of sMAPE. The ranking of importance of the variables from the smallest to the largest is lagged prices, demand, and supply. That paper provided useful insights for multi-step-ahead forecasting in the electrical market, since the proposed model can enhance forecasting accuracy and stability. Alongside this, in Ribeiro et al. (2021), seasonal-trend and multi-objective ensemble learning model for water consumption forecasting was proposed. Instead of using EEMD, the Seasonal-Trend Decomposition using of Time Series by Locally-Weighted Regression (STL) decomposition is used to deal with seasonal data. The findings suggest that the use of HTE provides more accuracy than non-decomposed and HME.

      Adjacent to the proposal of the use of EEMD combined with HTE ensemble learning model, in Ribeiro et al. (2022), several AI models including XGBoost, ELM, Long- Short Term Memory (LSTM), and SVR are used stand-alone, and coupled with the EEMD employed to decompose the time series into several intrinsic mode functions and residual signals. All AI techniques are evaluated in the task of forecasting the daily incidence of COVID-19 cases in ten Brazilian states, with a high number of cases by September 4th, 2020, forcasted seven and fourteen-days-ahead. Previous COVID-19 incidence cases and urban mobility information were employed as systems input for all forecasting models. The effectiveness of the models is evaluated based on the performance criteria. In general, the EEMD approach outperformed the compared models regarding the accuracy in 65% of the cases. Regarding the exogenous variables, urban mobility information indeed plays a key role in the forecasting task. Therefore, due to the efficiency of evaluated forecasting models to forecast cumulative COVID-19 cases up to fourteen-days-ahead, the adopted models can be recommended as promising models for forecasting and can be used to assist in the development of public policies to mitigate the effects of COVID-19 outbreak.

      The third contribution considers an ensemble learning model applied to Short- term Load Forecasting (STLF). Through this contribution, RQ 1, RQ 5, and RQ 6 are


      addressed, as well as the specific objectives (a) to (f). The framework is composed of the dual decomposition through STL and Variational Mode Decomposition (VMD) methods. The STL divides the time series into additive components called trend, seasonality, and remainder. The VMD divides the remainder components into four modes. Next, the COAâXGBoost is used to handle the seasonality. Finally, the RR is used to handle the trend and four modes. The forecasts were obtained from DI aggregation. This case study used twenty time series associated with the Australian Energy Market Operator (AEMO) across the five Australian regions. The proposed framework was evaluated considering the load forecasting half-an-hour, half-day, and one-day-ahead.‌

      Finally, in the fourth contribution, a cooperative ensemble learning model that combines STL pre-processing, bagging, and stacking ensemble learning methods was proposed for multi-step wind power generation forecasting. Through this contribution, RQ 1 and RQ 7 are addressed, as well as the specific objectives a) to e). The very short- term (10 and 30-minute) and short-term (60 and 120-minute) forecasting horizons were considered. The arithmetic and weighted average values are used to integrate the samples from the bagging strategy. The weights were defined through MOO, aiming to enhance the forecasting accuracy and stability simultaneously. To show the wide applicability of the non-linear ensemble learning model, it is extensively tested with measurement data collected from two wind farms in the Bahia state, Brazil. The empirical results evidenced that the proposed forecasting model can outperform the single stacking ensemble learning model, some ML methods, and statistical methods in terms of accuracy improvement.

      The subsection 1.5 summarizes the papers related to the content of this thesis.‌

    6. Outline‌

The remainder of this thesis is structured into five chapters, which are detailed in the following. Chapter 2 details the main theoretical aspects employed in the development of each case study. In fact, the background regarding time series forecasting is presented, the ML models employed in the case studies, and the pre-processing techniques in the field of time series forecasting are detailed. In the next, some concepts about optimization are described. Finally, the chapter is concluded with the presentation of criteria adopted to evaluate the forecasting models performance and hypothesis tests for the errors. In chapter 3 the works related to the four case studies are presented. Next, in chapter 4 four case studies are presented, based on theoretical backgrounds of chapter 2, to attend the RQ and specific objectives (a) up to (f). Specifically, for each case study, through the grid of related works presented in chapter 3, the literature gaps are identified. In turn, the objectives and contributions of each case study are detailed. Finally, the methodologies are described. Also, in chapter 5, the results, discussions, and conclusions of each case study are described. Finally, chapter 6 concludes this thesis and describes some research opportunities. In Figure 2 the thesisâ structure is presented.

Chapter 2‌


Theoretical Background




    1. Time Series‌

      In this section, the main aspects related to time series forecasting and analysis are presented.

      In supervised learning, there are two main tasks named classification and regression. In this thesis, the focus is on regression problems. However, in this field of application, there are two concepts related to that. They are prediction and forecasting. Indeed, prediction is concerned with estimating the outcomes for unseen data. In this context, a model is fitted using training data, and new predictions are obtained. In other words, a prediction tries to explain the underlying relation between dependent and independent variables to explain some outcome or future event. For example, for some features related to the energy efficiency of a set of residential buildings, it is desired to predict the heating and cooling load (output variables). In this type of problem, the variable to be predicted is observed in a given timestamp.

      On the other hand, given a sample of historical data related to some output variable, it could be required to know future values. For this context, it is needed to obtain forecasting for some timestamps in the future. This process uses past and current information related to the outcome of interest. For example, given some lagged values related to the gold price, there is interest in forecasting the gold price for the next week. The gold price is observed several times into sequential timestamps, and there is a temporal dependency between the lagged observations. According to Brown (1963), the prediction term has Latin origins and means âsay beforehandâ. Overall, the prediction term can refer to subjective estimates of the futures, such as the impact of a new product in the market or the price of some object based on their features. Moreover, forecasting is of Saxon origin and means to âthrow aheadâ, implying that there is something in hand to be thrown. Forecasting can provide a basis for economic and business planning, production planning, inventory and production control, and control and optimization of industrial processes


      (BOX et al., 2015). Therefore, it could be seen that every forecast is a prediction, but not all predictions are forecasts.

      A time series is a set of observations ordered over time, where yt â R, in which t is the instant where the value of y is recorded. The time series analysis is focused on the study of the time or frequency, where parametric and non-parametric models can be adopted, respectively (MORETTIN; TOLOI, 2006). The initial steps of the time series modeling aim to analyze the behavior of the data, where tendency, seasonality, and cyclicity can be identified. From this point, data modeling must follow some steps to accommodate these characteristics.

      Gathering information

      Choosing the forecasting models

      Given a time series, the most common problem is developing accurate models to perform forecasting based on past data and exogenous factors that might impact the predictive analysis. Moreover, associated with the forecasting task, the forecasting horizon must be defined, split into short, medium, and long-term. These kinds of forecasting windows can be characterized by a specific number of steps-ahead in the future, which are particular for each field of knowledge and time sampling and the decision-making process. According to Athanasopoulos and Hyndman (2018) the short-term are needed for the scheduling of personnel, production, and transportation. In its turn, the medium-term is required for companies to develop predictive maintenance in equipment. Finally, long-term forecasts are used in strategic planning. Such decisions must take account of market opportunities, environmental factors, and internal resources. Figure 3 shows five steps usually adopted during the forecasting process.




      1

      2

      3

      4

      5

      Problem definition

      Exploratory data analysis

      Models' performance evaluation

      Figure 3 â Roadmap of forecasting task.

      Source: The author.


      The problem definition needs to define the field of application, such as economy, renewable energy, or healthcare, for example. In this step, it is necessary to determine the forecasting horizon based on the implications for supporting the decision-making. Also to define the experimental protocol is an important step. In the second step, the data required


      to meet the specified objective must collect. However, in some cases, it is a challenging task. Therefore, the researcher must acquire the available data since some forecasting models require much data to learn the patterns. Besides that, a deep knowledge of the data, such as the information that affects the forecasts, is needed. For this purpose, the interdisciplinary plays a key role, where the experts in the field of applications can provide valuable information regarding the problem and adopted data. In the exploratory data analysis, investigations are conducted to verify if the data has some characteristics, such as seasonality (repetitive pattern according to some periodicity), trend (behavior related to the series growth or decreasing), cyclicity (pattern without a fixed period), stationarity (the series develops randomly over time around a constant average), and nonlinearity. Figure 4 illustrates some of these features for the time series related to the dengue cases in PR, from January 2007 to December 2017 (BRAZIL, 2019). The first plot represents the observed time series, the second component shows the residual that presents some degrees of nonlinearity, the third represents the seasonal pattern, and the last, the trend of the series in some periods.

      Moreover, autocorrelation and cross-correlation analysis can be conducted to define if the inputs of the adopted model are only past values of the series or exogenous variables (ATHANASOPOULOS; HYNDMAN, 2018). Once the data characteristics are identified, it is necessary to define the model taking into account these features and the available data. Statistical and ML models can be considered, in which Cross-Validation (CV) can be used to ensure the model generalization. Finally, several punctual criteria and hypothesis tests must be used to validate the adopted and compared approaches.


      In the following sections and subsections, the main techniques employed to meet the aforementioned steps are detailed.‌


      1. Cross-Validation

        Different parameters must be defined for each forecasting model. Therefore, a way to determine the appropriate combination of parameters of the models discussed is by Grid-Search (GS) using CV. Through this, it is possible to minimize forecasting errors associated with test samples to find the set of hyperparameters that maximize some performance measures of the models and avoid overfitting. In the field of time series forecasting, according to Athanasopoulos and Hyndman (2018), the approach of Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation (LOOCV) or walk forward are suitable. These approaches can also be understood as a CV procedure in sequential blocks and a particular case of k-fold CV.‌

        In this perspective, the training is iterative and uses training and validation sets. The walk-forward validation is carried out several times, and in each iteration, the training set contains more observations than in the previous iteration. The corresponding training set consists only of observations that occurred before the observation that forms the validation set (ATHANASOPOULOS; HYNDMAN, 2018). The major drawback of this approach is the computational cost, mainly when the adopted time series is significant, and according to Bergmeir et al. (2018) the block-k-fold CV could be an alternative for both mentioned methods. In the LOOCV, in each iteration, the first observation of the training set is leave out, and the validation observation of the previous step is added in the training set. Next, the following observation is used to validate the trained model. At the final of the process, the CV error is equal to the average of the error for each "fold". Figure 5 shows the LOOCV and walk forward procedures.

        In the sliding window or LOOCV with time slice, the training process starts with some observations of the training set to train the forecasting model and validate the trained model. A performance measure is computed by comparing the forecast value and the observation not used in the training process. In the next iteration, the first observation used in the training process is leave out. Then that observation used for validation is incorporated into the training set, the model has trained again and validated in the next observation. An error measure is computed in each iteration, and at the end of the training process, the average is calculated. The walk forward approach is similar to LOOCV. However, the difference is that in this approach, in each iteration, some observation is added in the trained process, and no observation used in the previous stage is leave out of the training process.

        To perform both CV using the R software (R Core Team, 2020) the trainControl

        function contained in caret package is used. In the case of LOOCV, the parameters are:

        1. method equals timeslice, (ii) initial window equals to the desired size of the training set, (iii) horizon, equals to the desired horizon of the training set to compose the validation set and (iv) fixed window equals true. On the other hand, in the walk forward approach, the fixed window is defined as equals to false (KUHN; JOHNSON, 2013). Alternatively, the function tsCV can be adopted for any forecasting model that belongs to the forecast package (HYNDMAN et al., 2020; HYNDMAN; KHANDAKAR, 2008).‌


      2. Recursive Technique for Multi-Step-Ahead Forecasting

        To develop multi-step forecasting, recursive or iterated strategy can be employed (TAIEB et al., 2012). In this aspect, one model is fitted for a one-step-ahead time window. Next, the recursive procedure uses the forecasting value as an input for the same model to forecast the next step, continuing this manner until reaching the desirable horizon.

        Two situations should be considered. The first one lies in the use only the past values of the original series as inputs of the model, defined by autocorrelation analysis, or evolutionary algorithms, for example (ATHANASOPOULOS; HYNDMAN, 2018). Considering only the lags of the series as inputs of the model, the training structure can be stated as follows:


        y(t+1) = f {yt, . . . , yt+1âny + E, (2.1)

        where f is a function related to the adopted model in the training stage, yt+1 is the value of the time series one-step-ahead, ny = 1, . . . , n are the lags of the series, E is the random error that should be independent and identically distributed.

        When the aim is to obtain the cases up to H steps-ahead, the following structures can be considered,


        ï£±ï£´f yt, ytâ1, . . . , ytâny +11 if h = 1

        yËt+h = ï£²ï£´f yËt+hâ1, . . . , yËt+1, yt, . . . , yt+hâny 1 if h â [2, . . . , ny]

        ï£´ï£³f yËt+hâ1, . . . , yËt+hâny 1 if h â [ny + 1, . . . , H],

        (2.2)


        where yËt+h is the forecast value at time t and forecast horizon up to h, yt+hâny and yËt+hâny are the previously observed and forecast cases lags in ny = 1, . . . , n. When exogenous variables related to the input variable are adopted, a vector x of exogenous variables must be considered and incorporated in Eq. (2.1) and Eq. (2.2), with lags according to the forecasting horizon desired.

        Regarding the recursive strategy, the weakness is related to the cumulative errors according to the expansion of the forecasting horizon. Moreover, looking for the Eq. (2.2), it is possible to observe that for the h-th forecasting horizon, there is ny â (h-1) observed values, and h-1 predicted values are used as the inputs in the case of h-1 < ny. Otherwise, the set of inputs is composed only of the predicted values, reducing the forecasting accuracy. Figure 6 illustrates the recursive strategy when four lags are used as inputs of the model in the forecasting horizon of 3-steps-ahead.


        Forecasting Horizon


        Input

        h = 1



        Output

        h = 2


        h = 3


        Figure 6 â Scheme of the recursive forecasting strategy for 3-steps-ahead.

        Source: The author.


        Alongside this, other strategies can be considered to perform multi-step-ahead forecasting, such as the direct combination of recursive and direct, Multiple Input and Multiple Output (MIMO), as well as direct and recursive combined with MIMO. Each one of them has its vantages and disadvantages. The advantage of the recursive lies in using one model to forecast all steps-ahead, that is, training one model to forecast a one-step-ahead horizon and using it for multi-step-ahead forecasting tasks by updating the inputs of the matrix. The errors accumulation is its main drawback. On the other hand, the direct strategy uses only past values to predict the future, which is its advantage, as it does not accumulate prediction errors. However, its disadvantage lies in the necessity to fit or train a new model for each forecasting horizon. Therefore, this disadvantage makes the forecasting process computationally intensive. There is a trade-off between computational cost and accuracy in the choice of a multi-step-ahead forecasting strategy.

        According to Ma and Fildes (2020), comparative studies between recursive and direct strategies have shown contradictory results regarding the strategy that leads to better forecasting accuracy. While Rana and Rahman (2020) achieved better results for direct over the recursive, Xue et al. (2019) provided evidence of better results from the recursive over the direct forecasting strategy. To summary, according to Taieb and Atiya (2016), the recursive strategy is helpful to produce recursive multi-step-ahead forecasting for short time series using the same model due to allowing more flexibility for the forecasting model. The direct strategy can provide better forecasting for the case of long time series or if it needs a minimal bias. Combining the MIMO strategy with recursive or direct strategies is also attractive for short time series and long-term time windows because they provide a balance for bias and variance. From a broader perspective, the choice of the multi-step-ahead strategy depends on factors such as times series behavior (linear or nonlinear) and forecasting model (linear or nonlinear) (TAIEB, 2014).

        ML models, sometimes, have high training time, either owing to the use of different training strategies such as using CV, or even due to the number of hyperparameters to be


        tuned. In this context, because in the case studies detailed in chapter 4 several models are evaluated, the recursive forecasting strategy is adopted. Therefore, even though the recursive could lead to high forecasting errors, this thesis uses it due to its lower computational cost. However, the direct and the aforementioned methods can be considered.‌


    2. Forecasting Models

      In this subsection, the forecasting models employed in each case study described in the chapter 4 are detailed.‌


      1. Artificial Neural Networks

        Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) are mathematical models that simulate the biological neuron behavior and acquire knowledge through experience. They are able to solve classification (AN et al., 2020), clustering (LUO, 2020), or regression (MARIANI et al., 2019) tasks. According to Haykin (2009), an ANNs is a massively parallel distributed processor made up of simple processing neurons that has a natural tendency for storing experiential knowledge and making it available for use. In the field of time series forecasting, it is possible to consider that ANNs are efficient and reliable black-box models able to deal with several features of temporal data such as nonlinearities and noise of the time series signal. Figure 7 represents ANNs composed of one input layer with, two hidden layers, and one output layer.


        Input Layer

        Hidden Layer 1

        Hidden Layer 2

        Output Layer


        Figure 7 â Illustration of ANNs.

        Source: The author.


        ANNs are composed of a neuron model (information processing unit), an architec- ture (set of neurons interconnected and with some weights), and a learning algorithm (used to train the ANN). Moreover, a neuron comprises synaptic weights, an adder (used to sum


        up the input signals), and one activation function (step where the neuron is processed). The ANNs are composed of layers, with units that can be connected to units in the back layer.

        In this subsection, the models related to ANNs used in the chapter 4 are described.‌


        1. Bayesian Regularized Neural Network


          The Bayesian Regularized Neural Network (BRNN) is a kind of feedforward neural network, composed by one input and one hidden layer, which uses the Bayesian methods, such as Empirical Bayes, for parameter estimation, with the purpose of avoiding overfitting (MACKAY, 1992). The mathematical modeling can be stated as follows,

        2. Multilayer Perceptron Neural Network


          The MLP is a kind of feedforward neural network proposed to overcome the limitations of single perceptron (RUMELHART; MCCLELLAND, 1987). This method can solve nonlinear problems and is then suitable for problems associated with time series. This architecture has three essential features stated as follows: (i) Each neuron in the network includes a differentiable activation function, (ii) the network exhibits a high degree of connectivity, and (iii) contains one or more hidden layers between the input and output layers. To train the MLP several approaches can be adopted, such as the error backpropagation algorithm. This approach proceeds in two phases, namely forward and backward (MABU et al., 2015).

          ï£º

          In addition, the mathematical expression for this network can be stated as follows:

      2. Cubist Regression

        The CR is a rule-based model, which performs predictions following the regression of trees principle (QUINLAN, 1993). Given a regression tree, for each leaf is constructed a linear regression model, or in this case, a rule, associated with the information contained in each leaf. Once all rules are built, the final predictions are based on the linear combination of developed rules. The main difference between a simple regression tree and a CR model is how the models make predictions within the nodes (WORLAND et al., 2018).

        Attempting to improve the modelâs accuracy, this rule-based model generates a set of rules, named of committee, as happens with the boosting approach. Also, given a set of new features, the CR can adjust the model prediction using samples from the training set by employing the neighborhood concept, like the KNN (AHA et al., 1991). To find a number of neighbors, a distance measure is applied in this case, Manhattan. Finally, once the set of committees and number of neighbors are defined, the final rule prediction is the simple average of committees predictions.‌


      3. Ensemble Learning Methods

        Models featured as ensembles refer to multiple base models (base learners or similar techniques) combined to solve the same problem, where the aggregated decision is better than any individual model. It is an approach designed to obtain a robust system in terms of accuracy that incorporates the prediction from all base models. The general prediction is obtained by aggregating, on average, the results of the individual predictions (VILLANUEVA, 2006). In general, according to Allende and Valle (2017), the advantages of combining models for time series forecasting can be credited to three aspects as follows:

        1. It increases overall forecast accuracy to a large extent by using appropriate aggregation techniques;

        2. There is uncertainty about the optimal forecast model and, in such situations, combination strategies are the most suitable alternatives;

        3. The combination of multiple forecasts can efficiently reduce the errors. According to Bates and Granger (1969), the combination of individual models provided satisfactory improvements in forecasting performance by averaging model errors, and thus reducing the forecasting uncertainty.

        Using ensembles to carry out forecasting can be justified in different ways. For example, it may be associated with a more remarkable ability to generalize results, reduced variance of the model, and greater tolerance to data noise (MENDES-MOREIRA et al., 2012). From a broader perspective, regression ensembles comprise a set of tools to create predictive systems with high accuracy. The advantages of the ensemble learning methods are: (i) better capacity of generalization compared to individual models, (ii) flexibility to adapt to different tasks, (iii) ability to model nonlinear patterns, (iv) handling missing data, and (v) identifying the importance of inputs variables. On the other hand, it has the following disadvantages: (i) difficulty in determining values for the set of hyperparameters,

        1. high computational costs, (iii) difficulty in definition of models for the composition of the ensemble, and (iv) difficulty to interpret the results (ANIFOWOSE et al., 2015; QURESHI et al., 2017).

          According to Opitz and Maclin (1999) an ensemble learning model can be classified as competitive or cooperative. Competitive ensemble learning methods have data, hyper- parameters, and structural diversity. In this perspective, multiple models with different learning structures are used to construct the forecasting model in the way of an ensemble learning model (REN et al., 2015a). In this context, the methods widely employed are bagging (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020) and boosting (KUMARI; TOSHNIWAL, 2021) for data diversity, stacking ensemble (FRACCANABBIA et al., 2020) for structure diversity. At the same time, the Kalman filter can be adopted to induce parameter diversity.


          Cooperative ensembles integrate different methods designed to solve one task, aiming to maximize the performance of the forecasting system in terms of errors reduction. In addition, these types of ensembles are also named hybrid methods. The final forecasts are obtained by aggregating the forecast values of all individual models (REN et al., 2015a; HE; WANG, 2021). In this context, pre-processing (MORENO et al., 2021), metaheuristics for hyperparameters tuning (SAHU et al., 2021), feature selection (IZIDIO et al., 2021), statistical models (LIU et al., 2021a), and ML models (DUAN et al., 2021) can be used to compose this type of ensemble learning. Regarding cooperative ensemble learning models, time series pre-processing or decomposition methods are usually adopted for performance improvement. Indeed, these methods divide the original series into subseries named components with high and low frequency, trend, and seasonality. In the modeling process, each component must be handled by one forecasting model. Finally, the individual forecasts of each subseries are aggregated to obtain the desired forecasting.

          Mathematically, given a time series of n observations and m inputs, D =

          {(xi, yi)|xi â Rm, yi â R}, where x is the vector of inputs y is the vector of outputs, an ensemble model uses an aggregation function G that aggregates the predictions of K base model f1(x), . . . , fK(x) towards predicting a single forecasting model as follows:


          yËi = G(f1(x), . . . , fK(x)), (2.6)

          where yËi is the forecasting value of i-th observation of time series in specific time window. Overall, the success of ensemble models is related to the diversity of their base models. In this direction, Brown et al. (2005) showed in terms of errors decomposition why diversity is an important aspect in ensemble learning modeling. Their conclusions lead to the fact that the ensemble is better than a single learner due to the sum of bias, variance, and covariance of the ensemble membersâ errors.‌


          1. Bagging Ensemble Learning


            Bagging is an ensemble learning method proposed by Breiman (1996) and is also called bootstrap aggregation. It aims to decrease the variance of the forecasting model (regression tasks) or classifier (classification tasks) and avoid an overfitting. Indeed, owing to its versatility and efficiency in dealing with different kinds of data, bagging has been successfully applied to solve different problems, such as wind power forecasting (HARROU et al., 2019), streamflow forecasting (RIBEIRO et al., 2020), the strength of hollow concrete (SHARAFATI et al., 2021), and classification of voltage sags (MOHAMMADI et al., 2021).

            It works by generating multiple versions of original raw data, with replacement, and using them to obtain an aggregated predictor. The bagging prediction is obtained through the aggregation of synthetic samples, which is the arithmetic average commonly



            Bootstrap sample 1‌


            Prediction 1

            Base model 1

            Time series

            Bagging predictions

            adopted as an aggregation strategy. Considering that this aggregator is sensitive to outliers, in some cases, it can lead to inaccurate forecasts in the case of the time series. The new samples are generated by bootstrapping, which allows the generation of multiple samples for the same set. The advantage of using this technique for ensemble generation relies in the reduction of errors in the baseline predictors (HAMZE-ZIABARI; BAKHSHPOORI, 2018). In general, the learning process is conducted using homogeneous predictors, independently of each other in parallel manner. Dantas and Cyrino Oliveira (2018) detailed in terms of MSE decomposition into three terms named, the variance of the real values, the squared bias of the forecasts and their variance why bagging working for time series forecasting. Figure 8 illustrates the bagging ensemble model. In this opportunity, the base models are Decision Trees (DT) and the arithmetic average is the aggregation strategy.

            Overall, the bagging approach involves three steps: Using the bootstrap technique,


            adopting base models to train and forecast the new synthetic samples, and an aggregating operator to find the final forecasts. Alongside this, pruning strategies can select the most suitable base models to compose the ensemble structure. The time series analysis is a challenging task since the data are auto-correlated. In this case, for the case study presented in section 4.4, instead of apply a traditional bootstrap strategy for non-correlated data, Moving Blocks Bootstrap (MBB) is used. The MBB was proposed by Kunsch (1989), and it consists of resampling the data inside overlapping blocks until the desired horizon is reached to imitate the autocorrelation of the data. In this method, given a time series with n observations (samples) and a block size of length l, there are n â l + 1 possible blocks. From these blocks, n/l blocks are selected randomly and they will be gathered in order, to build the bootstrap observations. The time series values can be repetitive in different blocks. To deal with non-stationarity and autocorrelation of the data, Bergmeir et al. (2016) proposed to use n/l + 2 blocks.‌

            In the following, two bagging based ensemble approaches are detailed.‌


                    1. Random Forest


                      When the bagging ensemble is adopted, and base learners are DT, the built trees may have similar characteristics, thus implying an absence of diversity. A way of circumventing this problem is to use RF (BREIMAN, 2001), which can be understood as modeling using bagging together with a random selection of predictors to compose each node of the DT. This method, together with the selection of the best set of characteristics that explain the data, represents an important step in this approach (THAKUR; KUMAR, 2018).

                      Following the method described by Breiman (2001), the RF performs in the following way: (i) Given a training set with n observations for the output variable and x predictors or input variables, m samples are generated via the bootstrap technique, (ii) beginning from the previous item, m regression trees are built, one for each sample, each node containing a randomly chosen subset of x predictor variables, (iii) with the best subset obtained in step (i), an estimate of the response variable is generated from each regression tree, and (iv) a final prediction is generated by arithmetic average considering the estimates obtained in step (iii). In general, the main objective of this approach is to improve the performance of regression trees through the reduction of their variance (ASSOULINE et al., 2018).

                      Mathematically, the final prediction achieved by RF can be computed as follows,

                    2. Quantile Random Forest


            The Quantile Random Forest (QRF) (MEINSHAUSEN, 2006) approach is an extension of the RF ensemble model (BREIMAN, 2001). It provides information about the full conditional distribution of the response variable, and not only about the conditional mean. In this approach, the use of conditional quantile is to enhance the RF performance, which makes this a consistent approach (MEINSHAUSEN, 2006). The main assumption about QRF lies in the weighted observations that can be used for estimating the conditional average (VAYSSE; LAGACHERIE, 2017). Additionally, while the RF approach retains the resultâs information about the average of observations number of the leaves, the QRF keeps all observations contained in the leaves to estimate, such as follows,


            PË (yt+h â¤ y|px) = FË(y|px), (2.8) in which the left side of the equation represents the conditional probability of the number

            of observations conditioned to the predictors, being yt+h the observations in a h horizon and px the number of predictors. The right side refers to the conditional distribution function of the average notification numbers regarding the predictors. Considering that QRF uses the quantiles in the prediction process, the Î±-quantile of conditional distribution function is stated as the probability that the observed values is lower than QÎ± if the given px is equals to Î±, where the estimate of Î± is stated as follows:

            2006). For the QRF architecture only the number of randomly selected predictors should be determined.‌


          2. Boosting Ensemble Learning


            Boosting is a technique used to solve problems of classification and regression, which combines a set of weak models (usually DT) whose individual performance can be considered weak. Whereas when the individual predictions are aggregated, a model of high accuracy is obtained. Its central focus is bias reduction, that is, improving the suitability of the model to data (SCHAPIRE, 1990). It learns from the errors of previous iterations by increasing the importance of those wrongly predicted training instances in future iterations. Moreover, the base models of the boosting approach are trained iteratively. Therefore, it


            is an approach classified as iterative or dependent on the base model training. Several ML models have been proposed in this idea, and the GBM and XGBoost should be highlighted, which are described in the following.

            Figure 9 illustrates the boosting ensemble model. In this opportunity, the base models are DT.

                    1. Gradient Boosting Machines‌


                      The generalized boosted regression modeling or GBM model is based on the boosting principle, proposed by Friedman (2001), which seeks to find an additive model that minimizes a loss function. By using a gradient descent approach, the GBM builds models in the negative sense of the partial derivative of the loss function regarding the set of predictors. The GBM is executed according to an iterative process so that a regression model is fitted to the data, and the residuals are obtained. A new model is adjusted for previous residuals, a new prediction, to which the initial forecast is added, and then a new residue measure is obtained. This process is performed iteratively until a convergence criterion is reached (usually the number of base models).

                      Adjacent to the improvement that can be reached by the GBM structure, this process tends to generate overfitting. To avoid it, a regularization parameter regarding the


                      learning rate is used. In this thesis, for the adopted GBM approach, control hyperparameters such as the number of boosting iterations, maximum tree depth, shrinkage and minimum terminal node size are used.

                      The step by step of GBM is described as follows:

                    2. eXtreme Gradient Boosting‌


            The XGBoost is a boosting-based ensemble learning model (CHEN; GUESTRIN, 2016). It uses several base learners, such as regression trees to predict an output, and through their results aggregation, a strong and efficient ensemble could be obtained. In the perspective of time series forecasting, the XGBoost proved to be an effective tool to deal with cyclical/seasonal data due to its learning ability (YU et al., 2020). Two main advantages are attributed to XGBoost, that is, the preventive overfitting, and optimization of available computational resources. In this respect, to prevent overfitting the shrinkage operation is introduced. In each iteration, considering DT as a base model, each leaf node weight of the tree is multiplied by a coefficient reducing the impact on the results. Less importance is given to trees with the worst generalization. Moreover, inputs sub-sampling helps to avoid model overfitting and optimizing the model training speed by sampling inputs columns (HUANG et al., 2020).


            Let [xi, yi] be an ordered pair of observations, in which xi â Rd is a set of input variables, and yi â R its respective output variable, the predicted output is given by a sum of individual predictions and computed as following:

            • Learning rate is a real variable that refers to the step size shrinkage used in the update to prevents overfitting related to the boosting approach.             • L1 and L2 regularization terms on weights or models parameter are real variables, that shrinks the weights such as in Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator (LASSO) and RR methods, respectively. Greater values of these hyperparameters make the model conservative.

          3. Stacked Generalization


            Stacking ensemble learning is an approach that combines different prediction models in a single model, working at levels or layers. This approach introduces the concept of meta-learning, represents an asymptotically optimal learning system. It aims to minimize the errors of generalization by reducing the bias of its forecasting models for the time series (WOLPERT, 1992; LAAN et al., 2007). Usually, the stacking framework applies the learning using two layers (level-0 and level-1).

            In layer-0, different models are trained, and subsequently, the prediction of the


            response variable for each one is performed. These forecasts are used as an input set for the layer-1 model. This model, also named the meta-model, is trained, and its prediction is the desired result. In general, the model of the subsequent level learns from the previous level models, where each model of the level immediately below provides its best estimate (SHAMAEI; KAEDI, 2016; SERBES et al., 2015; PETROPOULOS et al., 2017). In general

            lines, the model in layer-1 learns with the predictions of the models of layer-0. Particular attention should be given such that the number of levels does not need to be restricted to two. The rule is that the l level model must use the predictions of the l â 1 level models (PERNÃ­A-ESPINOZA et al., 2018).

            Figure 10 illustrates a two-layers stacking ensemble learning. First, the inputs and outputs are used to train the base models which compose layer-0. In this case the models DT, ANNs, and KNN are considered. In the next, the SVR is used as a meta-model in layer-1. The main improvement in the predictive results when the stacking ensemble is applied is apparent when there is diversity among the models of the different levels. It occurs because models with different principles of generalization tend to yield different results (MENDES-MOREIRA et al., 2012). Diversity can be included in the modeling process by using models that follow different learning strategies, using different data characteristics and/or observations. In this way, the objective is that models of different levels disagree with each other, introducing diversity in the set that allows for the modeling of different dynamic patterns in a scenario of time series forecasting (CERQUEIRA et al., 2017a).‌


      4. k-Nearest Neighbors

        Such as several models for supervised learning, KNN approach can be applied in classification, and regression problems (AHA et al., 1991). Given some features, exogenous or explanatory variables, of a new observation to be predicted on KNN finds the k training observations that are closest to the new observation according to some distance metric and returns their average explained variable. The underlying intuition to using KNN on time series forecasting is that any time series contains repetitive patterns. It is possible to observe the previous similar patterns and use them to predict the next values (MARTÃNEZ et al., 2019). Adjacent to the simplicity of this approach, the computational cost may be a disadvantage.

        In fact, in the time series context, let y = {y1, . . . , yn} be a training set of output variables composed by n observations (n = 1,. . ., t), in which each yn is an n-th output variable associated to x set of inputs or features. Given a set of training inputs, the algorithm will maps k nearest past similar outputs to new observations, in which these k values are namely nearest neighbors. In this aspect, to find the nearest values, a similarity


        measure is adopted. Some measures can be adopted, such as Euclidean and Manhattan. In this context, the k-nearest neighbors are those that similarity measure between past inputs and new inputs is the smallest. Considering that the set of k-nearest neighbors are defined, the output variable will be computed by average of past similar values such as follows:


        1

        yË =

        k

        xn

        ï£º

        , (2.27)

        where yË is the predicted output, k is the set of k observations similar to the output, xn is the feature or input for training data point which belongs to x.‌


      5. Partial Least Squares

        The Partial Least Squares Regression (PLS) regression approach is a technique to analyze multivariate data, in which the aim is to relate one or two output variables (y) with several inputs (x). For this purpose, given a linear model, the problem that often arises is the matrix of inputs being singular. Faced with this, to deal with this problem, the PLS decomposes x into orthogonal scores T and loadings P, in which x = T Ã P. Regarding this approach, T and P values are chosen in such a way that the covariance between inputs and outputs is maximized. In other words, the PLS finds components that maximize the variation of the predictors while simultaneously requiring these components to have a maximum correlation with the response. In a more general way, the PLS finds linear combinations of the predictors, named components that are like the principal component analysis. Additionally, the PLS in its classical form is based on the nonlinear iterative partial least squares (WOLD et al., 1983; GELADI; KOWALSKI, 1986). Considering the hyperparameters of PLS, only the number of components should be defined.‌‌


      6. Regularized Regression

        When there is an interest in solving a problem using the ordinary least squares approach in a regression field, minimizing the sum of squared errors is necessary to find the parameter estimates. In some cases, this approach fits a model with lower bias and high variance when new observations are considered. Penalty to the sum of the squared errors is an approach that could be applied to deal with the trade-off between the bias-variance paradigm.

        In this respect, it is possible to highlight two approaches, RR (HOERL; KEN- NARD, 1970) and LASSO regressions. The first one adds a penalized term (L2 norm or parameters squared) in the ordinary least squares to control the parameters estimate,


        solve the inputs multicollinearity, and overfitting. The RR minimizes the sum of squared residuals and penalizes the size of the parameter estimates to reduce them to zero. On the other hand, adding a penalized term (L1 norm or absolute value of parameters) in the ordinary least squares improves the accuracy of the models by bias reducing and conducting feature selection.

        The main difference between LASSO and RR approaches is that the first one can remove the non-useful variables and reduce the model variance making it more stable and less sensitive to new observations. Also, according to Zhao and Bondell (2020) the LASSO produces solutions of sparse structures by shrinking some parameters to precisely zero, which makes the model more interpretable than black-box models.

        The RR and LASSO parameters estimates can be computed according to the Eq. (2.28) and Eq. (2.29) as follows,

      7. Support Vector Regression

Initially, support vector machines were proposed to solve classification tasks and then were extended to solve regression problems and name as SVR (CORTES; VAPNIK, 1995). The main idea behind this methodology consists of determining points close to a hyperplane (support vectors) that maximize the margin between two-point classes (points greater and lower than the target variable) obtained from the difference between the target value and a threshold.

Let [xi, yi] be an ordered pair of observations, in which xi â Rd is a set of input variables, and yi â R its respective output variable. The main concept behind the SVR is


to map low-dimensional input data into high-dimensional space based on the non-linear mapping or kernel functions. The forecasting is obtained through the linear regression stated as,

    1. Optimization Approaches

      The MOO approach is employed to optimize two or more objective functions aiming to achieve a preferable solution by dealing with the trade-off between them (MARLER; ARORA, 2004). The MOO is applied according to three steps. First, it is necessary to define the Multi-Objective Problem (MOP); second, and some algorithms are used to optimize the objectives; third, it is essential to choose the most relevant result for the formulated problem, appointed as Multi-Criteria Decision Making (MCDM) (REYNOSO-MEZA et al., 2014).‌


      According to Marler and Arora (2004), in the first step, the MOP is defined, regarding which decision variables, constraints and objectives are stated. The MOP for two J objectives can be expressed as follows:


      min/max

      Î¸Ë


      subject to inequality constraints

      J(Î¸) = [J1(Î¸), J2(Î¸)], (2.35)


      Li â¤ Î¸i â¤ Ui, (2.36)

      in which Î¸ = [Î¸1, . . . , Î¸i], (i = 1, . . . , n) is a vector of decision variables, Li and Ui are the lower and upper boundaries for each decision variable, and Jk(Î¸) is the k-th objective to be minimized or maximized.

      The multi-objective approach is used in time series analysis to develop a model that makes predictions with minor errors, which should vary slightly. Indeed, it is adopted to deal with bias-variance trade-off (NEVILLE; JENSEN, 2008) where the forecast errors and errors variation are minimized simultaneously. In addition, the bias-variance framework can be decomposed as follows:


      E(yË â y)2 = E(yË â E(yË) + E(yË) â y)2

      In this respect, during the MOO step, an optimization algorithm is applied to find the Pareto Front (PF). This set is composed of non-dominated solutions, which are solutions for which there are no other permissible solutions that simultaneously improve


      all objective functions without sacrificing at least one other objective function. In this aspect, each set of decision variables associated with each element of the PF makes up the Pareto Set (PS). Figure 11 illustrates the solutions and the PF, along with the decision variables, for a MOP with two dimensions.‌
