      When the MOO approach is adopted, most of the algorithms proposed in the literature are based on evolutionary computation and are named Multi-Objective Evolu- tionary Algorithms (MOEA). An evolutionary algorithm is based on natureâs laws. It uses mechanisms such as crossover, mutation, and selection. The crossover is an operation used to combine the genetic information of parents to produce a new offspring. The mutation is an operator used to maintain the diversity of the population by introducing another level of randomness. Finally, the selection is an operation applied to select the fittest individuals according to the objectives to be optimized (MIRJALILI, 2019).

      Basically, in a MOEA, the fittest members of a parent in a population will survive and propagate their fitness along with the evolution of its populations of offspring. In the literature, new approaches to deal with MOO are constantly being proposed. Nevertheless, in this thesis, the Non-Dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm â version II (NSGA-II) is adopted (DEB et al., 2002), considering it is a classical MOO approach and has already shown promising results (in terms of accuracy, in general for regression analysis, lower error) to deal with MOP on several fields of knowledge (BORA et al., 2019; RIBEIRO; REYNOSO-MEZA, 2019). The NSGA-II is a derivative-free method that employs a non-sorting ordering operator and crowding distance criteria in the optimization process. The first operation is used to find a set of equally satisfactory solutions closest to the Pareto-optimal front. In contrast, the second is employed to promote diversity among members of the solution population. The main idea behind the crowding distance is finding


      the Euclidean distance between neighboring individuals in the m-dimension space (DEB et al., 2002; NETO et al., 2018).

      Lastly, in the MCDM step, it is possible to find a preferable set of decision variables (weights in this thesis) that allows dealing with the trade-off between the objectives. It means finding the best compromise between the optimized objectives. An approach used for this purpose is Technique for Order of Preference by Similarity to Ideal Solution (TOPSIS), which was proposed by Hwang and Yoon (1981). The TOPSIS was meant to determine the best alternative based on the concepts of the compromised solution. In other words, the chosen solution should be as close to the best solution as possible and as far away from the worst solution as possible, considering a measure of similarity. The Euclidean distance can obtain the distance of best and worst solutions (TZENG; HUANG, 2011; HWANG et al., 1993).

      When the task is associated with optimizing the objective function J1(Î¸) or J2(Î¸), given some design variables and constraints, the problem lies in SOO. Over the last years, several Over the previous years, several approaches have been already proposed aiming to perform for hyperparameters tuning (SAHU et al., 2021) and feature selection (IZIDIO et al., 2021) in the time series forecasting field. In this thesis, for the case study detailed in subsection 4.3, the COA is used to tune the XGBoostâs hyperparameter. The COA is a stochastic population-based algorithm that considers the social relations inside the packs of the Canis latrans species proposed by Pierezan and Coelho (2018). It has already shown promising results in a range of applications achieving satisfactory results, especially to define the hyperparameters of three-diode photovoltaic models (QAIS et al., 2019), heavy-duty gas turbine (PIEREZAN et al., 2019), photovoltaic cells (CHIN; SALAM, 2019), and feature selection (SOUZA et al., 2020).

      In the following are presented the NSGA-II, TOPSIS, and COA approaches.‌


      1. Non-Dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm â version II

        NSGA-II is an alternative to solving multi-objective problems of the genetic algorithm proposed by Deb et al. (2002). This method is featured by several operators such as selection, crossover, mutation, non-dominated sorting approach, and elitist strategy (used to enhance the convergence). Moreover, a crowding distance is used to obtain a uniform spread of solutions over the PF approximation. The main steps are described as follows:


        1. An initial parent population P0 with size N is randomly generated according to the decision variables for a feasible set using a uniform distribution. Each solution is assigned to a population member according to its non-domination


          level. The operator selection, recombination, and mutation are adopted to create an offspring population Q0;

        2. A combined population is obtained through Rt = Pt âª Qt is generated, and has a size of 2N , where t represents the generation. Then, the population Rt is then classified into several non-dominated fronts based on non-dominated sorting. Using the solutions from the last front, the population members are sorted using a crowded comparison;

        3. The N suitable individuals from Rt are selected according to non-dominated sorting and crowding distance to form the new population Pt+1;

        4. A new population Pt+1 of size N is used for selection, crossover, and mutation to create a new offspring population Qt+1. The elitist strategy is applied to maintain the best members from combined populations. During this process, the binary tournament selection operator is employed, whereas the selection criterion is now based on the crowded comparison;

        5. If the stop criterion is satisfied, the PF approximation is obtained, and the process ends.


      2. Technique for Order of Preference by Similarity to Ideal Solution‌

      3. Coyote Optimization Algorithm‌‌

        The COA was proposed by (PIEREZAN; COELHO, 2018) and considers the social relations inside the packs of the Canis latrans species.     2. Time Series Decomposition Methods

      Beyond bagging, boosting, stacking ensemble learning, and a combination of forecasting methods through arithmetic and weighted averages, and median, an alternative approach widely employed in generating ensemble learning models, is the use of time series pre-processing techniques. Through the use of decomposition methods, the original time series is divided into several subseries and one residual, which are named components. Each of them reflects different data characteristics such as high and low frequency, trend, and seasonality. Indeed, the âdecomposition and ensembleâ framework uses the idea of "divide and conquer" to decompose the original data into multiple components, each component is forecasted separately, and finally, integrate the prediction result of each component into the final result (LIU et al., 2021b).

      In this approach, each component is handled by some statistical or ML models. Then, when the raw signal is recomposed, the final model is viewed as an ensemble learning model. Alongside the use of time series decomposition methods, some choices are needed. The first is related to the selection of the forecasting method to handle the subseries. In this respect, when the same learning strategy is used for modeling all subseries, the final forecasting model can be featured as a cooperative homogeneous ensemble model. Otherwise, a cooperative heterogeneous ensemble model is defined if at least one subseries is handled by a different learning strategy from the remaining. Moreover, the aggregation method plays a vital role in the efficiency of the forecasting model. In turn, WI and DI


      can be adopted. The first one refers to assigning weights for the subseries, and the second is only by summing up the subseries. From a broader perspective, choosing the correct strategy to compose an accurate forecasting ensemble learning model is a challenging task.

      The following subsections detail the decomposition approaches employed in the case studies presented in chapter 4.‌


      1. Seasonal and Trend decomposition using Loess

        The STL was proposed to split the time series into three components, named seasonal, trend, and residual (SAVITZKY; GOLAY, 1964; CLEVELAND, 1979; CLEVE- LAND et al., 1990). Given a time series, the STL is a filtering approach employed to obtain three types of components named seasonality (describes regular patterns), trend (describes the increasing or decreasing in a time-space), and the remainder (component not described by seasonality and trend). The STL is robust to deal with outliers and missing values.

        Let Y (t) be a time series the STL approach decomposes the series into three components, which in an additive way, are giving by


        Y (t) = S(t) + T (t) + R(t), (2.56)

        where S(t) is the seasonal component, T (t) is the trend, and R(t) is the remainder or residual component at time t = 1, . . . , n.

        The STL operates iterative, with inner and outer loops. In the inner loop, S(t) and T (t) are computed, while in the outer loop R(t) is determined. The inner loop is split into six steps: (i) trend are removed of observed time series; (ii) through loess, the time series obtained in the first step are smoothed, and seasonal components are obtained;

        1. to find the remainder trend, the seasonal time series provided in the second step are processed by low-pass filtering; (iv) through the difference between the low-pass values from the third step and seasonal series of the second step, the harmful of the seasonal smoothed component are performed; (v) deseasonalized series are obtained calculating the difference between the original and provided in the fourth step; and (vi) the original data is smoothed by loess to obtain the trend component. Finally, in the outer loop, removing of original series the smoothed trend, as well as the smoothed seasonality, the remainder (residual) component, is computed.‌


      2. Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition

        The EEMD technique was proposed by Wu and Huang (2009). It is an extension of the Empirical Mode Decomposition (EMD) algorithm and should be used with the purpose of data de-noising. The EMD approach allows the analyzing of nonlinear and non-stationary signals. The steps followed in this technique are data decomposition, and later data aggregation. First, in the decomposition stage, the EMD separates the original signal into coexisting oscillatory components, named Intrinsic Mode Functions (IMF) and residue (HUANG et al., 1998). Next, after the modeling of each component, it is necessary to perform the aggregation of results to obtain the original signal.‌

        When the EMD is used, the main drawback is named "mode mixing", that is, each single IMF consists of signals with dramatically disparate scales or a signal of the same scale appears in different IMF components (WU; HUANG, 2009). Seeking to solve this problem, the noise assisted EEMD was proposed. In this approach, EMD is performed k times, and different white noise (a random signal that follows a normal distribution with zero mean and constant variance) is added to the data in each trial. Two disadvantages can be stated for EEMD, as follows: (i) extra noise exists in the reconstructed signal and

        1. it needs more computational resources than EMD (QIAN et al., 2019).

          Initially, the EMD approach is presented and generalized for EEMD. In fact, the main steps are stated as follows,


          1. Input the original time series;

          2. Add white noise on the original series;

          3. Obtain the local maximum and minimum values of series of step 2;

          4. Generate envelops for the new series, taking into account its boundaries;

          5. Calculate the average of the boundaries of step 4;

          6. Extract from the generated data the average value obtained in step 5;

          7. After performing each step 2-6, each component is named IMF (WANG et al., 2016) if it has the following characteristics: (i) in the entire dataset, the number of extreme and zero crossings must either be equal or different, at most, by one, and (ii) at any point, the mean value of the envelopes is defined by the local maximal and the local minimal which must be zero;

          8. Defining that the component of the step 7 is an IMF, the residual component is computed as the difference between the IMF and the remaining data. The steps 2-7 are performed until that residual component becomes a monotonic function or has one local extreme point from which no more IMF can be extracted.


        The EEMD performed the steps 2-8 k times and for each trial there are n components (IMF(1,k), . . . , IMF(n,k), Residue(n+1,k)). Therefore, each final component is treated as the average of the respective components of the k executions and the number of repeated times of the procedure is executed is called the ensemble number.

        After the end of the decomposition process, the original time series can be expressed as the sum of IMF and residue components. In this stage, DI or WI strategies should be used. The DI consists of assuming the same weight for each component, while WI considers different weights for each component. When a decomposition technique is adopted, there are two possibilities for data analysis, as follows:


        1. Datasets are decomposed and components are aggregated and used as input in some forecasting method, such as developed by Jiang and Liu (2019);

        2. Each component obtained during the decomposition stage is used as an input by some forecast method, and the forecasting of each component is used in the aggregation stage such as developed by Wang et al. (2015), Wu et al. (2020).


      3. Variational Mode Decomposition‌

        The VMD is a well-established tool usually adopted for time series pre-processing to extract data features, as well as to remove signal noise. VMD is a generalization of the classic Wiener filter into multiple adaptive bands, and it is a non-recursive decomposition method developed to remove nonlinear trends and harmonics patterns from complex time series (DRAGOMIRETSKIY; ZOSSO, 2014). Compared with EMD-based approaches, the VMD has two main advantages, it requires less computational power to obtain the components (time and memory), and it is not affected by the mode mixing problem. Also, regarding Wavelet Transform (WT) the approach VMD pre-processing all data, while in iterative WT, only high frequencies are pre-processed.

        According to Dragomiretskiy and Zosso (2014), through VMD pre-processing the raw series is decomposed into a finite and predefined number k of IMF, or simply mode functions uk(t) (or components) described by,


        uk(t) = Ak(t) cos (Ïk(t)) , (2.57) in which Ïk(t) is a non-decreasing function, Ï k (t) â¥ 0, the envelope is a non-negative

        Ak(t) and the instantaneous frequency Ïk(t) = Ïk (t) vary slower than the phase Ïk(t). The obtained modes are designed to represent different data (low and high) frequencies. The modes, when aggregated represent the original signal, have limited bandwidth. In this respect, each mode is more compact around in the center (Ïk), defined throughout the decomposition process. The main steps to determine the modeâs bandwidth are:


        1. Given each mode uk, the Hilbert transform (HAHN, 1996) is computed with the purpose to obtain a unilateral frequency spectrum of the signal;

        2. Through mixing the estimated center frequency, the spectrum of each mode is modulated to the corresponding baseband;

    3. Performance Measures‌

      After adjusting the various models for each response variable, a model that best explains the variability of the data must be chosen, and, consequently, in the case of time series prediction, this is the one that has a greater accuracy in the generalization of the results. Faced with this aspect, different performance measures have been used to assess the models performance, in which the most frequent being MAE, MSE, MAPE, RMSE, RRMSE, sMAPE, Theilâs U index type 2 (U2). In this aspect, for the evaluation of the models adopted in this thesis, such performance measures will be used, and are computed as follows:

      The Overall Weight Average (OWA) given by Eq. (2.66) and IP given by Eq. (2.67) are two additional criteria employed to compare the accuracy of the forecasting models. The OWA is used to connect the average of two different performance criteria. It allows perform an analysis from a broader aspect and would help to achieve a higher level of objectivity (MAKRIDAKIS et al., 2020a). On the other hand, the IP can be beneficial to observe the degree of improvement in the accuracy from between two models.‌‌


    4. Hypothesis Tests

Besides punctual performance measures employed to evaluate the performance of the algorithms, statistical tests can be employed. In this aspect, non-parametric tests have


been frequently applied by the academic community to test hypotheses to evaluate the performance of different proposed approaches.

The DM test (DIEBOLD; MARIANO, 1995) is usually employed to compare the errors of forecasting models. The lower tail priori hypothesis H is given by Eq. (2.68),

Chapter 3‌‌


Related Works



This chapter presents the related works for each case study detailed in chapter 4.

Concerning the areas of the application adopted in this thesis, are choose strategic sectors of society that have a high impact on lives of citizens. The first area is agribusiness. The Brazilian commodities such as soybean, wheat, meat, sugar, and coffee, for example, are essential for the economy worldwide since they are exported to several countries. As a result that, the agribusiness trade balance ended July 2021 with a trade surplus of US$ 10.1 billion (IPEA, 2021). Alongside this, even though the problems owing to the COVID-19 pandemic, the gross value of production taken as an annual billing indicator is R$ 1.076 trillion, 12.1% higher in real currency than in 2020 (BRASIL, 2021).

For the epidemiology context, early diagnosis and the immediate initiation of the treatment are fundamental for a good prognosis of the disease and the development of strategic planning to mitigate the effects of the outbreaks. The most recent example of this is related to the COVID-19 outbreak. In that situation, due to the impact on the economy and society day-to-day, the governments and population are most concerned with (i) how long the outbreak will last, and (iii) how many people will eventually be infected (ZHANG et al., 2020). Therefore, the development of efficient predictive models plays a vital role in epidemiological modeling. Since they can support the proposition that efficient public policies and preventive campaigns are the keys to changing the epidemic scenario.

Electric energy demand forecasting is an essential object of study since it allows the management of the energetic resource. Through forecasts, companies can develop energetic planning able to meet electric power distribution and generation requirements (QIU et al., 2017). Also, it allows establishing strategic scheduling to leverage earnings and reduce the losses of the companies. Alongside this, developing proper grid construction planning will improve the economic and social benefits of the systems. The load forecasts make it possible to design future energy consumption scenarios and solve conflicts involving supply and demand, environment, and economic development.

Finally, the development and expansion of clean energy or renewable energies,


such as wind energy, are essential in preserving the environment and developing local economies and an alternative to hydroelectric and thermal energies. According to the report of "INFOVENTO" (Brazilian Wind Energy Association - ABEEÃ³lica, 2021), the size of the wind industry of Brazil in terms of installed capacity is 19.1 gigawatts produced by 726 wind farms in 12 states. In the Brazilian electric matrix, wind energy represents 10.8% of the energy production. Due to the high installed capacity wind energy, 57 terawatt-hours of wind energy were generated in 2020, benefiting 86.4 million Brazilians. Economically, 35.8 billion dollars have already been invested in this area between 2011 and 2020. For every megawatt-hour of generation, 15 citizens are employed. Environmentally, 21.2 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) were avoided in 2020. In this respect, the development of efficient forecasting models to support the decision-making process in the energetic planning is needed.‌‌


    1. Case Study 1: Agricultural Commodities Prices Time Series

      Commodities comprise an essential chain of products that directly influence the global economy. These products are grouped into categories as follows: energy, metal, livestock, and agriculture. For commodity prediction in the precious metals sector, He et al. (2012) used linear ensembles, based on multiple-resolution analysis for value-at-risk to estimate copper, gold, and silver prices in the United States of America. The results obtained are compared with ARIMA generalized autoregressive conditional heteroskedas- ticity models. The authors argue that the predictions generated are more significant and accurate than those obtained with traditional methods that consider individual predictions. Gabralla et al. (2015) proposed an ensemble to forecast energy commodity. Three types of ANNs were combined by weighted average to forecast the West Texas Intermediate oil prices. The authors showed that the neural network ensemble achieved better accuracy in terms of MAE than the ensemble members.

      Pierdzioch et al. (2015) applied the L2-boosting algorithm to forecast silver and gold price returns. The errors and biases of the predictions were significantly reduced. Alongside that, Pierdzioch et al. (2016) evaluated a boosting approach with different loss functions to forecast gold volatility. When the results were compared with an Autoregressive (AR) model, the boosting approach showed better results in terms of accuracy. Yu et al. (2016) proposed a decomposition-and-ensemble learning approach combined with ELM to forecast energy commodity, in that case, the crude oil prices. The forecasting errors in terms of MAPE spans from 1% to 6% in the horizon of 1 up to 6-months-ahead. Proposed models showed better results regarding individual ELM, Least Squares Support Vector Machines (LSSVM), ANNs, ARIMA, as well as when associated to decomposition‌


      paradigm. Yu et al. (2017) developed an ensemble of LSSVM with results aggregated by weighted average to forecast crude oil price. The proposed model showed better results when compared to traditional prediction methodologies and individual LSSVM. In terms of MAPE, the proposed model achieved errors between 1.59% and 3.55%.

      Zhao et al. (2017) proposed an ensemble of bagging and Deep Learning (DL) to forecast oil gross price per barrel. The proposed approach was tested against some competing methodologies such as random walk, Markov Regime switching, Feedforward Neural Network (FNN), SVR, and DL. The results showed superior forecasting capability of the proposed model than compared models by achieving accuracy in terms of MAPE of 5.3%. Wang et al. (2017) hybridized the Multilayer Perceptron Neural Network with Backpropagation error (BPNN) by Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) with four de- composition approaches such as EMD, wavelet packet transformed, intrinsic time-scale decomposition, and VMD to forecast wheat, corn, and soybean prices. The approach that combined VMD, PSO and BPNN showed better results than other combinations of proposed approaches. In terms of MAPE, proposed model achieved MAPE 1.72%. Xiong et al. (2017) proposed an cooperative ensemble by combining EEMD, ARIMA, and AI tools such as FNN, SVR, and ELM to short-term forecast of hog prices in China. Regarding the sMAPE criterion, the proposed models achieved forecasting errors that span 6% to 8%. Results showed that the enhanced EEMD-ARIMA-ELM-SVR outperforms the selected counterparts.‌‌‌

      Yang et al. (2017) proposed a Bagging Heterogeneous Autoregressive (BHAR) model to forecast the volatility of agricultural commodities futures contracts such as soy, cotton, wheat, and corn in China. The proposed model and principal components analysis predictions produce the lowest metrics is relatively longer forecast horizons (1, 5, and 10-days-ahead). Pierdzioch and Risse (2018) evaluated a multivariate RF to forecast 1- week-ahead future returns of gold, silver, platinum, and palladium. The proposed approach outperforms univariate models. Tang et al. (2018) hybridized EEMD with predictions generated by Random Vector Functional Link Network (RVFL) to forecast crude oil prices. Results from proposed approach outperform EEMD-ELM and other single models such as ARIMA, RF, ELM, and LSSVM.‌

      Bonato et al. (2018) developed a quantile boosting approach to forecast future returns for gold 1, 5, and 10-days-ahead. In terms of Directional Accuracy (DA), results obtained from the proposed model are better than results from AR models. Ding (2018) proposed an EEMD process associated with ANNs to forecast the West Texas Intermediate crude oil price series. The results suggested that the EEMD-ANNs method presents better predictions than other EMD-ANNs in terms of MAPE, RMSE, and DA. Wang et al. (2019a) proposed an ensemble learning model composed of three denoising methods and five forecasting models to forecast soybean and corn futures prices. The pre-processing methods


      adopted are Singular Spectral Analysis (SSA), EMD, and VMD. Also the forecasting models used are ARIMA, SVR, Recurrent Neural Network (RNN), Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU), and LSTM. The Artificial Bee Colony Algorithm (ABC) was employed to tune the ensemble weights. As a result, semi-heterogeneous forecast combinations have error reductions of 53.3% and 50.0% of MAPE and improvements of 32.4% and 34.5% in DA compared to the best single models.‌‌‌‌

      Herrera et al. (2019) evaluated an ensemble of statistical methods, RF approach, and ANNs. The proposed ensemble is composed by ARIMA, Exponential Smoothing (ETS), Seasonal Components based on a Fourier Transform, BC transform, ARMA errors, Trend, and Seasonal Component (TBATS), STL, and theta model. The ensemble was generated through weighted aggregation. These models were adopted to forecast energy commodities. Concerning the MAPE and RMSE criteria, The results show that ML methods outperform traditional econometric methods and also that they present an additional advantage, which is the capacity to predict turning points. Alongside that, the RF model achieved better results than compared models, where the MAPE spans 8%-10%.‌

      Liu et al. (2021b) proposed a cooperative ensemble to forecast West Texas Inter- mediate crude oil prices, London Metal Exchange zinc prices, the New York Mercantile Exchange natural gas prices, and the Commodities Exchange gold prices. The proposed methodology consisted of decomposing the adopted time series through VMD and han- dling the components using ANNs. The authors showed that in comparison with other pre-processing techniques and single models, the proposed approach is more accurate and achieved forecasting errors lower than 1% regarding MAPE in 1, 3, and 6-days-ahead. Deepa et al. (2021) evaluated boosting DT and RF methods to forecast cotton monthly prices of India. Compared with boosting in terms of accuracy, the Bayesian and linear regression also perform well. Xu and Zhang (2021) proposed to forecast corn cash price across sixteen states of the United States using ANNs. The authors argued that including futures prices in the data modeling benefits corn cash price forecasting. Alongside that, related works published between 2005â2012 are presented by Xiong et al. (2013) concerning forecasting models in terms of energy commodities.

      Concerning the related works described, it is possible to identify that different approaches, based on regression ensembles, have been used to predict commodities prices, return, and volatility and have achieved better accuracy in percentage errors against single models. However, it is also possible to verify that, for the most part, these studies do not use bagging, boosting, and stacking, especially in approaches with a focus on short-term forecasting for agricultural commodities are combined with a set of diversified features related to price drivers.

    2. Case Study 2: Meningitis Cases Time Series

      Ch et al. (2014) used SVR-Firefly Algorithm (FFA) to forecast malaria incidences in India. The rainfall, relative humidity, and temperature were used as exogenous features. Compared with ANNs, and Autoregressive Moving Average (ARMA) methods, the pro- posed approach outperforms compared models by achieving an Normalized Mean Squared Error (NMSE) of 0.21. Guo et al. (2017) compared SVR, GBM, LASSO, and Generalized Additive Model (GAM) for dengue forecasting in China. Climate factors were used as exogenous features. The SVR model had the consistently lowest prediction error rates in terms of RMSE and can capt the data variability by achieving a better coefficient of determination than compared models for tracking the dynamics of dengue and forecasting the outbreaks.‌‌‌

      Scavuzzo et al. (2018) used SVR, ANNs, KNN, and DT for temporal modeling of the oviposition activity (measured weekly on 50 ovitraps in a north Argentinean city) of Aedes aegypti (Linnaeus). Features related to remote sensing were used as exogenous factors to give additional information for the forecasting models. The considered ML models perform better than linear approaches, in particular, KNN performs better than compared approaches. Chen et al. (2018) proposed to use LASSO for providing sound forecasts for different pathogens in countries with different climates. Climatic variables and monthly effects were considered as exogenous features. Despite the LASSO being a linear regression, satisfactory performance in terms of MAPE was achieved in the task of forecasting a nonlinear epidemiological time series. From a broader perspective, short-term predictions generally perform better than longer-term predictions, suggesting public health agencies may need the capacity to respond at short notice to early warnings.

      Chekol and Hagras (2018) compared Adaptive Neuro-Fuzzy Inference System (ANFIS) and SVR approaches on the task of predicting the malaria epidemic, in Ethiopia, up to three-months-ahead. The SVR model RMSE for training and testing data were

      0.04 and 0.12 respectively whereas for ANFIS RMSE was 0.049 and 0.133 respectively. These results revealed that the performance of the SVR model was slightly better than the ANFIS model to predict the malaria epidemic. Poirier et al. (2018) compared internet and electronic health records data through statistical models combined with RF, SVR, and Elasticnet (ENET) to identify the best approach for influenza estimates in real-time. The study was conducted in France. The best forecasting accuracy based on MSE was obtained using SVR and ENET.

      Liang et al. (2018) explored the application of the SVR-based ensemble learning model for forecasting influenza data in Liaoning, China. Also, internet search queries and traditional surveillance data were considered in the modeling. It was observed the feasibility of using engine query data and the efficiency of the SVR model in tracking influenza.


      Mollalo et al. (2019) investigated the applicability of MLP to predict the tuberculosis incidence. Among the developed models, single hidden layer MLP had the best test accuracy. Sensitivity analysis of the MLP model showed that immigrant population (proportion), underserved segments of the population, and minimum temperature were among the factors with the most substantial contributions.

      Soliman et al. (2019) investigated the utility of DL to forecast influenza in Dallas County compared with LASSO, Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines (MARS), and ARIMA. Meteorological data were used as exogenous features. The DL and the multi- model ensemble of forecasts yield similar and competitive performance. The Bayesian model averaging provided better forecasting results by achieving a MAPE of 2.78% and 3.17% in the horizons of one and two-weeks-ahead. Chen et al. (2019) developed a non- parametric model based on LASSO-GP regression for influenza prediction considering meteorological effect. Meteorological variables were used as exogenous features. Proposed approach outperforms Linear Regression (LR), ANNs, SVR, and SARIMA. From a broader perspective, the model with meteorology was capable of capturing the fluctuations of the influenza series and obtained a predictive performance of 7.63% in terms of MAPE (275.79 in terms of RMSE) for 1-week-ahead.‌

      Guo et al. (2019) used an ensemble learning model to forecast weekly dengue incidence and detect outbreak occurrence defined using different cutoffs during the periods of 2011â2016 in Guangzhou, South of China. The proposed ensemble model provided near-real-time estimates of dengue incidence and captured the fluctuations of dengue dynamics. Shirmohammadi et al. (2019) investigated and compared the performance of RF, SVR, and MARS to forecast monthly brucellosis. Meteorological variables were used as exogenous features. In terms of RMSE and MAE, results indicated that the RF model outperformed the SVR and MARS and it can be utilized to diagnose the behavior of brucellosis over time. Venna et al. (2019) proposed a novel data-driven ML method using LSTM-based multi-stage for influenza forecasting. The proposed method performs better than the existing well-known influenza forecasting methods ARIMA and Ensembled adjustment Kalman filter (EAKF) and the results offer a promising direction to improve influenza forecasting.

      Thakur and Dharavath (2019) determined the malaria abundances using clinical and environmental variables with big data by ANNs. The results vary from area to area based on clinical variables and rainfall in the prediction model corresponding to areas. The authors observed that climatic conditions and clinical treatment play a significant role in malaria. Chakraborty et al. (2019) proposed a hybrid ARIMA-Neural Network Autoregressive (NNAR) for dengue forecasting on three regions. The ARIMA-NNAR give better forecasting accuracy in comparison with LSTM and SVR models. As a result, the authors argued that the cooperative ensemble ARIMA-NNAR model explains the linear


      and nonlinear autocorrelation structures present in the data better than the traditional component and other hybrid models and yields better forecast accuracy than them.

      Su et al. (2019) Developed a self-adaptive model by integrating the SARIMA, and XGBoost approaches for real-time estimation of influenza in Chongqing, China. Compared with LASSO and LSTM approaches, the proposed framework reaches better forecasting accuracy. Mussumeci and Coelho (2020) evaluated the predictive performance of LSTM, RF, and LASSO model to forecast weekly dengue incidence (four-weeks-ahead) in 790 cities in Brazil using multivariate predictors. The authors argued that LSTM could achieve better performance, in terms of mean prediction errors in quantile scale, than RF and LASSO models. Kara (2021) proposed a hybridization of Genetic Algorithm (GA) and LSTM for influenza forecasting in United States. The experimental results suggest that the proposed hybrid framework achieved higher accuracy than ARIMA, RF, and SVR models in terms of MAE and RMSE. Moreover, a detailed review of the research and application of AI tools with forecasting purpose was presented by Hoyos et al. (2021) in the context of dengue, and for COVID-19 by Khan et al. (2021), Shastry and Sanjay (2022).

      Adjacent to those mentioned earlier, some gaps about the developed approaches can be found. Firstly, considering the diseaseâs type, most papers focused on malaria, dengue, or influenza. Hence, there is a lack of discussion concerning the predictive capacity of ML-based approaches for diseases such as measles, meningitis, and chikungunya on the forecast task. Second, only four papers focused on ensemble approaches such as bagging and boosting or models combined by average in the modeling aspect. One paper used an optimization approach of the swarm intelligence field called FFA for hyperparameters selection, and no paper adopted signal decomposition or MOO with the purpose of building ensembles. It is well known that the combination of these strategies can help in the improvement of the modelâs accuracy and, therefore, out-of-sample generalization. Finally, in general, to the forecast horizon, most of the papers focused on a single horizon, that is, one week or one-month-ahead. The discussions are narrow for the multi-step-ahead forecast. Indeed, the use of other horizons could be vital because they can be helpful for managers to develop strategic plains to prevent the population from having these diseases and develop strategies and public policies so that these diseases will affect as few people as possible.

      Therefore, faced with the aspects as mentioned earlier, case study 2 seeks to fill the pointed-out gaps by proposing a hybrid framework to forecast the number of meningitis cases, which considers EEMD, heterogeneous ensemble, and MOO approaches to reconstruct the decomposed signal.     3. Case Study 3: Electricity Energy Load Demand Time Series

      For datasets from AEMO, Qiu et al. (2017) developed an ensemble decomposition by combining EMD with components handled by Deep Belief Network (DBN). Results revealed promising forecasting performance in comparison with other state-of-the-art methods such as SVR, DBN, and persistence, for example. The proposed method achieved MAPE lower than 2% and 11% for half-an-hour and one-day-ahead forecasting, respectively. From a broader perspective, the EMD based hybrid methods normally outperform the corresponding single models for load demand forecasting. Qiu et al. (2018) proposed a dual decomposition by combining WT and EMD and components handled by RVFL. Datasets from AEMO were adopted to test the performance of the proposed method. Results revealed promising forecasting performance compared to other state-of-the-art methods, therefore proving the effectiveness of the assembled methodology.

      Zhang and Wang (2018a) proposed an ensemble learning model with weights tuned by Cuckoo Search Algorithm (CSA) to forecast load demand data from AEMO and Singapore. Firstly, the load demand data was decomposed through SSA, and then the components were handled by ARIMA and SVR. The weighted integrated and decomposed model outperformed directly integrated and single models such as SVR, BPNN, CSAâSVR, GAâBPNN, and FFAâSVR. Mohan et al. (2018) used Dynamic Mode Decomposition (DMD) for STLF one-day-ahead in Australia and America markets. The ability of the DMD algorithm to deal with the latent Spatio-temporal dynamics of the time-evolving load data was verified, and the generalization is achieved for load prediction of different seasons. Proposed approach achieved MAPE lower than 10% and outperformed some state- of-art methods such as AR, SVR, and ANNs for example. Yang et al. (2019) developed an approach that combines LSSVM, and feature selection based on Autocorrelation Function (ACF). Also, a Grey Wolf Optimization (GWO) was used to tune the LSSVM hyperparameters. This approach has high time-consuming to perform inputs selection. Still, it can increase the forecasting accuracy regarding some benchmarks by achieving MAPE lower than 1% for STLF half-an-hour-ahead considering datasets from AEMO.‌‌‌

      Wu et al. (2019) proposed the hybridization of Fast Empirical Mode Decomposition (FEMD), Generalized Regression Neural Network (GRNN), and Multi-Objective Cuckoo Search Algorithm (MOCSA) for STLF of AEMO. Experiments showed that the hybrid FEMDâGRNNâMOCSA model could obtain more accurate and stable forecasting results than single and non-optimized models such as BPNN, GAâBPNN, ELM, and GRNN, for example. The proposed method reached a MAPE lower than 1% for STLF half-an- hour-ahead considering datasets from AEMO. Wang et al. (2019b) proposed the hybrid local mean decomposition, Gravitational Search Algorithm (GSA), and Wavelet Neural‌‌‌‌


      Network (WNN) for STLF in AEMO. The proposed hybrid model can better approximate the actual value, and it can also be employed as a valuable tool for intelligent grid dispatching planning. The proposed approach achieved an average MAPE by 0.97% for the evaluated datasets. Talaat et al. (2020) developed a combined model composed by MLP with hyperparameters optimized through Grasshopper Optimization Algorithm (GOA) for STLF in Egypt. The proposed GOAâMLP proved to be more reliable and effective than MLP coupled with other optimizers. A regressive model was introduced to determine the relations between the dependent variable (the load) and the independent variables that affect the load, such as the temperature. The AR model used in the study highlights the effect of the temperature on the hourly load. The accuracy of the hybrid model in terms of deviation error spans -0.06â0.06.‌

      Ribeiro et al. (2019) proposed a wavenets ensemble for STLF considering datasets from Italy and Global Energy Forecasting Competition. The proposed approach outper- formed the MLP with sigmoid activation function in the hidden layer, single wavenets, and a regression tree. Khwaja et al. (2020) proposed performing load forecasting using bagged-boosted ANNs for New England Pool region. The proposed technique enables the reduction of both bias and variance compared to a single ANNs, bagging ANNs, and boosted ANNs. Alongside that, the proposed ensemble model reached a forecasting error of 1.43% in terms of MAPE. Ding et al. (2020) proposed a cooperative ensemble learning model by integrating WT and Relevance Vector Machine (RVM) for STLF. The ensemble WTâRVM is computationally efficient due to its sparsity property and outperformed several models such as SVR, ARIMA, and others for day-ahead in terms of MAE and MAPE. Tayab et al. (2020) proposed the hybridization of wavelet packet transform, Harris Hawks Optimization (HHO) and FNN for STLF, considering data from Australia. Meteo- rological variables were used as exogenous features. The proposed approach reduced the average MAE error by 33.30%, 49.54% and 60.76% as compared to the PSO based ANNs, PSOâLSSVM, and BPNN, respectively.‌

      Fan et al. (2020) proposed an ensemble learning model by coupling EMD with components analysed by DBN and Multi-Objective Deep Belief Network (MODBN) for STLF in AEMO. The experimental results showed that EMDâMODBN achieved better generalization and stability performance than single models such as ELM, RF, and SVR. The proposed approach reached a MAPE lower than 8% for STLF 24-hours-ahead. The authors argued that satisfactory results were achieved due to the enhancement of accuracy and stability simultaneously by using MOO. Li et al. (2020a) developed a comprehensive treatment for the data of electricity demand through an ensemble learning method. For STLF in AEMO, the load demand was decomposed through adaptive Fourier Transform (FT), components analyzed through SVR with structure tuned by Sine Cosine Optimization Algorithm (SCOA). Results showed that hybridizing FTâSVRâSCOA enhance the accuracy of the models and outperform NaÃ¯ve, ARMA, SVR, BPNN, and‌‌


      ELM methods in terms of Standard Deviation (Std), sMAPE, and Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE).‌‌

      Neeraj et al. (2021) used five datasets from AEMO to evaluate the proposed method composed by SSA and LSTM for STLF. The proposed approach achieved better results with evaluations for two forecasting windows than some previously published results regarding adopted datasets. The errors based on MAPE spans 0.39%â1.25% and 2.51%â10.17% for STLF half-an-hour and one-day-ahead. Through the SSA pre-process combined with recurrent neural networks, the accuracy is enhanced. Nie et al. (2020) Proposed a three-stage model. First combined CEEMD and SSA. Next individual ANNs named Radial Basis Function (RBF), ELM, and GRNN. Finally, a Multi-Objective Grey Wolf Optimization (MOGWO) is adopted to combine the individual forecasts. Proposed ensemble framework can lead to accurate forecasting results compared with some individual models such as ARIMA, LSTM, and SVR. Also the dual CEEMDâSSA can reach better stability than EMD, EEMD, CEEMD, SSA, and wavelets when the forecasting horizon of half-an-hour and one-hour-ahead are considered. Dong et al. (2021) proposed an ensemble learning model composed by KNNâDBN, and NSGA-II methods. According to the authors, the NSGA-II-KNN-DBN can generate excellent forecasting results with high stability in multi-step-ahead and at different confidence intervals compared with SVR, ARIMA, and other ANNs architectures for half-an-hour and one-hour-ahead. Based on the efficiency of ensemble models, Hu et al. (2021) combined multimodal evolutionary algorithm and RVFL for STLF considering datasets from Australia, Great Britain, and Norway. The proposed forecasting model improves accuracy and power system management level regarding bagging ensemble and some versions of RVFL models in terms of accuracy.‌

      In consideration of the related papers, are highlighted some research gaps for STLF. First, in the analyzed approaches, the original data is decomposed with components trained individually, and later the results are superimposed. Also, the major drawback of the related methods is attributed to using the same model to handle all obtained components. Using different models to deal with particular features of the data can improve forecasting accuracy. Indeed, the potential of dual (secondary) should be evaluated or ensemble of decomposition methods for STLF. Second, generally, load data has seasonal behavior, then to deal with this characteristic, most of the papers used calendar effects, similar load days, climatological variables as exogenous inputs. However, the use of these features is problematic, increasing the complexity of the models and making it challenging to develop multi-step-ahead forecasting (GONZALEZ-ROMERA et al., 2006). Therefore, the use of pre-processing approaches to deal with load seasonality should be explored, such as STL can be adopted to overcome the related drawbacks.

    4. Case Study 4: Wind Power Generation Time Series‌‌

Wang et al. (2019) developed an ensemble model induced by the use of WT combined with Echo State Neural Networks (ESN) for wind power forecasting into four forecasting horizons, considering real data from a Belgian wind farm. In terms of the MAPE, the model achieved errors spanning 1.2% to 2.1%. The proposed ensemble learning model achieved better forecasting results than the SVR and a BPNN in terms of accuracy, as computed using MAE, RMSE, and MAPE. The authors indicated that the method has a high potential for practical applications in real electric power and energy systems, such as preventive maintenance. Cevik et al. (2019) adopted EMD and WT combined with an ANFIS, ANNs, and SVR for wind power forecasting when considering a single forecasting horizon, adopting real data from the Sotavento Galicia wind farm, Spain. An ensemble learning model obtained through the weight average strategy of the cited methods was defined and achieved better results than the combination of two pre-processing strategies with these three forecasting models in terms of the MAE and RMSE. The forecasting errors in terms of the MAE reported by the authors spans 0.27â0.33

Du et al. (2019a) proposed a framework composed of a Complementary Ensem- ble Empirical Mode Decomposition with Adaptive Noise (CEEMDAN) and WNN with weights defined by Multi-Objective Month-Flame Optimization (MOMFO), applying it to a dataset collected from the Sotavento Galicia wind farm, Spain. The proposed ensemble outperformed the ARIMA model and other hybrid forecasting models. The experimental results show that the proposed hybrid model has errors of 5.02% (1-step-ahead), 7.79% (2-steps-ahead), and 10.70% (3-steps-ahead) in terms of the MAPE. Naik et al. (2019) proposed the use of VMD and Robust Kernel Ridge Regression (RKRR) coupled with a Multi-Objective Chaotic Water Cycle Algorithm (MOCWCA) for interval wind power forecasting. The Coverage Prediction (CP) (%), Prediction Interval Normalized Average Width (PINAW) (%), Average Coverage Error (ACE) (%), and Coverage Width-based Criterion (CWC) (%) were computed. The results showed that the proposed multi-objective predictive method is superior when applied to the task of obtaining quality forecasting in- tervals in comparison to other single and multi-objective models. In addition, Tahmasebifar et al. (2020) proposed a bagging ensemble model coupled with a WT and ELM. Datasets from a capital wind farm located in the New South Wales and Cathedral Rocks wind farm located in South Australia, Australia, were adopted. Points and probabilistic interval forecasting were applied. The 1-h-ahead forecasting achieved MAE values of 0.50â2.21 and RMSE values of 0.64â2.91.‌‌‌‌‌‌‌

Liu and Duan (2020) proposed a multi-objective ensemble learning model that uses WT, an Outlier-Robust Extreme Learning Machine (ORELM), ARMA, and Multi- Objective Grasshopper Optimizatoin Algorithm (MOGOA) for point and interval wind‌


forecasting. The performance in terms of Index of Agreement (IA) lies within the interval of 0.9292â0.9942, and in terms of CWC (%) between 47.53 and 89.45. Considering the results of the ensemble learning model, the authors argued that the proposed model is efficient and can deal with different types of data features by considering the WT, weighted ensemble of ANNs, and ARIMA model for error correction. However, complexity is a major drawback of the proposed framework. Concerning a dataset from a wind farm in Turkey, Yildiz et al. (2021) proposed a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) ensemble learning model by considering the VMD as a pre-processing technique. In this study, the original dataset was converted into an image and 70,080 samples were produced. In terms of the sMAPE for the three forecasting windows, the errors spans the interval of 0.2532â0.2915. The major drawback of this approach is related to the use of high-dimensional data, which increases the training time, and there are millions of hyperparameters to be tuned.‌‌

Through the use of WT, a clustering analysis, and an optimized Kernel Least- Squares Support Vector Machine (KLSSVM), Ding et al. (2021) obtained an ensemble learning model to conduct wind power forecasting 5, 10, and 15-steps-ahead. Compared with the EMD-LSSVM and WT-LSSVM models, using a direct-recursive method as a forecasting strategy, the proposed method achieves better forecasting results in terms of the RMSE and MAE. As a disadvantage of this method, for medium-and long-term forecasts, additional information is needed. In addition, Silva et al. (2021) proposed an ensemble learning model by combining CEEMD, feature engineering, and stacking ensemble learning for wind power forecasting within the a very short term. Three real datasets from Parazinho, Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil, were used. The proposed framework outperforms pre-processed ensemble learning and single models with performance improvements in forecasting errors ranging from 0.06% to 97.53%. This forecasting method achieved a better performance than models without time-series pre-processing, single models, and individual stacking ensemble learning models.

Motivated by the advances in ensemble methods, He and Wang (2021) proposed a framework that uses EEMD, LASSO, and a Quantile Regression Neural Network (QRNN) for wind power forecasting with two datasets from Sotavento Wind Farm, Spain. Moreover, four additional datasets from the electrician mathematical contest modeling were used. Point and interval forecasting were also applied. In terms of the MAPE, the forecasting errors ranged from 1.60% to 14.71%. With respect to the interval forecasting, the PINAW (%) ranged between 16.93% and 45.45%. The drawback of the proposed method is related to the use of pre-processing methods, which can burden the system. However, compared to LASSO, QRNN, and the combination of these two approaches with EEMD, in most cases, the proposed method achieves better forecasting results in terms of the MAE, RMSE, and MAPE.

Applying a statistical approach, ARIMA, and a FNN, Dumitru and Gligor (2019)


used data from the Romanian National Power System Operator for wind power forecasting. Considering the RRMSE, ARIMA outperformed the FNN for the one-step-ahead horizon. As a weakness of this approach, the authors do not consider other forecasting windows. Through the integration of LASSO and Vector Autorregression (VAR), Messner and Pinson (2019) applied wind power forecasting for wind farms located in France and Denmark. In comparison with the non-adaptive versions of VAR-LASSO, the proposed model is more accurate in terms of the MAE and RMSE. Considering datasets from the La Haute Borne wind farm, France, Li et al. (2020) proposed a hybrid model by combining an Improved Dragonfly Optimizer (IDA) and SVR and applied it to a dataset from the La Haute Borne wind farm, France. The Normalized Mean Absolute Error (NMAE), RMSE, MAPE, and coefficient of determination criteria were adopted for the model evaluation. The error percentage lies within the interval of 8.64% to 10.58%. Latimier et al. (2020) adopted the Markov Switching Autoregressive (MSA) model. The authors reported that they can reduce forecasting errors and lead to a 15% reduction in operating costs, mainly derived from a fine model of forecast errors, which also outperformed the autoregressive model.‌‌‌‌

Liu et al. (2021c) also proposed a Stacked Recurrent Neural Network (SRNN) with a Parametric Activation Function (PSAF) algorithm for one-step-ahead forecasting, considering data from the National Renewable Energy Laboratory of the United States of America. Compared to LSTM and a GRU, the proposed model achieves a better accuracy in terms of the MAE and MAPE. The limitation of this approach is related to the convergence and stability of the proposed model, which remains open and must be examined. RodrÃ­guez et al. (2020) adopted a RNN for 10-minutes-ahead wind power forecasting using a database from Euskalmet, Basque Country. The deviation between the actual and wind power density reported was less than 6% for 81% of the examined days in the validation step. In addition, Hossain et al. (2021) proposed a novel GRU algorithm. The proposed model achieved MAPE values of 10.40%, 10.97%, 12.36%, 13.73%, and‌

14.41% for 2, 3, 5, 7, and 9-steps-ahead, respectively. In addition, the proposed model achieved a better performance in terms of percentage error regarding the ANNs, SVR, and ARIMA models.

Duan et al. (2022) proposed a hybrid forecasting model by coupling a time series pre-processing called VMD, a recurrent neural network, and PSOâDBN. Based on the MAE, the forecasting errors are equal to 35.37 kilowattsâhour (kWh). Compared with well-established EMD and WT, the adopted VMD deals with the influence of outliers through the Wiener filter, thereby more effectively reducing the complexity of the original wind power data and enhancing the predictability. In addition, the authors argued that the proposed method is relatively time-consuming, the main reason for which is that the VMD decomposition technology is more complicated than the EMD and WT technologies. Finally, although the hybrid model is time-consuming, its prediction performance is better than that of a single model. In turn, Zhou et al. (2021) proposed a hybrid forecasting


model based on a VMD and a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) for wind power generation and ramp event casting. They adopted datasets from Belgium and China. For wind power forecasting, the RMSE and MAPE criteria were then computed. Moreover, the forecast accuracy and ramp capture were used for the ramp forecasting. For the Belgium datasets, the improvements in the MAE, RMSE, and MAPE were 89.95%, 88.64%, and 88.08%, respectively. Considering the dataset from China, the authors argued that the proposed model improved the wind power ramp event forecasting.‌

Zhen et al. (2022) proposed a forecasting model based on the time-scale recognition and dynamic adaptive modeling. The authors split the wind series according to its features and then according to its time scale. Based on the SVR model, for data sampling taken every 15 minutes, time windows of 15, 30, 45, and 60 were considered. The empirical results indicate that the proposed approach presents higher accuracy in terms of the RMSE and MAPE than the benchmark models using the same forecasting algorithms but without considering the time scale or data screening. Chen et al. (2022) proposed a cooperative ensemble learning model based on CEEMDAN, fuzzy entropy, LSTM, and an improved BPNN. The forecasting horizons adopted were 1, 2, and 3-steps-ahead for 15 of resolution. The authors argued that the proposed model achieves a good reliability in terms of both stability and accuracy. In addition, it can deal with high volatility data and can reach a MAPE lower than 2.5% for 1-step-ahead. Moreover, the proposed model achieved better accuracy in terms of the MAPE than ARIMA, an Elman neural network, an LSTM, and a BPNN.

Moreover, a detailed review of the research and application of wind forecasting models was presented by Ahmadi and Khashei (2021). Table 4 presents a summary of the related works above described. In consideration of the aforementioned related works, it is possible to observe some search opportunities. The first refers to the geographic region of the datasets adopted in this study. Most of them focused on data from European and Asian regions, and limited discussions have been conducted on real data from Brazil. Second, the efficiency of the competitive ensemble forecasting method through a combination of bagging (through the MBB), stacking ensemble, and MOO within the same framework remains an open question.

Chapter 4‌‌


Real World Applications




Towards addressing the contributions of this thesis, in this chapter, four case studies are presented.

The first one is based on Ribeiro and Coelho (2020) entitled "Ensemble approach based on bagging, boosting and stacking for short-term prediction in agribusiness time series" and published in the Applied Soft Computing journal (v. 86, January 2020, 105837, <https:

//doi.org/10.1016/j.asoc.2019.105837>). The case study 2 is based on Ribeiro et al. (2020a) entitled "Multi-step ahead meningitis case forecasting based on decomposition and multi- objective optimization methods" and published in the Journal of Biomedical Informatics journal (v. 111, November 2020, 103575, <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2020.103575>).

The third case study is based on the paper "Ensemble Learning Model Applied to Electric Short-Term Load Forecasting" that will be submitted to the Elsevier journals database. Finally, the last case study is based on the paper Ribeiro et al. (2022) entitled "Efficient bootstrap stacking ensemble learning model applied to wind power generation forecasting" accepted for publication in International Journal of Electrical Power and Energy Systems journal (v. 136, Mach 2022, 107712 <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijepes.

2021.107712>).

In the next subsections, different forecasting ensemble learning models are designed using different methods involving time-series pre-processing, forecasting models, and optimization techniques. It is well known that the real data have different features according to the application. Based on the "No-Free-Lunch Theorem" formulated for optimization problems (WOLPERT; MACREADY, 1997; ADAM et al., 2019), the choices performed in the thesis regarding the models selection are supported by the fact that no single forecasting method performs best for all time series. In other words, one forecasting method can perform well for some applications and have some weaknesses depending on the considered time series. Therefore, different models must be evaluated.     1. Agricultural Commodities Prices Time Series‌‌

      This subsection presents a contextualization, contributions, datasets, and method- ology adopted for case study 1.

      The operations inherent to agribusiness constitute an important network of activities that have a strong influence on the local, regional, and national economy. Generally, in times of crisis, agribusiness has been one of the areas that have contributed to the growth of different indicators related to the economy, such as the Gross Domestic Product (GDP). Over the year of 2020, even during the COVID-19 pandemic, there is an estimate of growth for the Agricultural GDP around of 1.5% and for 2021, 3.2% (IPEA, 2020). For PR state, over the last months, there was an economic downturn due to the COVID-19 pandemic, and its GDP decreased around 7.52% for the second quarter of 2020. However, agriculture increased by around 9.36% concerning the same quarter of 2019 (IPARDES, 2020). Regarding production, according to the Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply (MinistÃ©rio da Agricultura, PecuÃ¡ria e Abastecimento, in Portuguese) (MAPA) (BRASIL, 2018), the area planted with grains is expected to increase by 14.9% in the next ten years. Indeed, this is an important area for the development of the regions, and it also contributes to family income. Faced with this, it is important to know future price quotations, since this may affect the economic planning of small, medium, and large producers.‌

      In this aspect, the forecast for time series of agricultural commodities prices plays an important role in the economic scenario (PUCHALSKY et al., 2018; BACCI et al., 2019; PINCE et al., 2020; DEGIANNAKIS et al., 2020). Also, the forecasting accuracy is as important as the expected results, and it is directly linked to the accuracy of the adopted model. Its importance permeates all areas of knowledge, as forecasts can be used as the basis for revision/implementation of public policies, development of strategic planning in companies, and decisions in the corporate world. In general, forecasting can be understood as a process of idealizing a more probable result, assuming a set of assumptions inherent in several aspects such as technology, environment, pricing, marketing, and production.

      To improve the predictive capacity of time series models, several approaches have been proposed in the literature. One of these are regression ensembles learning models (HAYKIN, 2009; DIETTERICH, 2000). This principle is based on ML, whose essence is associated with the idea of divide and conquer and which seeks to overcome the limitation of a ML model that operates in isolation (REN et al., 2015b; DIVINA et al., 2018). Models featured as ensembles refer to multiple base models (base learners, similar or not) developed to solve the same problem, each of which learns characteristics from data and accordingly makes a prediction. Hence, the final prediction is presented as a combination of the individual predictions. Through this approach is desired to obtain a robust system

      in terms of forecasting accuracy that incorporates the prediction from all base models.

      Among the basic ways to build ensembles for regression problems is the grouping by arithmetic and weighted average. In general, these approaches achieve better results than single prediction models, since it has a better capacity to generalize and adapt in different scenarios (SOARES et al., 2018). The purpose of using regression ensembles is to use a set of models to improve the forecasting accuracy of the adopted models (MENDES-MOREIRA et al., 2012). In this aspect, it is a methodology that has been evaluated extensively over years and has been successful in different applications such as energy (TORRES-BARRÃ¡N et al., 2019), climate (SOARES et al., 2018), market forecasting (ZHANG et al., 2016), finance (KRAUSS et al., 2017; WENG et al., 2018), and chemistry (PEIMANKAR et al., 2018).

      From this perspective, this case study aims to explore the predictive capacity of regression ensembles by comparing ensembles among themselves, as well as with approaches that consider a single model (reference models), to forecast agricultural commodities prices one-month-ahead. The motivation for choosing this forecast horizon for the area of agribusiness is associated with the fact that short-term forecasting allows small, medium and large producers to develop strategic planning for a short time to meet their instantaneous requirements. Moreover, in this case study the aim is also to identify if the number of base- learners adopted in the stacking ensemble learning approach can increase the forecasting accuracy. This case study uses two datasets in which historical data of monthly prices (R$) paid to the producers in PR state, Brazil, are considered for 60 kg bags of soybean (dataset 1) and wheat (dataset 2). Specifically, the ensemble learning methods named bagging, boosting, and STACK were evaluated in the task of forecasting soybean and wheat prices for one-month-ahead. In that case of bagging approach, the RF is adopted, while for boosting, GBM and XGBoost are used. The accuracy of these ensemble learning approaches were compared with single models named KNN, MLP, and SVR based on MAPE, MAE, RMSE, and MSE as well as DM hypothesis test.

      In consideration to the aforementioned, the following RQs are defined:


      RQ 1.1 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform price forecasting in agribusiness time series?

      RQ 2 - What are the appropriate price drivers to use as exogenous factors in the forecasting structure of agricultural commodities?


      To address the aforementioned RQs, the contributions of this case study are summarized as follows:

      • The first one lies in the application, evaluation and addition of discussions not previously developed regarding the behavior of GBM, RF, STACK, and XGBoost to forecasting (in the short-term) agricultural commodities prices;

      • Second, based on related works, several price drivers are identified and used as features or inputs by the evaluated models. Also, the feature importance in each case study is computed.

      • Third, while the related works identified in chapter 3 section 3.1 focus on the study of price volatility by hybrid models, as well as combining decomposition, optimization and ML models, this case study proposes the investigation of the performance of bagging, boosting and STACK ensemble learning approaches in the presence of different features (price drivers) regarding short-term forecasting for the soybean and wheat commodities;

      • Finally, the conducted experiments verified that the stacking ensemble accuracy is linked with the diversity of the base models and not with the number of the members of the layer-0.


        Through the aforementioned contributions, it is expected that a few time series models using regression ensembles to predict the agribusiness theme are introduced in the literature, this work will fill a gap in an area of the economy essential to the composition of economic indicators. Seeking to illustrate the superior performance of the ensemble learning models regarding reference approaches to one-month-ahead forecasting in time series associated with agribusiness, it is expected that this study will stimulate the interest of financial market researchers to use this approach since it performs well and enables managers to minimize their losses and leverage their earnings.

        To meet the objectives of this case study, monthly series of the prices received by the producers in PR state, Brazil, for soybean and wheat agricultural commodities are used. These commodities are chosen because they are part of an essential productive chain, being a source of income for many producers. They also contribute to different aspects of the economic sector. The whole datasets are split into two parts, the first one being used for training the models (70% of the data) and the second to test the performance of the trained model (30% of the data) (ANIFOWOSE et al., 2017). Table 5 presents the datasets split and sample size (n).

        Understanding which agents influence commodity pricing policies is of the utmost importance. This makes it possible to evaluate the timeliest moment in the financial market against these elements, rendering decision making more assertive. With regard such price driver in relation to agricultural commodities such as soybean and wheat, there is no consensus regarding which agents play a role in price determination. Thus, in the literature it is possible to find a range of references that sought to evaluate the association of their prices with factors such as Energy Commodities (EC), ER, FM, and ICP. Indeed, Table 6 presents some references which guide the choose of adequate predictors to forecast soybean and wheat prices.

        From Table 6 information, to forecast the prices of commodities adopted in this case study, the input (y) and features (x) are described in the sequence. In fact, the time series used in this case study are multivariate, that is, the soybean and wheat prices depends on other variables. In the same way, in this case, we have a multiple-input and single-output system. The inputs are the price (R$) of a 60 kg bag of soybean (y1) and wheat (y2) received by producers in PR state, price (R$) of a 60 kg bag of soybean (x2) and wheat (x3) from the CEPEA, exchange rate (US$ for R$) (x4), average pump price (R$) per liter of ethanol (state PR) (x5), price of a 50 kg (R$) bag of wheat flour (state PR) (x6) and future price of soybean (x7) and wheat (x8) contract (US$) quoted on the CBOT.

        4.1.1 Proposed Methodology

        In this subsection, the main steps adopted to perform the data modeling are described as follow:

        Step 1 Initially, the main features related as price drivers for soybean and wheat com- modities are identified based on Table 6. The original time series are pre-processed using BC transformation as follows:


        ï£´ï£³

        yâ = ï£±ï£´ï£²

        yÎ»â1 , Î» /= 0


        (4.1)

        Î»

        log y, Î» = 0

        where yâ denotes the transformed value. The maximum likelihood method esti- mates the parameter Î» of Eq.(4.1). It is easy to observe that when Î» = 0, this transformation is reduced to the logarithm transformation (BOX; COX, 1964).

        ANNs

        Regularized Regression

        GBM and XGBoost RF

        Stacking

        KNN SVR

        Step 2 In the sequence, the models, GBM , KNN , LASSO/SVR, MLP, RF, and XGBoost are trained to check it individual performance, as well as in the stacking ensemble learning framework. To perform one-month-ahead forecasting for the prices of adopted commodities, LOOCV described in subsection 2.1.1 is adopted in the training stage. Figure 18 presents the classification of the models used in this case study according to the categories described in the subsection 2.2.




        MLP

        Ensemble Models

        Source: The author.

        Alongside this, the training structure adopted in this case study is stated as follows:


        y(t + 1) = f {xi(t + 1 â nx)} + E, (4.2)

        where f is a function that maps the commodities prices, y(t + 1) is the commodity price in the horizon h = 1 at time t (1, . . . , 143 for dataset 1, and 1 . . . , 121 for dataset 2), xi(t + h â nx) is the exogenous inputs vector at the maximum lag of inputs (nx = 1), at feature i = 1, . . . , 8 for both commodities. Moreover, E is the random error that should be independent and identically distributed;

        Step 3 In the stacking ensemble learning two levels are considered. One of issues in this approach is related to the chose of base models to compose the layer-0. Firstly, the base models trained in step 2 are combined in order to compose the stacking ensemble learning layer-0. In fact, all combinations considering 2, 3, 4 and 5 of six evaluated models is made. For dataset 1, the GBM, KNN, LASSO, MLP, RF, and XGBoost are used as candidate to base model, while for dataset 2, the LASSO is replaced by SVR with linear kernel. Moreover, the SVR with linear kernel and LASSO regression are adopted as meta model for datasets 1 and 2, respectively. The model adopted in stacking ensemble learning layer-1 is not used in layer-0 ;

        Figure 19 illustrates the training process of stacking ensemble learning approach used in this case study. Each base model is chosen between the models described in Step 2.

        Step 4 In Step 3, for each case study, a grid of 56 stacking ensemble learning models is considered, and the choice of most suitable approach is made using results from the test set. For the results presented in Appendix A, the models numbered between 1 - 15 refer to the combination of the models above (in this order) taken 2 in 2, between 16 - 35 refer to the combination of 3 in 3, 36 - 50 refer to the combination of 4 in 4, and between 51 - 56 refer to the combination of models taken from 5 in 5 in the order mentioned in Step 3.
