        Step 5 The different models used herein have different sets of hyperparameters, so that, depending on the set of values used, the predictive performance can be maximized (WANG et al., 2016). As a result, because such parameters control the complexity of the model, wrong choices can result in models prone to improper inferences, as well as models prone to overfitting (ZHANG et al., 2016). In the boosting approach, due to the amount of parameters to be defined, different combinations tend to make the training process lengthy. Therefore, the step of setting such values should be undertaken with caution. In this way, Table A1 contained in Appendix A presents grid values, as well as the values for the hyperparameters adopted for the models used in datasets 1 and 2.

        Step 6 After training each stacking ensemble learning model, the performance measures described in section 2.5, for the training and test set are obtained. Finally, the statistical tests, and residue analysis are conducted for the evaluated models.


        The results presented in section 5.1 are generated using the processor Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-4200U central processing unit of 1.6Hz, 8 Gigabyte (GB) of random access memory in Windows 10 operating system. The caret (KUHN, 2008) is used to training the ML models.

    2. Meningitis Cases Time Series‌‌

      This subsection presents a contextualization, contributions, datasets, and method- ology adopted in the proposed ensemble learning model for case study 2.

      Meningitis is an inflammation that has several classifications with specific causes and symptoms, and, unfortunately, it is still a major public health problem because it causes irreversible health damages and has kept mortality rates high (WRIGHT et al., 2019). Besides, this disease could be a result of viral, bacterial, or fungal infection of the fluid surrounding the brain and spinal cord (KWARTENG et al., 2017). Early diagnosis and the immediate initiation of the treatment are fundamental for a good prognosis of the disease. Concerning the number of meningitis cases registered in Brazilian states located in the southern or southeastern such as PR, SP, MG, and RJ presented over ten thousand cases in 2018 (BRASIL, 2019). Within this context, the development of efficient public policies and preventive campaigns are the key to change this scenario. The development of efficient predictive models plays an important role in epidemiological modeling.

      Mathematics models are widely used to design the epidemiological scenario of specific diseases. These approaches are adopted for different purposes such as comparing, implementing, evaluating, prevention, therapy, and the development of public policies (HETHCOTE, 2000). Usually, the epidemic models are based on parameters related to sus- ceptibility, infected, and recovered, as well as exposed individuals can be considered which leads to the Susceptible-Infectious-Recovered (SIR) or Susceptible-Exposed-Infectious- Removed (SEIR) models. Each variation of these models has its particularity, and different factors can be considered in these approaches to provide knowledge about the disease spread. Nowadays, these approaches have been proposed to understand the spread of COVID-19 (SILVA et al., 2020; SARKAR et al., 2020). Also, different mathematical approaches are proposed to mitigate the effects of several diseases such as ebola (SEIDU et al., 2020), influenza (ARONIS et al., 2017), and malaria (TSANOU et al., 2020). In the last years, a computer science field called AI able to recognize patterns of historical data and support the decision making has received attention to solving problems from the commerce (VANNESCHI et al., 2018) and industry (MAO et al., 2019).‌

      ML, an AI sub-field, becomes the kernel of data analysis, since it can deals with classification (LEE et al., 2018), data clustering (HUANG et al., 2019) and regression tasks (CHEN et al., 2019). Nonetheless, when it comes to matters of diseases that plague the Brazilian public health system, such as dengue, malaria, and others, there are limited discussions as regards the effectiveness of ML models to develop predictive models. Some of these studies aimed to define the incidence of diseases such as ventriculitis and meningitis (SAVIN et al., 2018), as well as map the transmission risk of Zika (JIANG et al., 2018), and make probabilistic forecasting of influenza (SOLIMAN et al., 2019).

      Considering the purpose of knowing the number of future cases for any disease, once the data contain temporal information, time series forecasting should be used for this task. Therefore, time series forecasting, a regression field, aims to use past data to know future values with the purpose of, for example, making strategic planning to improve the knowledge in the domains that are inserted and help develop public policies. In this aspect, developing an efficient model is desirable; moreover, techniques such as the ensemble learning and decomposition may be used for this purpose. These strategies can be employed to deal with nonlinearity, non-stationarity, and cyclicity inherent to time series.

      Faced with this, the ensemble learning is an approach that is applicable in regression (RIBEIRO et al., 2019) and/or classification (RIBEIRO; REYNOSO-MEZA, 2020) tasks which have the objective of improving the modelâs predictive accuracy. The main aspect of this approach lies in training several base (weak) models and combining their predictions to build an efficient model (DIETTERICH, 2000). It is believed that this improvement occurs because each base model learns the different characteristics of the data and adds this information to the final results. Indeed, this methodology has proven effective in forecasting tasks in different fields of knowledge such as agribusiness (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020), chemometrics (SHAN et al., 2019), ecology (FAVALESSO et al., 2019), and medicine (BHASURAN et al., 2016; da SILVA et al., 2020).

      Also, an additional approach usually adopted to improve the performance of the models is the EEMD (WU; HUANG, 2009). By employing EEMD, it is possible to separate the original signal into components (IMF and residue) with different amplitudes and frequencies added to the noise, aiming to extract relevant data information. The EEMD approach has been proven effective in then forecasting field of dealing with applications in several domains of knowledge, such as aquaculture (HUAN et al., 2018), economy (WU et al., 2019) and energy (DU et al., 2019b).

      The EEMD steps consist of data decomposition and aggregating the components or aggregating the predictions of each component to obtain the original signal. In respect of this, each component is treated as an input set, and they can be trained separately using various algorithms. One strategy considers the same weight for all components (DI), which penalizes those that explain more data variability by attributing the same importance for all components, while another strategy employs different weights (WI) for each component. Because the disease series show up nonlinear and non-stationary on most of the cases, the EEMD is efficient to analyze series related to meningitis cases.

      Considering the aforementioned, because of the use of the EEMD approach, two questions emerge. The first one lies in which algorithm should be employed to train and forecast each component. The second refers to which approach will be used to reconstruct the decomposed signal, that is, which strategy should be adopted to obtain an ensemble

      of components. To deal with these questions, this case study aims to propose an ensemble learning framework that was developed in three steps for multi-month-ahead forecasting (one, two and three-month-ahead) meningitis cases in the Brazilian states of MG, SP, PR, and RJ.

      In consideration to the aforementioned, the following RQs are defined:


      RQ 1.2 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform the menin- gitis incidence forecasting?

      RQ 3 - Considering pre-processing methods in the composition of an ensemble learning model, what is the better choice between the heterogeneous and homogeneous ensemble for time series forecasting?

      RQ 4 - What is the proper choice between weighted integration through MOO and direct integration when time series pre-processing is used in the cooperative ensembles?

      RQ 5 - What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?


      As regards to this, in this case study, the objective is to propose an ensemble learning model based on time series pre-processing, HTE and MOO. The original time series is split into five components (four IMF and one residue). In the sequence, each component is used as the input of techniques: BRNN (SUN et al., 2017), CR (WORLAND et al., 2018), GBM (GUO et al., 2019), PLS (GUSNANTO et al., 2013), and QRF (KHAN

      et al., 2019). Following, predictions for all components are obtained by each model. Different combinations of models to predict the components are developed, and, for each combination, the results are WI to formulate a HTE, considering that at least two different models are used in each combination. Besides, MOO using elitist NSGA-II (DEB et al., 2002) is employed to find a PF (composed by a set of candidateâs weight), and TOPSIS (HWANG; YOON, 1981) is applied to choose the adequate set of weights from PF. Finally, considering all the combinations developed, the most adequate model is the one with the best generalization of out-of-sample capacity in terms of MAE, RRMSE, and sMAPE.

      To address the aforementioned RQs, the contributions of this case study are summarized as follows:


      • The development of a unique hybrid framework based on data decomposing, ensemble and MOO can improve simultaneously the accuracy and stability of forecasts of meningitis cases.

      • Performing multi-step-ahead forecasting, since in the papers related to diseases incidence forecasting, single forecasting horizon is used;

      • An investigation of the effectiveness of the multi-objective procedure for choosing weights used to aggregate the forecasts of EEMD components. In this regard, this case study seeks to add discussions in this field, taking into account most of the debates regarding SOO for components aggregation, such as Du et al. (2017) and Zhang and Wang (2018b);

      • Another contribution lies in the use of a diversified set of algorithms, con- cerning algorithms structure, to train and forecast each component after the EEMD performance, where these different algorithms can capture their inherent variability.


        The datasets adopted in this case study refer to the monthly number of confirmed cases of meningitis, recorded on a disease information system at the Brazilian Ministry of Health. The adopted period of analysis ranges from January of 2007 to December of 2018, and the data is available at the Department of Informatics of the Unified Health System (Departamento de InformÃ¡tica do Sistema Ãnico de SaÃºde, in Portuguese, DATASUS) (BRASIL, 2019). The data ranged from January of 2007 to December of 2017 is used in the training process and the remaining information is used to test the proposed frameworkâs performance, respectively. In this context, the adopted data refers to information on the number of confirmed cases of meningitis in the Brazilian states PR, SP, MG, and RJ taking into account that these states presented the four largest notifications number in 2018.

        In this case study, to verify the generalization ability of the proposed methodology, the above-described datasets are used. The proposed model wasnât fitted on the time series of a single region and then validated by predicting new cases of another area because each state has different features, such as demography, geography, population density, economic, and human development index, as well as public health policies. Therefore, to avoid erroneous conclusions, the proposed model is trained (training set) and validated (test set, out-of-sample forecasting) in the same Brazilian state, but in different splitting setups of the datasets. In this way, it was tried to accommodate the data variability for each state.

                When all weights are defined as equal to 1, Eq. (4.5) is the DI. Otherwise, an MOO procedure integrating the NSGA-II (DEB et al., 2002) and TOPSIS (HWANG et al., 1993) is adopted to apply the ensemble weight tuning.

              2. In the aforementioned procedure, after obtaining the forecasts for the k-th component, according to the weights generated (population) dur- ing the optimization process, NSGA-II is employed allowing MOO to

                deal with the conflicting objectives related to the forecasting error and stability. In this study, it is used the MSE as the error criterion and the errorâs variance as the stability criterion (LIU et al., 2020). The objective function is computed as follows:


                ,

                Minimize ï£±ï£´ï£² J1(yË) = MSE

                ï£´ï£´ï£³ J2(yË) = var(y â yË),


                (4.6)

                where y is the vector of observed values, and yË is the vector of forecast values. Accordingly, a set of Pareto-optimal solutions was obtained from the optimization process.

                The NSGA-II parameters, that is, the population size (number of candi- date solutions), generations (number of generations to breed during an evolutionary process), crossover and mutation probabilities, crossover, and mutation distribution, are defined as 100, 100, 0.9, 0.1, 0.7, and 0.2, respectively. The crossover operators are set to 0.9 and 0.7 because this allows new structures to be introduced into the population at a faster rate, whereas the mutation operators are set to 0.1 and 0.2 because it prevents a given position from becoming stationary in a set of values for the parameters to be optimized (DEB et al., 2002)

              3. To find the best set of weights, between all candidates, the TOPSIS approach is employed, in which the weights for bias (error) and variance objectives are 50% and 50%, respectively;

        Step 5 Forecasting the meningitis cases, out-of-sample, according to

        n=4

        yËt+h = Î¸jI MF Modelj + Î¸5R esidueModel5 , (4.7)

        j=1

        where Î¸Ëj is the estimated weight;

        Step 6 Computing the performance measures MAE, RRMSE, and sMAPE as well as DM test, according to described in the chapter 2. The best model is the one with the best capacity of out-of-sample generalization in terms of MAE, RRMSE, and sMAPE.

        Aiming to compare the forecast errors of two models, the DM test proposed by Diebold and Mariano (1995) is applied. By using the hypothesis defined for the DM test, the interest lies in knowing if the errors for the proposed model are lower than the compared model. If the null hypothesis is rejected, it is possible to say that there is statistically evidence that there is a reduction in the errors

        of the EEMD-HTE-MOO model regarding the compared model at the Î± level of significance.

    3. Electricity Energy Demand Time Series‌‌

      This subsection presents a contextualization, contributions, datasets, and method- ology adopted in the proposed ensemble learning model for case study 3.

      Load forecasting plays a vital role in the electrical power system and several fields of society such as the economy, food, health, and industry. Through obtained forecasts, companies can develop energetic planning able to meet electric power distribution and generation requirements. Also, it allows establishing strategic scheduling to leverage earnings of the companies and reduce losses. Regarding forecasting horizon, the load forecasting is split in short, medium, and long-term, that is, forecasting hours-ahead up to one-week-ahead, several weeks-ahead up to months-ahead, and several years-ahead, respectively (HONG; FAN, 2016). STLF is important for planning the demand response, hour and day-ahead scheduling, and energy trading (AHMAD et al., 2020). Owing to the importance of STLF for the environment of power system companies, the short-term is the forecasting window selected in this case study.

      For STLF, statistical (that is, Box & Jenkins methodologies) (AL-MUSAYLH et al., 2018) and hybrid approaches (that is, a combination of different methods) (ZHANG et al., 2018; TAYAB et al., 2020) are widely adopted to try to develop an efficient forecasting model. Generally, load data has a high degree of nonlinearity due to speed changes in the pattern, and the use of statistical models becomes less attractive (LAHOUAR; SLAMA, 2015). Alternatively, it is possible to adopt cooperative ensembles. Essentially, in that approach several techniques are combined, such as pre-processing stage (that is, time series decomposition methods) (OLIVEIRA et al., 2020; ZHOU et al., 2020b), ML models (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020), and optimization approaches (GUO et al., 2020; RIBEIRO et al., 2020).

      The advantage of cooperative ensembles lies in the capacity to deal with different signal characteristics by using the best expertise of each method to obtain an efficient forecasting model. However, the different degrees of complexity due to several approaches to dealing with the data characteristics can be a disadvantage. Traditionally, in hybrid frameworks, also known as ensemble learning frameworks, several weak models (learners) are adopted to handle different components, working in a divide-and-conquer paradigm. These models, when combined, generate an ensemble learning framework able to improve the accuracy of the models when applied to forecasting tasks (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020).

      In consideration to the aforementioned, the following RQs are defined:


      RQ 1.3 - What is the most suitable cooperative ensemble learning structure to perform electric energy load forecasting?

      RQ 5 - What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing

      methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?

      RQ 6 - What gain is obtained by employing sequential decomposition methods over single decomposed methods for time series forecasting?


      In this study, an ensemble learning model is based on a dual decomposition ensemble learning model, which combines two pre-processing techniques, AI models, and optimization applied to electric STLF. In fact, in the proposed framework, the STL (CLEVELAND et al., 1990) and VMD (DRAGOMIRETSKIY; ZOSSO, 2014) decom-

      position are sequentially used. First, the STL is employed to decompose the data into seasonal, trend, and residual components. Next, VMD is used to decompose the residue of STL into different frequencies (mode functions) and extract several characteristics. After applying sequential decomposition to the raw data, the XGBoost model is employed to handle the seasonality component, with hyperparameters tuned by the COA. The ridge regression RR model is adopted to handle the trend and VMD components in the same stage. Finally, the individual forecasts out-of-sample are obtained for each component and then are directly integrated, and the final forecasting obtained through the hybrid ensemble learning model is computed. In subsection 4.3.1 the main steps of the modeling are described, and a flowchart of the proposed forecasting model is presented. Then, in chapter 2 the adopted methods were described.

      The choice of dual decomposition to pre-process the time series is motivated by the promising results achieved previously by this method for electricity price forecasting (YANG et al., 2019), air cargo forecasting (LI et al., 2020), and wind power forecasting (MORENO et al., 2020). The STL decomposition is used because it explicitly separates the components of the time series. Through the use of STL pre-processing, the seasonal component is separately evaluated, and the influence of weather and other exogenous factors is intrinsically considered (GONZALEZ-ROMERA et al., 2006). Also, this decomposition was already used successfully in different fields of knowledge, such as vegetable price forecasting (XIONG et al., 2018), and passenger flow forecasting (QIN et al., 2019). Furthermore, the VMD can effectively capture and extract particular features of the signal, which allows achieving good results in terms of performance measures adopted to evaluate the developed frameworks for different time series forecasting applications, such as streamflow forecasting (ZUO et al., 2020), load pattern identification (CUI et al., 2019), and price forecasting (LIU et al., 2020). In this context, the VMD becomes suitable as the second decomposition approach to be integrated into STL. Compared with WT, VMD can extract more information from the data.

      The seasonal component always exhibits a rigorous cycle (XIONG et al., 2018), and usually is reproduced in the future. Indeed, Xiong et al. (2018) and Qin et al. (2019)

      used a seasonal NaÃ¯ve method to deal with the seasonality in the context of vegetable prices and passenger flow forecasting. This method copies the sequence produced by STL as the forecasting of seasonal component. However, in the STLF application, if copying the values of the last day to forecast the next, for example, will be ignored the changes over the day that can occur due to the uncertainty related to the load data. Indeed, the seasonal pattern can change over the time. Since every technique has its weakness, that the seasonal NaÃ¯ve does not consider the changes on some days of the week. For example, in the weekends could have more demand of the load owing to the reduction in the commercial activities. Also, it does not consider any possible causal relationships underlie the forecasted variable (SHIM et al., 2011). Hence, long-term forecasts like a week ahead may be underestimated or overestimated.

      On the other hand, different approaches must be used to deal with the seasonal â periodic behavior of time series, to investigate its feasibility to enhance the forecasting accuracy. Qin and Li (2020) used an echo state of networks for modeling the seasonal subseries in energy consumption forecasting in the United States of America. Nguyen and NovÃ¡k (2019) forecasting seasonal components using fuzzy techniques, and Zhou et al. (2020c) used a weighted extreme learning machine for the periodic components for the context of passenger flow forecasting. Therefore, is proposed the use of COAâXGBoost in this case study. The justification for using the COAâXGBoost is two-fold. The first is that the XGBoost is an efficient ensemble method that can learn different behaviors inherent to data and then obtain forecasts similar to observed values (YU et al., 2020). So, it can be a suitable approach to deal with the seasonal component of load data due to its learning capacity. Also, it can avoid overfitting and optimize the available computational resources. Second, motivated by the use of XGBoost that has hyperparameters for tuning, metaheuristics for optimization purposes are employed as observed in (SHI et al., 2021). Hence, the COAâXGBoost is a suitable tool to train and predict this component. The COA is a recently proposed swarm intelligence algorithm inspired by the behavior of Canis latrans (coyotes). Originally, COA achieved promising results by outperforming the accuracy of algorithms such as Artificial Bee Colony and PSO in 92 cases (PIEREZAN; COELHO, 2018). Owing to the observed effectiveness of COA, this algorithm is adopted to obtain the hyperparameters of XGBoost. Moreover, the investigation of COAâXGBoost is new in the field of load forecasting. Finally, since the RR model can effectively deal with the multicollinearity of inputs, overfitting and its versatility and convenience are adopted as models for the remaining components.

      The proposed ensemble learning model is named STL-VMD-COA-XGBoost-RR, and its effectiveness is evaluated for STLF using datasets from AEMO (Australian Energy Market Operator, 2019), considering five Australian regions, and four months (seasons) of the year. To test the efficiency of the proposed ensemble learning model for STLF, the forecasting horizon of 12-hours (half-day-ahead) and 24-hours-ahead (one-day-ahead) are

      considered. Three class of benchmarks are compared with proposed model, such as (i) non-decomposed models (ELM (HUANG et al., 2006), RR (HOERL; KENNARD, 1970), SVR (DRUCKER et al., 1997), and XGBoost (CHEN; GUESTRIN, 2016)); (ii) single‌

      decomposed models (STL, VMD, and Maximal Overlap wavelet transform (MODWT) (PERCIVAL; WALDEN, 2000)), and (iii) dual decomposed or ensemble of pre-processing techniques (STLâVMD and STLâMODWT) frameworks coupled with models used in (i). The WT approach is frequently adopted to pre-process load data, such as observed in Bento et al. (2019), El-Hendawi and Wang (2020), and in this study, WT is used as a second benchmark pre-processing. This study differs from Fan et al. (2019) and Wang et al. (2021), first because it uses an ensemble of decomposition techniques, second because it develops multi-step-ahead forecasting, and finally because uses a recent and effective metaheuristic named COA to tune the XGBoost hyperparameters.

      Aiming to compare the efficacy of the proposed approach, when the COAâXGBoost is adopted to deal with a seasonal component of load data, it was used other three well- established metaheuristics Differential Evolution (DE) (STORN; PRICE, 1995), GA (HOLLAND, 1992), and PSO (KENNEDY; EBERHART, 1995; TANWEER et al., 2016)

      to obtain the XGBoost hyperparameters by the RMSE performance metric minimization. In fact Peng et al. (2021) and Moreno-Carbonell et al. (2020) used GA, Peng et al. (2021) adopted DE, as well as Ozerdem et al. (2017), Wu et al. (2021), and Wang and Wang (2016) employed PSO for STLF. The accuracy of each forecasting model is measured by MAE, MAPE, sMAPE, OWA, IP, as well as the DM statistical test.

      To address the aforementioned RQs, the contributions of this case study are summarized as follows:


      • The first contribution lies in evaluating the use of an ensemble learning model that combines STL, VMD, COAâXGBoost, and RR models to capture the main features of electric load time series such as seasonality, nonlinearity, and non-stationarity in the same modeling. Extensive experiments are conducted to demonstrate the efficiency of the proposed forecasting model for the STLF field. In this context, twenty datasets are adopted, that is, load data from five regions of Australia and four months of the year to reflect the seasons for each one;

      • Second, aiming to demonstrate the efficiency of proposed ensemble learning, by considering results from the literature related to STLF, comparisons of the proposed method with EMDâDBN (QIU et al., 2017), SSA combined with recurrent neural network LSTM (NEERAJ et al., 2021), SSAâSVRâARIMAâ CSA (ZHANG; WANG, 2018a), DMD (MOHAN et al., 2018), and EMDâ MODBN (FAN et al., 2020) for half-an-hour and one-day-ahead forecasting;

      • Also, since COA is an approach proposed recently, this is the first study employing COA and XGBoost in the same framework. In fact, due to the necessity to define two control hyperparameters for COA (number of the packs and number of coyotes), a study of the feasibility of some values for these two parameters was conducted. The performance for the COA is compared with DE, GA, and PSO to tune the hyperparameters of XGBoost. for the seasonal component.


The datasets analyzed in this study refer to the 2019 electricity load in megawatt- hour (MWh) for the AEMO (Australian Energy Market Operator, 2019). The five Aus- tralian regions named New South Wales (NSW), Queensland (QLD), South Australia (SA), Tasmania (TAS), and Victoria (VIC) were chosen to train and test the proposed method. Due to the electricity demand changing over the months (seasons) of the year, in this study, for each region, four months were chosen to reflect the effects of different seasons of the year (QIU et al., 2017), i.e., May (Autumn), August (Winter), October (Spring), and December (Summer).‌‌‌‌

Twenty datasets (five regions and four months for each one) are considered in this study. The load data is sampled every 30 minutes during each month, and composed of 1488 observations. According to the Qiu et al. (2018) in the experiments developed in this study, for each dataset the first 70% observations are used to training the proposed model, while the remaining 30% are used to test the performance out-of-sample. In other words, for each month, around twentyâtwo days are used to train the proposed model using, while the remaining days are used to test the performance. Also, this experimental structure is adopted since only sequential periods are allowed to train the forecasting models, since the temporal dependency must be preserved and modeled. There are other possibilities to structure the training-testing process, but not limited to them, such as using the data from the first month to train and test in the second; to adopt the second month to train and test in the third; to train the model using the two first months and the third for testing, and so on.‌

4.3.1 Proposed Methodology

In this subsection, the proposed forecasting model is detailed using four steps.

Step 1: The load data is pre-processed by STL to obtain seasonal, trend, and residue components. Next, the residue is pre-processed by VMD to obtain four modes. The number of modes is defined through GS, taking into account the trade-off between accuracy-complexity. In Figures 28 up to 31 are illustrated the decomposed data for the first week of the time series (336 samples). In this study, the data seasonality is handled in two ways. First, by considering several datasets to represent each season of the year, aiming to capture the seasonal behavior of different periods of the year. Second, when STL decomposition is performed, seasonal period as daily is specified. Figures 28 up to 32 show that the weekly seasonality is included in the other components, such as in the trend and those produced by VMD (STL-residual decomposition). It is supposed that the proposed model can capture the weekly seasonality by handling the remainder components using RR regressions. Indeed, the results achieved by an ensemble of RR can produce reliable forecasting results even without considering additional features.

Step 3: In this step, the recursive strategy, also known as an iterated strategy, is adopted to find STLF values half-an-hour, twelve, and twenty four hours-ahead according to the experiment. Only one model is fitted for one-step-ahead forecasting. Then, the forecasting value is used as an input by the same model to forecast the next step-ahead. In fact, in this respect, the training structure adopted in this case study is stated as follows:


y(t+1,k) = f {y(t,k), . . . , y(t+1âny ,k) + E, (4.8)

in which f is a function related to the adopted model in the training stage, y(t+1,k) is the output forecasting one-step-ahead to the k-th component (k = 1, . . . , 6), ny = 3 are the lags to the load, E is the random error. To find up to H STLF values, especially to half-an-hour, 12, and up to 24-hours-ahead, H = 1, 24, and 48, respectively, the following structures are considered,


ï£±ï£´fË y(t,k), y(tâ1,k), . . . , y(tâny +1,k)1 if h = 1

yË(t+h,k) = ï£²ï£´fË yË(t+hâ1,k), . . . , yË(tâ1,k), y(t,k), . . . , y(t+hâny ,k)1 if h â [2, ny ]

ï£´ï£³fË yË(t+hâ1,k), . . . , yË(t+hâny ,k)1 if h â [ny + 1, . . . , H]

(4.9)


yË(t+h,k) is the forecast value for k-th component (k = 1,. . . ,6) at time t and forecast horizon up to h, y(t+hâny ,k) and yË(t+hâny ,k) are the previously observed and forecast load lags in ny = 3 half-an-hour. Indeed, in this case study, for each forecasting model, the three past values of load data are used as models inputs (ny = 3). The number of inputs was defined based on the analysis of Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF). In fact, the first three lags have the highest correlations at the 95% confidence level, and are adopted in this case study.

In the first case of the Eq. (4.9), the trained represented by fË model performs STLF one-step-ahead. To exemplify the recursive forecasting strategy, Table 14 describes for each forecasting horizon, how many inputs are used and the composition of inputs set.

After training and obtaining the forecasting of each model, the final forecasts were obtained by summing up the forecasting of each model. In other words, the COAâ XGBoost contributes to the final forecasting by modeling the seasonal component. The RR contributes to the final forecast by modeling the trend and four modes obtained in VMD pre-processing. Finally, the summation of the individual forecasts is done, and the final forecasts are achieved. The hyperparameters used in the proposed model are presented in Appendix C.

Step 4: The RMSE (2.62), sMAPE (2.63), MAE (2.59), MAPE (2.61), and IP

(2.67) criteria are used to check the effectiveness of the models. Also, a criterion that combines the sMAPE and MAE, named OWA (2.66) is introduced to compare the accuracy of the proposed model regarding the benchmark models.

The results presented in section 5.3 are generated using the processor Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-4200U central processing unit of 1.6Hz, 8 GB of random access memory in Windows 10 operating system. The caret (KUHN, 2008) is used to training the ML models.

    1. Wind Power Generation Time Series‌‌

      This subsection presents a contextualization, contributions, datasets, and method- ology adopted in the proposed ensemble learning model for case study 4.

      Renewable energy plays an important role in the energy matrix because there are no greenhouse gas emissions evolved, and owing to increased interest in the International Renewable Energy Certificate (I-REC), which is leading businesses to meet 100% energy consumption from renewable energy. Thus, global attention has turned to energy production by solar and wind power plants. I-REC are particularly useful to companies with global operations, and owing to their ability to be bought and sold, a global target of 100% renewable energy use has been proposed. Countries having increased their growth of renewable energy sources and increased their installed capacity of solar and wind energy are the biggest suppliers of I-REC (International REC Standard Foundation, 2021).

      The global wind industry installed a record of 93 gigawatt (GW) of new capacity in 2020, a 53% year-on-year increase (Global Wind Energy Council (GWEC), 2021). In Brazil, wind energy production already represents 17% of the national grid consumption, and the installed capacity has grown by 15.5% in the last year (Brazilian Wind Energy Association - ABEEÃ³lica, 2021). However, because ensuring the efficiency, correct use, and conversion of renewable resources, and minimizing renewable energy curtailments, play important roles, the growth of installed renewable energy capacity cannot be the only key performance indicator related to eliminating greenhouse gas emissions. Following this direction, the main process that can guarantee a better use of natural resources is the ability to predict the wind speed or solar irradiance when planning the daily dispatch of electrical energy, thereby avoiding or minimizing the impacts on the system stability and frequency control, also can reduce the excess of renewable energy curtailment (MORENO et al., 2020).

      Wind speed, and hence wind power production, is affected by uncertainties owing to climatic variations, which characterizes it as an intermittent source of energy production in long-term evaluations. In fact, the development of efficient forecasting models designed to forecast wind power generation is recognized as an important contribution to the reliable integration of large-scale wind energy (MORENO et al., 2021). Because of Brazilâs climatic diversity, there is significant potential for centralized wind power generation in the Brazilian Northeast region (SANTOS et al., 2020). In addition, owing to the benefits of wind energy production and its challenges, it is possible to observe the ongoing increase in the development of wind power and speed forecasting models for different areas globally, such as in Australia (HOSSAIN et al., 2021), Brazil (JACONDINO et al., 2021; SILVA et al., 2021), China (CHEN et al., 2022), Germany (WOOD, 2020), Japan (HU et al., 2020), among others (AHMADI; KHASHEI, 2021). Figure 37 presents the evolution of

      wind power installed capacity in MW for Brazil in the period of 2006â2024. For the future, data regarding 2022 to 2024 are projections based on contracts and can be updated at any moment. (Brazilian Wind Energy Association - ABEEÃ³lica, 2021).

      Improving the wind speed and power generation forecasting models will be nec- essary since renewable energy has a high participation in the composition of the global energy matrix (CHEN et al., 2022). Many researchers have explored forecasting tasks over the last few years (AHMADI; KHASHEI, 2021). Obtaining reliable and accurate forecasting models allows for an assertive decision-making process (DUAN et al., 2022). In fact, the intermittency and changes in speed of the data patterns constitute the major challenges in a forecasting task, which can affect the stability of a power system (ZHEN et al., 2022). Providing reliable wind power, wind speed, and solar forecasts is important in the renewable energy field and can help decision-makers provide preventive maintenance, electricity market clearing, and reload sharing (NAJIBI et al., 2021). Ensemble learning and statistical methods (LIU et al., 2021a) can be developed to obtain reliable wind-power forecasting. From a broader perspective, ensemble learning methods comprise a set of methods that can solve different types of problems and generate predictive systems with high accuracy. Two types of ensemble forecasting methods can be found in the literature (OPITZ; MACLIN, 1999).

      The first, competitive ensemble learning methods, include data, hyperparameters, and structural diversity. From this perspective, multiple predictors with different structures are used to construct the forecasting model as an ensemble learning model (REN et al.,

      2015a). In this context, the widely employed methods are bagging (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020) and boosting (KUMARI; TOSHNIWAL, 2021) for data diversity, and a stacking ensemble (FRACCANABBIA et al., 2020) for structure diversity, for structural diversity, whereas a Kalman filter can be adopted to induce parameter diversity. As the second type, cooperative ensembles integrate different methods designed to solve a single task, aiming to maximize the performance of the forecasting system in terms of error reduction. The final forecasts are obtained by aggregating the forecast values of all individual models (REN et al., 2015a; HE; WANG, 2021). In this context, pre-processing (MORENO et al., 2021), metaheuristics for hyperparameters tuning (SAHU et al., 2021), and feature selection (IZIDIO et al., 2021), statistical models (LIU et al., 2021a), and artificial intelligence models (DUAN et al., 2021) can be used to compose this type of ensemble learning framework. In particular, when time series pre-processing techniques are adopted, VMD (MORENO et al., 2020), a WT (STEFENON et al., 2020a), EMD (RIBEIRO et al., 2020b), and

      their variants (RIBEIRO et al., 2020) have been adopted to deal with the time series characteristics.

      In consideration to the aforementioned, the following RQs are defined:


      RQ 1.4 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform multi-step wind power generation forecasting?

      RQ 7 - What improvement is reached by combining bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods against the single stacking and statistical models?


      In this study, an improved ensemble learning model was developed for wind power generation forecasting. Our motivation is based on the ongoing implementation and development of renewable energy worldwide. Without loss of generality, our study used data from Brazilian wind farms. According to the Global Wind Energy Council, new global wind installations will reach an installed capacity of 280 GW by 2030 (Global Wind Energy Council (GWEC), 2021). From an economic perspective, replacing fossil energy with renewable energy usage can benefit countries by attracting stakeholders concerned with environmental, social, and governance factors. Therefore, studies focusing on the renewable energy sector are required.

      This study aims to evaluate a competitive ensemble forecasting model that integrates different learning strategies to achieve reliable wind power generation. Bagging with a Moving Blocks Bootstrap (MBB) resampling technique is the first approach used, as proposed by Bergmeir et al. (2016). Second, a ML paradigm called stacking ensemble learning is applied to handle the samples of the bagging stage. To aggregate the samples after obtaining the stacking forecasts, arithmetic and weighted averages are used. To tune the weights, MOO is adopted, aiming to simultaneously enhance the accuracy and

      stability of the forecasting model. This study differs from the approaches by Meira et al. (2021), Oliveira and Oliveira (2018) in two aspects. First, instead of applying an ARIMA model or Exponential Smoothing (ETS) to deal with applications of the electricity energy field, the efficiency and versatility of the stacking ensemble are used. Second, as suggested by Ren et al. (2015a), the MOO was explored to tune the weights used in the bagging aggregation. The proposed ensemble model is adopted for very short-term (10 and 30-minutes-ahead) and short-term (60 and 120-minutes-ahead) predictions for wind power generation considering the real-time series from two wind farms located in Bahia State, Brazil. The forecasting accuracy of the proposed and compared models was evaluated using the MAE, RMSE, RRMSE, MAPE, U2, IP, and DM hypothesis test.

      To address the aforementioned RQs, the contributions of this case study are summarized as follows:


      • A new ensemble learning model is evaluated that combines bagging and stacking to deal with the intermittent features of wind power generation to obtain reliable forecasting. Several experiments were conducted to evaluate the efficiency of the proposed model;

      • Different numbers of MBB samples, i.e., 30, 50, and 100 samples, are considered, in contrast to most papers related to this approach, which did not conduct this type of analysis. In this context, it is possible to establish a relationship between the number of samples and the complexity of the forecasting model;

      • The suitability of different settings is investigated based on the number of bootstrap samples and using aggregation methods along with the arithmetic average and weighted average through the MOO strategy. In this study, the MOO strategy is adopted because previous research in different fields in the context of time series forecasting has proven to be an efficient strategy for obtaining ensemble weights and simultaneously improving the accuracy and stability of the developed forecasting framework;

      • The efficiency of the developed model is compared with a single stacking ensemble, different ML models applying a stacking ensemble as base models, deep learning models, and statistical models for 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes- ahead wind power forecasting. In fact, through the use of these horizons, the effectiveness of the bagging stacking ensemble learning model can be verified under several different scenarios.


This study adopted two time series composed of wind power generation in kilowatts- hour (kWh) recorded every 10 minutes, from two Wind Farm (WDF) (WDF1 and WDF2), both located in Bahia, Brazil, for January 2021. WDF1 is located in SÃ£o SebastiÃ£o do Alto

and has an installed power of 19.20 megawatt-hour (MWh) of installed capacity, composed of 12 wind turbines, each one with 1.60 MWh of power capacity. Moreover, the WDF2 is located in Rio Verde and has an installed power of 31.92 MWh, being composed of 19 wind turbines, each one with 1.68 MWh of power capacity. Both have a rotor diameter of 90 m and a rotor height of 80 m. The length of the time series reached 4,322 samples for January 2021, collected at a sampling rate of 10 minutes, as illustrated in Figure 38.

The datasets were split into training and testing sets in proportions of 70% and 30%, respectively. The first 70% were used to train the adopted models, and the remaining 30% were used to test the effectiveness of the evaluated forecasting models. Moreover, once the datasets are time series, the training and test sets are composed through a sequential

observation and not by randomly selected observations. The adopted percentage of data used to train and test the models is useful for providing more information to the models to learn the wind power generation dynamics, as well as to have a sufficient number of data to evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed model.

4.4.1 Proposed Methodology‌

This subsection provides a detailed description of the steps employed to obtain the proposed forecasting model.

Step 1: The original time series is pre-processed using BC transformation as follows:


Î»

yâ = ï£±ï£´ï£²

yÎ»â1 , Î» /= 0


(4.10)

ï£´ï£³ log y, Î» = 0

where yâ denotes the transformed value. It is easy to observe that when Î» = 0, this transformation is reduced to the logarithm transformation (BOX; COX, 1964). Thus, the BC transformation is applied. Next, the data are decomposed using the STL if the time series have a seasonal component. Otherwise, the series is decomposed using the Loess method. In both cases, the residual component is bootstrapped using the MBB approach, and s samples are obtained. In this study, s equals 30, 50, and 100 were considered. Finally, raw data are recomposed, and s samples are obtained. The inverse BC transformation is also applied. This process is conducted using the bld.mbb.bootstrap function from the forecast package (HYNDMAN et al., 2021) in R software.

Step 2: The s samples obtained in the previous step are used to train the stacking ensemble model. Moreover, CV is employed in the training stage using the training set. The models GP, SVR, KNN, and RF are used as base models to compose layer- 0, whereas the RR is used as a meta-learner in layer-1. The base-learner selection is a critical issue in obtaining an efficient ensemble learning model. Regarding the stacking methodology, selecting base models and meta-learners is a challenging task because the meta-learner uses the prediction provided by the base models as input features. There are no guidelines for this selection. In most cases, this is achieved through trial and error by using base models with different learning strategies, aiming to add diversity in the ensemble learning model, as observed in (RIBEIRO; COELHO, 2020).

In this study, was selected a set of diverse base models to compose the stacking layer-0, which have different learning strategies, lower computational costs, and a lower number of hyperparameters for tuning. These learners are a GP and an SVR with different kernel functions, i.e., a KNN, RF, and XGBoost. Also, some ANNs such as ELM, ANNs with regularization, and MLP were considered. Different compositions of layer-0 were evaluated in both case studies. Always was used a probabilistic model such as a GP, the SVR approach, an ensemble method such as an RF or XGBoost, and an ANNs in the composition of layer-0. For the meta- learner, the LASSO or RR regression were considered. After conducting several experiments considering the above, the GP, SVR, KNN, and RF were chosen. This setting achieved a better accuracy in terms of the RMSE, MAE, and MAPE than the other combinations. The hyperparameters for each forecasting model were obtained during the CV process in the training stage through an automatic GS using the caret package (KUHN, 2008) from R software (R Core Team, 2020). These results are presented in Table D1.

Step 3: The recursive strategy is adopted in this study to conduct multi-step-ahead forecasting using each model. For the desired forecasting window (H=1, 3, 6, and

12), the forecasts are computed according to Eq. (4.11), as follows:‌


ï£´ï£´ â â y

ï£±f yt, yt 1, . . . , yt n +11 if h = 1

yËt+h = ï£²f yËt+hâ1, . . . , yËt+1, yt, . . . , yt+hâny 1 if h â [2, . . . , ny]

ï£´ï£³f yËt+hâ1, . . . , yËt+hâny 1 if h â [ny + 1, . . . , H],


(4.11)


where yËt+h is the forecast value at time t and the forecast horizon up to h, yt+hâny and yËt+hâny are the previously observed and forecast power generation lags for ny = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11, 15, 24. Through GS in a trial-and-error strategy, the five past values for wind power are used as inputs.

Step 4: After conducting the training for s samples obtained through an MBB using stacking ensemble learning, the final forecasts are obtained according to Eq. (4.12)


ï£º Ë

Î¸iStackingi

s

ï£º

Î¸Ëi

i=1


, (4.12)

where the Î¸ = [Î¸1, . . . , Î¸s] is the weight vector to be estimated, in which Î¸i â¼ Unif [â2, 2] (SONG et al., 2018). When all weights are defined as equal to 1, Eq. (4.12) is the arithmetic average. Otherwise, an MOO procedure integrating the NSGA-II (DEB et al., 2002) and TOPSIS (HWANG et al., 1993) is adopted to apply the ensemble weight tuning.

In the aforementioned procedure, after obtaining the forecasts for the s samples, according to the weights generated (population) during the optimization process, NSGA-II is employed allowing MOO to deal with the conflicting objectives related to the forecasting error and stability. In this study, it is used the MAE as the error criterion and the errorâs variance as the stability criterion (LIU et al., 2020). The objective function is computed as follows:


,

Minimize ï£±ï£´ï£² J1(yË) = MAE

ï£´ï£´ï£³ J2(yË) = var(y â yË),


(4.13)

where y is the vector of observed values, and yË is the vector of forecast values.

Accordingly, a set of Pareto-optimal solutions was obtained from the optimization process. Finally, the TOPSIS method is adopted to rank all of these solutions from the best to the worst to determine the best compromise solution.

The results presented in section 5.4 are generated using the processor Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-4200U central processing unit of 1.6Hz, 8 GB of random access memory in Windows 10 operating system. The caret (KUHN, 2008) is used to training the ML models and forecast for statistical models from R software (R Core Team, 2020). Moreover the tscv is used to fit the statistical methods considering a rolling window strategy. The Python 3.8 was employed to obtain the forecasts from CNN, GRU, LSTM, and RNN using Keras.


Chapter 5‌


Results and Discussions



In this chapter are presented the results and discussions for each case study presented in chapter 4.‌


    1. Case Study 1

      This subsection presents the results of performance measures (subsection 5.1.1), statistical tests for the errors of the test set, and residual analysis for case study detailed in subsection 4.1. Tables A2 and A3 show the performance measures of the 56 stacking ensemble models.‌


      1. Comparisons of evaluated ensembles and single models

        Table 16 details the performance measures achieved by each evaluated forecasting model. In addition, the results are sorted regarding lower MAPE for training and test results. Finally, the best models are those that presented lower metrics in the test set. For the stacking ensemble learning approach, regarding results from test set, in dataset 1, layer-0 is composed of models KNN, LASSO, and XGBoost with SVR in layer-1. In dataset 2, SVR and XGBoost compose layer-0 with LASSO in layer-1. In Table A, the models numbered 9, 19, 30, 31, 40, 41, 49, 54 achieved the same performance. The Layer-0 of these models is composed of SVR and XGBoost in all cases, with some variations for base models combination. In this case study, it means that including other base models did not improve the stacking ensemble learning performance. In this aspect, model 9 is chosen for the stacking ensemble learning approach since its complexity is lower than other configurations. In Table 16 the best results are presented in bold.

        Evaluating the results by test set, as presented in Tables 16 and 17, it can be stated in general that the methods based on the ensemble approach gives good performance for short-term forecasting in the agribusiness area about other models used. According

        Regarding the performance of adopted models, it could be seen in the training phase that the XGBoost fit well the data. Its MAPE is lower, between 146% and 2337.79%, concerning the ensemble models for datasets 1 and 2, respectively. Regarding the single approach models, this percentage reduction is even higher, being at minimum 6211.83% and 4917.56% lower for datasets 1 and 2. Concerning the RMSE of models, the XGBoost performance is also better concerning the others, that is, it had lower observed RMSE values, and greater variations are observed when comparing the results of XGBoost about MLP, SVR, and KNN in both datasets. In this scenario, this allows high-capacity predictions of observations of this approach, with small errors, thus being stable concerning the time series forecasting (FAN et al., 2018).

        In respect of the results for the test phase, Table 16 shows that the approaches based on ensemble learning presented results consistent with minimized errors. In both datasets, GBM, stacking ensemble learning, XGBoost, and RF presented lower performance

        measures compared to the other approaches. In percentage terms, in dataset 1, the XGBoost and stacking ensemble learning models had similar behaviors. Comparing the results of XGBoost model with the others models, except stacking, percentage reduction of the performance measures are observed, which range between 11.04%â40.36%, 10.47%â36.82%, 19.35%â83.87% and 11.30%â41.03% for MAPE, RMSE, MSE, and MAE respectively, in relation to the other models.

        When the performance of XGBoost is evaluated in relation to stacking ensemble learning, GBM, and RF, smaller variations are observed compared to XGBoost in relation to MLP, SVR, and KNN. These results demonstrate the generalization capacity and robustness of the XGBoost approach when applied to forecasts one month ahead of the price paid to the producer of soybean. The XGBoost and stacking ensemble learning models are competitive, with similar performances. This perhaps may be associated to the fact that in the stacking ensemble learning model, only the XGBoost, LASSO, and KNN models form the layer-0. In addition, the good performance in terms of MAE, MAPE, MSE, and RMSE of the boosting-based approach is associated with the fact that such a model acts by correcting errors committed by its previous basic models, thus potentially improving prediction accuracy (ZHANG; HAGHANI, 2015).

        With regard to the results of dataset 2, similar considerations can be made. However, the RF approach is more effective than other ensemble and reference models. If we compare the results of the RF model with STACK, XGBoost and GBM, the reduction in the performance measures of this model range from 19.46%â33.11%, 14.17%â16.39%, 30.77%â38.46%, 18.49%â31.32% for MAPE, RMSE, MSE , and MAE respectively. This reduction is greater when comparing the RF performance against reference models. It can be stated that the RF model reduced the predicted errors, showing to be a suitable tool for short-term forecasting, which should be used as an aid in decision making, since an accurate modeling can be developed (KHANAL et al., 2018).

        Besides, for both training and test sets, the base models in layers-0 of the stacking ensemble learning approach did not statistically interfere in the predictive performance

        3

        of the final model (Ï2 = 0.1232â2.99, p-value > 0.05), that is, MAE, MAPE, RMSE,

        and MSE did not have statistically significant gains with this variation. This information confirms that an ensemble modelled in layers tends to achieve good results depending on the diversification of the initial layer models and not according to the number of elements. Alongside this, the Appendix A show that 23.21% and 57.14% of the models have better performance than single models to forecasting soybean (dataset 1) and wheat (dataset 2) commodities.‌

          Figures 42a and 42b show the observed and price forecasting of the models that achieved lower forecasting errors in terms of the performance measures reported (for the test set) in Table 16. The best performing model to forecast agricultural commodities prices one-month-ahead is XGBoost for dataset 1 (soybean price) and RF for dataset 2 (wheat price). In this aspect, possible to identify that the behavior of the data is learned by

          the models, which can perform predictions compatible with the observed values. The good performance obtained in the training phase persists in the test stage, thus indicating that the ensemble the methodology is robust in the accomplishment of the developed predictions. This is justified by the fact that ML modeling is able of accommodating nonlinearities, as well as complex modeling relationships between dependent and independent variables, such as the pricing relationships relevant to agribusiness (FAN et al., 2018).

          According to the illustration of Figures 42a and 42b, it is possible to identify that the models learn the behavior of the data. They were able to perform predictions similar to the observed values. The excellent performance in terms of MAE, MAPE, RMSE, and MSE obtained in the training phase persists in the test stage, thus indicating that the ensemble methodology is robust in the accomplishment of the developed predictions. It is justified by the fact that ML modeling is capable of accommodating nonlinearities, as well as complex modeling relationships between dependent and independent variables, such as the pricing relationships relevant to agribusiness (FAN et al., 2018).

          For both datasets, the indicator of CEPEA/ESALQ-USP (x1 and x3) showed a high contribution to the pricing of these commodities. Alongside this, the ICP (x2, x3, and x6), FM (x7 and x8), and EC (x5) influence was less intense in both datasets, and these results corroborate with those in the Figures 16 and 17. It should note that the price of ethanol (x5) was excluded from the set of features in both cases. However, the results obtained in the new modeling are worse than those presented here, so it was decided to keep this feature.

          The aforementioned results suggest that agricultural commodities prices are extremely affected by reference indicators such as CEPEA/ESALQ-USP and prices of the main markets, such as the CBOT. In addition, feature engineering plays an important role in ML modeling. Initially, this approach was used with the purpose to improve the performance of proposed ensembles. In this context, statistical features are adopted based on lags (5, for example) of inputs (average, Std, skewness, kurtosis for five past values).

          Besides, features such as hyperbolic tangent, square root, x2, x3 (predictive variable

          i i

          i = 1, . . . , 8) and several combinations such as sum, rate and difference between variables from Table 8, were adopted. The feature extraction technique (filter based on correlation) was used to extract a feature set in this context. However, the improvement is not significant regarding the use of initial features alone (predictive variables of Table 7). Hence, in this context, a model with fewer components is preferable.

          According to the illustration of Figure 44, it is possible to evaluate the residuals of final models adopted in each case study from training set results.       3. Conclusions

        This case study aimed to compare the predictive performance of the GBM, XGBoost, RF and stacking ensemble learning ensembles, as well as the MLP, SVR, and

        KNN models. Two datasets related to agribusiness, namely dataset 1, the soybean price and dataset 2, the wheat price paid to the producer from the state of PR, for short-term forecasting were used. Were chosen explanatory variables based on studies found in the literature. Different models were combined, in the stacking ensemble learning, to form layer-0 of the meta-modeling. The SVR with a linear kernel and LASSO regression were adopted as meta-learners for the time series of soybean and wheat prices. The DM test was adopted to verify the existence of a difference between the APE of the models. Additionally, residual analysis was conducted to check the residual adequacy of the trained model.

        Considering the RQ 1.1 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform price forecasting in agribusiness time series?, the findings suggest that to forecast one-month-ahead, three models can be adopted as follows: XGBoost and LASSO-KNN- XGBoost-SVR stacking ensemble learning to forecast soybean prices, and RF to forecast wheat prices. In both cases, the BC (Î» = 0) is applied to predictors and exogenous variables. The results regarding the test set ensure that the ensemble approaches perform better than single models, especially the XGBoost model, to forecast agricultural commodities in the short term. In addition, the approaches based on boosting for ensemble generation proved to be robust for the commodity price forecasting one-month-ahead. In addition, the conducted experiments verified that the stacking ensemble accuracy is linked with the diversity of the base models and not with the number of members of the layer-0. For the answer to RQ 2 -What are the appropriate price drivers to use as exogenous factors in the forecasting structure of agricultural commodities?, it was found that the exogenous factors, the interaction between commodity prices in the domestic market, prices in the external market, and exchange rate play a vital role in the price direction of considered commodities. From a broader perspective, this first case study showed that the evaluated ensemble learning methods in the presence of correct exogenous factors achieve better accuracy than single models for time series forecasting. To answer RQ 1.1 and RQ 2 the specific objectives (a) and (b) were achieved.

        The information contained in this case study is relevant for decision-making aid and synthesizing the main factors that affect soybean and wheat agricultural commodities prices. Based on the results presented here, small producers and managers of cooperatives are supported by concrete information that allows them to choose when to deliver their products to the wholesaler, as well as to draw market strategies that maximize their profits. Therefore, the findings in this case study allow those responsible for carrying out deliberations with reduced risk and maximized assertiveness. In this case study, there are no considerations about weather changes or political aspects for agribusiness area. According to Thompson et al. (2018), these aspects can modestly increase the price volatility. In this context, the prediction assertiveness can be reduced. Since, at this moment, these factors are not considered, this is assumed to be a study limitation. Nevertheless, even with satisfactory results, the decision-making process must be parsimonious since agricultural

        commodities prices are volatile and tend to show large fluctuations.

    2. Case Study 2‌‌

      This subsection presents the results and discussions of the results obtained from the developed experiments for case study detailed in subsection 4.2.

      The objective of subsections 5.2.1, 5.2.2 and 5.2.3 is to present the main results obtained with the proposed approach against various classes of models. Faced with this, three different comparisons were developed and performance on the out-of-sample forecast (for test set) is presented. Through these comparisons, the prediction accuracy of the proposed framework is effectively evaluated. Tables 18, 19, and 20, present the best results in bold. Table B1 contained in B presents the control hyperparameters of the adopted models for the task of training and predicting each component of the decomposition stage, as well as the data trained without EEMD decomposition. In the context of the structure of the ensemble learning model, the weights of proposed framework are presented in Table B3 contained in Appendix B, and the respective models used to train and predict each IMF and residue. Considering all the forecast horizons, for the developed models, the GBM model is the most used to train the components, while QRF is the least employed for this task. In both cases, GBM and QRF are ensemble approaches; however, the first model is based on boosting, while the second one on bagging‌


      1. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and decomposed homo- geneous optimized ensemble models

        The comparisons I is designed to verify the forecast performance of the proposed hybrid framework by comparing it with five models based on decomposition, which uses the same model for all components and MOO in the aggregation step, namely EEMD- BRNN-MOO, EEMD-CR-MOO, EEMD-GBM-MOO, EEMD-QRF-MOO, and EEMD-

        PLS-MOO. The comparisons are shown in Table 18 and additional discussion are also presented.

        The results presented by Table 18 show that the approach considered as a hetero- geneous ensemble of components is more accurate than other approaches that consider the same model for all IMF and residue, to forecast the number of meningitis cases one, two and three-month-ahead of time. According to Zhang et al. (2018), this effectiveness is associated with the diversity used by the heterogeneous ensemble approach, which is an efficient and simple way to perfect forecasting accuracy and stability (errors with lower Std). Faced with this, it makes the predictive model more robust.

This is associated with the fact that in the proposed framework, for these states, there is the use of two and four different models, respectively, to compose the heterogeneous ensemble approach. This diversity allows the developed model to achieve the best performance, regarding RRMSE and sMAPE, associated to the fact that the manipulation of some algorithms to build the ensemble is an important strategy to get an efficient model (LIU; YAO, 1999). In this respect, each model learns different patterns of the data, and when the results are combined, they build an effective model. These results corroborate with the findings of Heinermann and Kramer (2016) and Xiang et al. (2018), proving that using different models for the decomposed components is promising for time series forecasting.‌


      2. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and non-decomposed models

        The comparison II is designed to verify the forecasting performance of the proposed hybrid framework by comparing it with five models which do not consider EEMD for signal decomposition, namely BRNN, CR, GBM, QRF, and PLS. The comparisons are shown in Table 19 and additional discussion is presented.

        Regarding the results described in Table 19, it could be seen that the use of signal decomposition, specifically in the case of the EEMD approach, can enhance the modelâs performance. These results show that the EEMD approach is suitable for decomposing the meningitis case series for all states. For this reason, the idea of decomposition and ensemble is feasible, and the proposed framework can overcome the drawbacks of individual models by removing the noise of the original data.

        Considering the average of each criterion for each forecast horizons, there is a reduction in the criteria for the proposed approach compared to models that do not consider signal decomposition. The increasing on MAE criterion compared models regarding proposed ensemble learning model is ranged between 95.03% - 116.18%, 64.90% - 91.48%, 75.20% - 99.88%, 98.52% - 125.62% for the states of MG, SP, PR and RJ. In its turn, for sMAPE and RRMSE, the same behavior is observed. The smallest reduction is visualized by comparing the proposed framework to the PLS model, and the largest when it is performed comparison with QRF, for both criteria.

        In accordance with the results presented in Table 20, it can be stated that the use of MOO in the WI aggregation allows an improvement of the modelâs accuracy. Based on the evaluation of all criteria for the EEMD-HTE-MOO, its approach achieves more optimum accuracy than the EEMD-HTE-DI approach. Thus, the proposed methodology can generate robust models that have enhanced forecasting performance with this model combined with it based on decomposition, ensemble, and MOO.

        The EEMD-HTE-MOO presents a better generalization capacity than the EEMD- HTE-DI, considering that the nonlinearities are accommodated by the use of different weights for each component. In general, this shows that the proposed ensemble model can combine the advantages of the single forecasting models, through the use of MOO, making

        it possible to add more accuracy and stability to the model (QU et al., 2017). Also, the effectiveness of the proposed approach, according to Bui et al. (2018), can be attributed to the process of construction of the combined model using the optimization. Consequently, the MOO allows dealing with the trade-off between bias-variances while assigning different weights for each model. By minimizing the forecast and Std errors it becomes possible to obtain an efficient model with both accuracy and stability improved simultaneously presenting a balance between the two optimized objectives.

        As presented in the subsection 4.2.1, the results detailed in Tables 18 to 20 are obtained through the recursive method to forecasting multi-step-ahead meningitis cases. Through this method, the errors can be accumulated according to the growth of the forecasting horizon. This phenomenon can be observed in MG, PR, and RJ states when are compared the first two forecasting horizons (regarding MAE and sMAPE), and for SP state in the three forecasting horizons. However, in some cases, the proposed model reduces the forecasting errors, even with the increase of the forecasting horizon. Nevertheless, according to Taieb et al. (2012), there is greater evidence of errors accumulation in long- term forecasting horizons, since the input vector adopted by the predictive model can be formed only by previously forecasting, instead of observed values. However, this is not the case of this case study, once the forecast horizon is short (h equal 1, 2, and 3). In its turn, as three values (ny=4) are adopted as input to the models, there are always ny-h+1 observed values in the input vector. Therefore, the forecasting errors can reduce according to the adopted forecasting horizons.

        By considering the behavior of the meningitis monthly incidence, there is no clear trend in the time series. In this respect, since the forecasting value of two months-ahead is used as input of the models to forecasting three-months-ahead, the information provided in the previous forecasting value can be beneficial to the next forecasting, even though they are different of observed values. In this context, the forecasting errors of the next step-ahead can be reduced, which is observed in Tables 18 to 20. The same is observed in the results achieved by Xiong et al. (2018) when the hybrid model which combines STL with extreme learning machine was applied to forecast the vegetable market, and Moreno et al. (2020) when the authors proposed a hybrid model based on singular spectral analysis, VMD, and LSTM to forecasting multi-step-ahead wind speed. From a broader perspective, the results of this case study are corroborated by the results of Li et al. (2021), showing that the use of MOO and HTE models are good tools to improve the forecasting accuracy in different fields of application.

        Additionally, this information is supported by the results presented in Table 21, in which the Std of the errors is presented for each model throughout the twelve study scenarios. The best results are presented in bold.

      4. Hypothesis tests and graphical analysis.‌

        Table 23 presents the statistic of DM test for comparisons of proposed and the remaining models. For the one-month-ahead forecasting, Table 23 highlights that in 95% of

        the comparisons, the errors of the proposed approach are statistically smaller than errors of the compared approaches.

        In the cases of EEMD-QRF-MOO and EEMD-GBM-MOO, for the states of PR and RJ respectively, the proposed approach presents only smaller errors than these approaches. Considering two-month-ahead or three-month-ahead forecasting, in 85% and 95% of the comparisons, respectively, there is a statistical difference between the errors. For this scenario, the biggest differences are found when the proposed model and EEMD- PLS-MOO are compared with two and three-month-ahead forecast in the states of MG and PR, respectively. It is possible to perceive that the proposed approach shows better performance in a statistical context, in 91.67% of the cases, allowing an inference that makes the developed framework efficient for the proposed task. Second, when the errors of the developed structure and the models that do not employ signal decomposition are compared, for all cases, there is a statistical difference. By comparing these results, Table 23 illustrates that the biggest differences are -3.82, -37.76 and -3.69 in MG and SP, states on the task of one, two and three-month-ahead forecast, respectively, for models GBM and QRF. Additionally, the smallest differences are -1.24, -1.24 and -1.40 for the state of PR, for the three forecast horizons, for models PLS, QRF, and BRNN, respectively. Therefore, these results showed that signal decomposition to forecast meningitis cases enhances the accuracy of the models.

        Also, the results presented in Table 23, by comparing the EEMD-HTE-MOO and EEMD-HTE-DI, in 86.67% of the cases, there is a statistical difference between the errors. Moreover, on the task of forecasting the meningitis cases in one and two-month-ahead for the state of PR, and three-month-ahead for the state of RJ, there is no statistical difference between the errors. Moreover, the smallest and biggest differences are observed on three-month-ahead for the state of MG (-1.32) and two-month-ahead forecast for the state of RJ (-1.92), respectively. Regarding what has previously been mentioned, it can be stated that the proposed approach showed a significant improvement concerning the use of the DI strategy for the task of grouping the EEMD components.

        Therefore, regarding the results presented in subsections 5.2.1, 5.2.2, 5.2.3 and 5.2.4, the proposed approach showed better accuracy than the compared models. In parallel, the proposed framework achieves excellent performance in 83.33% and 25% of the cases, and good results in 16.67% and 25% of the cases for sMAPE and RRMSE, respectively (LI et al., 2013). This shows that the use of signal decomposition, heterogeneous ensemble components and MOO combined can enhance the modelâs performance, taking into account the combination of each methodologyâs expertise.

        The forecast cases of meningitis are close to the observed values. The satisfactory performance regarding accuracy in terms of MAE, sMAPE, and RRMSE obtained in the training phase persists in the test stage, indicating that the proposed ensemble framework is robust to reach the developed predictions.

        The overfitting phenomenon occurs when the model has good generalization in the

        training set, but not in test set or out-of-sample forecasting. To avoid it, two approaches were considered in this case study. First, each adopted model was trained using a CV procedure, as described in the methodology subsection, to prevent overfitting. And second, when the bias and variance are objectives adopted in MOO, the trade-off between these measures is considered which leads to overfitting treatment. Also, by the illustrated through of predicted and observed values since a similar performance is observed in training and test sets, there is no evidence of overfitting.
