      5. Conclusions

        In this case study, an ensemble learning framework was proposed which combines signal decomposition, a heterogeneous ensemble of EEMD components and WI strategy to aggregate the decomposed components. The MOO approach used to find the PF and TOPSIS is employed to find the most suitable set of weights used during the WI stage. This approach is applied to forecasting three different horizons (one, two and three-month-ahead) of the meningitis cases for the states of MG, SP, PR, and RJ, Brazil. The performance of the proposed framework was compared to the performance of the models that do not employ signal decomposition, models that apply the same model to forecast all components obtained in the decomposition stage combined with MOO to signal reconstruction, and finally with an approach that employs signal decomposition, heterogeneous ensemble of components and DI strategy to reconstruct the original signal. The MAE, sMAPE and RRMSE criteria, as well as the DM test, were adopted to evaluate the performance of the developed approach. Finally, a residual analysis was conducted by the ACF plot and Ljung-Box (MORETTIN; TOLOI, 2006) test to validate the proposed forecasting model.

        According to the empirical findings of this case study, regarding RQ 1.2 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform the meningitis incidence forecasting?, it was concluded that the ensemble learning model based on MOO and HTE models could be adopted as a promising tool for forecasting epidemiological time series, especially the number of meningitis cases time series. In other words, the combination of

        EEMD, HTE, and the WI strategy for result aggregation with weights selected by NSGA-II TOPSIS allows the enhancement of the performance of the models for the adopted time series. In terms of RQ 3 -Considering pre-processing methods in the composition of an ensemble learning model, what is the better choice between the heterogeneous and homogeneous ensemble for time series forecasting?, the use of HTE models for components allows the improvement of the framework accuracy in relation to the use of a homogeneous ensemble of components.

        For the answer of RQ 4 - What is the proper choice between weighted integration through MOO and direct integration when time series pre-processing is used in the cooper- ative ensembles?, it was found that the use of the WI strategy to combine the components is better than the use of the DI strategy when optimization is employed to find the set of weights. It allows the proposed approach to reach better accuracy and stability (lower Std of the errors) than the compared models. Finally, for RQ 5 What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?, it was observed that employing signal decompo- sition improves the final results compared to not applying decomposition. Also, in 89.17% of the cases, there is a statistical difference between the errors of the EEMD-HTE-MOO framework and the compared structures. Also, in 89.17% of the cases, there is a statistical difference between the errors of the EEMD-HTE-MOO framework and the compared structures. To answer RQ 1.2, RQ 3, RQ 4, and RQ 5 the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

        For all selected datasets, the lower RMSE is achieved when Np is defined as 8, in which 8 groups of solutions were employed to try achieving suitable XGBoostâs hyperparameters. Also, looking for Nc, the most suitable hyperparameters are defined when 8 or 10 coyotes belong to the packs. In this context, the population of possible solutions is between 64 or 80 elements. In respect of the Std over 10 independent runs for each group of Np and Nc, except for the setting of the NSW-October dataset, the other results indicated lower variation for RMSE values of best setting in the remaining datasets.

        In comparison of best and worst results for each dataset, the best combination of COAâs control parameters reduced the RMSE in a range of 36% - 66.52%, 0.41% - 13.95%, 84.10% - 89.53%, 3% - 16.47%, and 2.74% - 4.80% for NSW-October, QLD-December,

        SA-May, TAS-August, VIC-October, respectively. The selection of appropriate control parameters of COA can lead to the most adequate XGBoostâs hyperparameters tuning.

        However, the solutions achieved are on average the most adequate. Therefore, in respect of these results, without loss of generality, the settings in bold of each dataset are adopted for each region and its respective seasons of the year.

For each setting, the algorithm is allowed by 50 iterations and is executed for 10 independent runs (FAN et al., 2020). The RMSE given by Eq. (2.62) is used as fitness function by DE, GA, and PSO.         According to the results depicted in Table 26 (best results highlighted in bold) regarding the comparisons of the use of COA metaheuristic in respect to the use of DE, GA, or PSO, using COA to tune the XGBoost hyperparameters for the seasonal component achieve better accuracy, in terms of MAE and sMAPE, than 95% and 97.5% of the compared models, for 12-hours and 24-hours-ahead STLF, respectively. The COA is outperformed by PSO and GA in SAâMay, as well as by PSO in VIC-August. For the forecasting horizon of 12-hours-ahead, the GA and DE optimizers can achieve the closest results of COA, followed by PSO, in terms of sMAPE according to the IP. Indeed, the COA improves the sMAPE in a range of 0.13% - 78.95%, 65.94% - 91.95%, 23.94% -

        83.37%, 66.68% - 85.32%, and 0.20% - 78.24% for NSW, QLD, SA, TAS, and VIC. Similar

        results are achieved when the forecasting horizon is 24-hours-ahead.

        The aforementioned results achieved by the COA are assigned by the fact this metaheuristic be able to maintain a good balance between exploration and exploitation to find reasonable solutions of XGBoostâs hyperparameters for the seasonal component of power load demand as pointed out by Pierezan et al. (2021). Moreover, the extensive search by defining the XGBoost is performed because it was the first time that COA was adopted to tune de XGBoost hyperparameters in the STLF context, and there are no guidelines in the current literature to support the choices of Np and Nc. On the other

        hand, the same was not done for GA, DE, and PSO since references that support the choices of control parameters for these methods were found as reported in Table 25.

      2. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and single decomposed ensemble models‌

        Through the results presented in Tables 27 and 28 the effectiveness of the proposed framework and single decomposed models are evaluated. The aim of this subsection is to verify if using STL-VMD pre-processing in the same framework outperforms VMD,

        MODWT, or STL pre-processed models. Besides, the compared models use the same algorithm to train all components obtained in the pre-processing stage. In this respect, twelve models are generated by combining VMD, MODWT, or STL with COA-XGBoost, SVR, RR, or ELM. Since the proposed framework uses two different pre-processing and the compared methods only one, it is possible to verify if heterogeneous ensemble methods can improve the forecasting results regarding homogeneous ensembles.

        Indeed, the improvement in the accuracy measures (based on OWA) ranges between 70.17% - 93.33% and 56.23% - 98.35% concerning MODWT and STL pre-processing, for a time window of 12-hours-ahead, respectively. Best results regarding sMAPE are obtained in dataset QLD-August.

        In the horizon of 24-hours-ahead, the proposed model can develop more accurate forecasts with lower errors. The improvement in the effectiveness ranges between 46.99% -

        92.58%, and 31.06% - 98.26% in relation to MODWT and STL pre-processing. Best results regarding sMAPE are obtained in dataset QLD-August.

        Comparing VMD with the proposed framework, the proposed ensemble outper- forms VMDâbased methods in 95% and 75% of the scenarios, for STLF 12 and 24-hours- ahead, respectively. For these study cases, there is an improvement in the forecasting accuracy, which ranges between 6.29% - 89.18%, and 9.27% - 94.58% for 12 and 24- hours-ahead. Competitive results of developed ensemble learning model and VMD-RR are observed for NSWâDecember for 12-hours-ahead, NSW region for October and December, VIC region for May and December, and QLD-December month for STLF 24-hours-ahead.

        The proposed framework outperforms most of the single decomposed models, by combining the effectiveness of STL to decompose the time series into three components, with the effectiveness of VMD to remove the data noise of STL residue and converting into time series with lower frequencies. The performance of the developed model can be defined as excellent since it reaches forecasting errors lower than 10% in both forecasting horizons. Indeed, the proposed ensemble can achieve satisfactory accuracy in terms of MAE and sMAPE since achieved lower values for these criteria regarding 85% of the compared models. Also, compared with VMD pre-processing, competitive results are observed for NSW, QLD, and VIC regions for 24-hours-ahead STLF.

        Concerning the results presented in Table 28, it is supposed that the COAâ XGBoost captured the weekly seasonality in most of the cases leading to forecasting errors lower than 5% in 24-hours-ahead, as observed for NSW, QLD, and TAS, for example. However, the absence of an extra feature to represent weekly seasonality can be the factor that leads to some high forecasting errors in the SA region.‌


      3. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and dual decomposed ensemble models

        In this subsection, the performance of the proposed model, STL-VMD, and STL- MODWT based homogeneous models are compared. The results are shown in Tables 29 and 30. In fact, this subsection has the purpose of verifying if the STL-VMD and STL-MODWT, where the same model trains the components, can improve the forecasting results concerning the proposed model. In this respect, eight forecasting models are compared by combining the aforementioned pre-processing strategies with COA-XGBoost, SVR, RR, or ELM. These comparisons are an extension of those presented in subsection 5.3.2.

        Considering the forecasting horizon of 12-hours-ahead, better MAE and sMAPE are achieved by the proposed ensemble learning model compared with other dual de- composed models. Regarding comparison with STL-MODWT, the OWA ranges between

        To forecasting 24-hours-ahead, the proposed model outperforms 100% of the other dual decomposed models. The models with the closest results of the proposed model, employed COA-XGBoost to handle the components, in most of the cases. On the other hand, the worst results were obtained by ELM and SVR, independent of the dual decomposition employed. Indeed, the OWA for the proposed model, with respect to

        the compared models ranges between 22.85% â 80.78%, 25.60% â 98.27%, and 27.11% â 95.42% for SA, TAS, and VIC regions, respectively, for STLâVMD approach. When the proposed ensemble learning is compared with STL-MODWT based models, the OWA ranges between 33.70% â 75.49%, 30.24% â 98.28%, and 33.33% â 95.48% for SA, TAS,

        and VIC regions, respectively.

        The dual decomposed heterogeneous ensemble learning model achieves better results than other dual pre-processed models. In this way, by combining STL with VMD to decompose the data, with COA-XGBoost and RR to handle the obtained components, it is possible to outperform STL-MODWT, and STLâVMDâbased homogeneous models. Generally, concerning the second technique employed to decompose the STL residuals, the STLâVMDâbased models reach better accuracy than others.

        Usually, VMD has better capability than DWT, consequently better than MODWT, to control the center frequency and the noise level, and it is more feasible for STLF second level decomposition (ZUO et al., 2020). Moreover, the lower performance of MODWT, compared to VMD is associated with the fact that in each decomposition level, only low-frequency series is processed by the low-pass filter.‌


      4. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and non-decomposed models

        The third comparison assesses the performance of the proposed ensemble learning framework regarding non-decomposed models. This subsection evaluates if the use o pre-processing techniques can help to improve forecasting accuracy for load forecasting regarding COA-XGBoost, SVR, RR, and ELM. These models are performing forecasts without pre-processing the data using VMD, STL, or VMD, for example.

        Results depicted in Table 31 show that STL-VMD-COA-XGBoost-RR outper- formed the stand-alone ML models. The proposed model presents better accuracy con- sidering simultaneously MAE and sMAPE, for both forecasting horizons. Indeed, the improvement in the accuracy ranges between 7.45% - 17.08%, and 15.25%-36.94% for both regions, in STLF 12, and 24-hours-ahead, respectively. In comparison with the proposed model, the RR regression was able to achieve errors closer to the proposed model for both forecasting horizons, regions, and seasons of the year. Moreover, in most of the cases, the XGBoost is unable to reach satisfactory forecasting in terms of sMAPE and MAE due to the features inherent to the load data.

        The accuracy of the proposed model is better than classic non-decomposed models, for STLF 12 and 24-hours-ahead. In this context, the proposed model is more adequate than the single models without decomposition for STLF. The STLâVMD presents itself as being the more robust and accurate model after the nonlinear and non-stationary signals

      5. Comparisons of proposed ensemble model versus state-of- art results

        This subsection aims to compare the proposed ensemble learning model with some of the existing state-of-the-art methods for the AEMO in five regions of Australia. Previously published relevant results were selected, taking into account that experimental design was well defined and explained, allowing to evaluate the proposed model under the same conditions. The year of analysis is 2013, and the months are January, April, July, and October, for the half-an-hour-ahead (Table 32) and 24-hours-ahead forecasting (Table 33). The state-of-art results were published by Qiu et al. (2017), Mohan et al. (2018), Zhang and Wang (2018a), Neeraj et al. (2021), and Fan et al. (2020). The main results are summarized as follows:

        Regarding the models presented in Qiu et al. (2017), which proposed a pre- processed by EMD model combined with DBN, the proposed STLâVMDâCOAâXGBoostâ RR can lead to better results in around 95% and 72.5% of the comparisons for half-an- hour-ahead and 24-hours-ahead forecasting, respectively. In most of the cases, Qiu et al. (2017) achieved better MAPE for the SA region taking into account the very-short forecasting horizon (half-an-hour-ahead). Compared STLâVMD with EMD pre-process, the dual STLâVMD can deal with the time series seasonality and avoid the errors due to the decomposition performed by EMD.

        Neeraj et al. (2021) proposed a hybridization of recurrent ANN named LSTM combined with the SSA time series pre-processing. Compared with this model, the proposed ensemble achieved better results than SSA-LSTM in 75% of the cases for both forecasting horizons. Indeed, the SSA-LSTM usually achieved better results for the QLD and TAS regions. The proposed model is more suitable for the STLF in 24-hours-ahead forecasting since can deal with a long sequence of data while the LSTM has difficulty dealing with it (GUO et al., 2021);

        Concerning the comparison with Mohan et al. (2018), which proposed a DMD model to decomposed and forecast the load data, the proposed model can achieve better results in 75% of the comparisons for 24-hours-ahead forecasting. The results of Mohan et al. (2018) are better than the proposed model in QLD and VIC taking into account the RMSE criterion, SA considering MAPE for January, July, and October.

        Finally, it is worth noting that the proposed ensemble learning model outperforms all results depicted in Fan et al. (2020) that proposed an improved version of Qiu et al. (2017) as depicted in Table 33. Despite Fan et al. (2018) proposed a robust MODBN, they

        Zhang and Wang (2018a)


        is adopted. It should be noted that the proposed model outperforms the approach of these authors which combined the pre-processing SSA, the ML model SVR optimized by CSA, and the ARIMA approach.

        Notwithstanding the aforementioned, it should note that the developed ensemble

        learning model named STLâVMDâCOA-XGBoostâRR can lead to satisfactory forecasting results by achieving good accuracy in terms of RMSE and MAPE criterion for the very- short and short-term forecasting horizons. Indeed, in terms of comparison with state-of-art methods applied for the AEMO in the context of load forecasting, the proposed ensemble learning model outperforms 71.25% of the approaches. In fact, even though the proposed framework presents higher errors in some comparisons, the investigation of this framework is valid. Indeed, there are no forecasting models that can perform equally well on all problems. Therefore, although the proposed ensemble learning model did not achieve ideal predictions in some cases, it overcomes the compared ones. Usually, it yields better results than some kinds of ANNs such as DBN and LSTM, different pre-processing such as EMD and SSA. Also, the major drawback is that the state-of-art methods such as SSA-LSTM, EMD-DBN, EMD-MODBN fail into 24-hours-ahead forecasting. At the same time, the proposed framework sounds consistent according to the evaluation of 20 datasets showing that the use of dual decomposition combined with heterogeneous models are suitable forecasting models (RIBEIRO et al., 2020a; RIBEIRO et al., 2020).‌‌


      6. Hypothesis tests and graphical analysis.

The results of the DM test are used to evaluate if the forecasting errors in the test set of proposed and compared models are statistically different at the significance level of 10%. Tables 35 and 36 present the statistic of DM test for all months in each region. The models with errors statistically equal are presented in bold. The model presented in Tables 35 and 36 are (A) COAâXGBoost, (B) SVR, (C) RR, (D) ELM,

(E) MODWTâCOAâXGBoost, (F) MODWTâSVR, (G) MODWTâRR, (H) MODWTâ ELM, (I), STL-COAâXGBoost, (J) STLâSVR, (K) STLâRR, (L) STLâELM, (M) STLâ MODWTâCOA-XGBoost, (N) STLâMODWTâSVR, (O) STLâMODWTâRR, (P) STLâ MODWTâELM, (Q) STLâVMDâCOAâXGBoost, (R) STLâVMDâSVR, (S) STLâVMDâ RR, (T) STLâVMDâELM, (U) VMDâCOAâXGBoost, (V) VMDâSVR, (X) VMDâRR, and (Z) VMDâELM. The results of the DM test indicate that the proposed framework achieves error signals statistically lower than most of the other models for STLF out-of- sample, at level of 10% of the significance (p-value<0.10).

In terms of the first forecasting horizon, 12-hours-ahead, the proposed STLâ VMDâCOAâXGBoostâRR presents errors statistically smaller than 99.58% regarding the compared approaches (p-value < 0.10). For STLF 12-hours-ahead, the biggest difference between errors occurs when the proposed model is compared with (S) STL-VMD-RR in NSW region, in August, season winter. Also, the most similar forecasting errors are achieved when the proposed model is compared with the (X) VMDâRR model, for NSW in December.

In respect to the STLF 24-hours-ahead, the developed ensemble learning model outperforms 96.45% of compared approaches in STLF 24-hours-ahead (p-value < 0.10) in terms of DM test. The proposed framework presents statistically greater errors than the (X) VMDâRR for NSW in October and December, QLD in December, VIC in May and December (p-value > 0.10). Moreover, the proposed model have errors lower than the (X) VMDâRR for QLD in October and August, SA in October and December, TAS in May, October, and December, as well as for VIC in August (p-value > 0.10). Some similar results are identified when the errors of the proposed and (Z) VMDâELM model are compared.

To illustrate the contribution of each forecasting model in the ensemble, without loss of generality, in Figures 54 up to 58 the predicted and observed load values are shown. Results for each component in the task of STLF 12-hours-ahead for five regions are presented. The COAâXGBoost and RR methods were used to handle the seasonal and remaining components, respectively.

the components are aggregated to recompose the original energy demand, the ensemble composed by RR models and COAâXGBoost achieved reliable load values, as presented in Figures 59 up to 63.

Regarding the computational cost in terms of training time, to decompose the original series, the methods STL, MODWT, and VMD take on average (Std) 0.29 s (0.008s), 0.05s (0.0156s), and 9.58s (1.49s), respectively. In terms of the secondary decomposition for the residual component, the MODWT and VMD methods take 0.045s (0.074s) and 3.16s (1.58s), respectively. For the models used to modeling each component, the COAâXGBoost, ELM, SVR, and RR take 512s (102.35s), 175.12s (32.68s), 12.21s (3.72s), and 5.34s (1.18s),

respectively. Combining this information, the approaches that use COAâXGBoost to handle all components have a higher training time. However, the use of RR has a lower training time. Alongside this, the proposed model has an intermediary training time of 542.35s (109.87s). Despite the proposed model achieving satisfactory accuracy, it has an intermediary training time that must consider during the decision-making process.

Figures 59 up to 63 illustrate the predicted versus observed values for test set (out-of-sample). For all cases, the proposed framework learns data behavior, in most of the cases, which allows predictions compatible with the observed values. There is a challenge in the 24-hour-ahead forecast task, since the recursive method accumulates the errors of previous forecasts to the next. Moreover, in this forecasting horizon, in the ups and downs, the forecasting model has difficulty in capturing the data variability. Generally, the results indicate that the proposed ensemble learning model is robust to reach the developed predictions. According to the results pointed out in Table 28, it can be observed that the forecasting errors of the proposed model are lower than 5% for NSW, QLD, and TAS regions, and between 5% and 7.5% for STLF 24-hours-ahead. In most experiments conducted in this study, ensemble learning strategies and optimization can help achieve satisfactory forecasting values in terms of adopted performance measures for 24-hours- ahead, even though the forecasting errors are higher than 12-hours-ahead. Despite the use of complex forecasting structures, as the forecasting time window increases, the error increases, as observed in the results found by this study and those pointed by Qiu et al. (2017), Mohan et al. (2018), Fan et al. (2020), and Neeraj et al. (2021).

In this case study, half-an-hour (1-step-ahead), half-day (24-steps-ahead), and one-day-ahead (48-steps-ahead) forecasting horizons were adopted to evaluate the accuracy of the developed framework. However, other different forecasting horizons can be adopted, such as 6-hours-ahead or 168-hours-ahead (one week) can be used. As reported in Tables 26, 32, 33, and 34 since the forecasting horizon increases, the accuracy decreases. Usually, for time series forecasting, when the forecasting horizon increases, the accuracy decreases, as can be observed in Qiu et al. (2017) and Neeraj et al. (2021).

In terms of the contribution of the individual forecasts in the composition of final forecasts, it is supposed that since the individual forecasts are DI (summation of forecasts from each model), each one of the six learners contributed in the same way in the final electric load forecasts. However, it is possible to compute the individual contributions using

In fact, alternatively to COAâXGBoost to handle the seasonal component, the seasonal NaÃ¯ve can be an appropriate choice to modeling this component. In this context, instead of using COAâXGBoost for the seasonal component, this persistence model was integrated with the proposed time series pre-processing. In fact, the seasonal NaÃ¯ve allow achieving forecasting results equals to observed value, since it repeat the last seasonal period. The improvement of NaÃ¯ve method, compared with proposed forecasting model is little. Indeed, based on MAE for STLF 12-hours-ahead, the improvement compared with COAâXGBoost is 1.89Ã10â7, 1.54Ã10â7, 1.84Ã10â7, 7.13Ã10â7, 6.83Ã10â9 for NSW,

QLD, SA, TAS, and VIC, respectively. In the same direction, for STLF 24-hours-ahead,

the improvement is 3.73Ã10â8, 3.20Ã10â8, 2.43Ã10â8, 1.61Ã10â7, and 1.22Ã10â8 for NSW, QLD, SA, TAS, and VIC, respectively. However, owing to the seasonal component being composed of identical daily sequences the COAâXGBoost achieved results close to the NaÃ¯ve approach. Also, according to the Figures 54 up to 58, notably the COAâ XGBoost was able to obtain STLF similar to observed load. The sMAPE and MAE of COAâXGBoost were on average 5.77Ã10â6% and 0.0003, respectively. Even though the results of NaÃ¯ve are a little better than our proposed method the COAâXGBoost can be viewed as an alternative to the use of NaÃ¯ve method when additional features are considered in the forecasting model, owing to its flexible based on data sources and patterns.

5.3.7 Conclusions‌

In this study, an ensemble learning model based on dual decomposition, which combines two decomposition techniques, AI models, and optimization was applied to electric STLF multi-step-ahead (12, and 24-hours-ahead). The developed framework used STL and VMD to pre-processing the raw data, the XGBoost coupled with the COA to handle seasonality, and the remaining components were modeled through the RR model. Datasets from AEMO, for NSW, QLD, SA, TAS, and VIC were adopted to evaluate the proposed framework. To compare different type of ensemble learning models, alternatively, MODWT was employed to pre-processing the STL residual component into four levels. The effectiveness of the proposed model was compared with several models including, non-decomposed, ensemble, single decomposed, as well as dual decomposed into four datasets related to the months (seasons) of the year for each region. The MAE, MAPE, RMSE, sMAPE, IP, and OWA criteria, as well as the DM statistical test, were adopted to evaluate the performance of the developed forecasting approach.

According to the results of this case study for RQ 1.3 -What is the most suitable cooperative ensemble learning structure to perform electric energy load forecasting?, it was observed that the most suitable ensemble learning model to forecast load energy is composed of the STL and VMD decomposition, where the COAâXGBoost is the better choice to deal with the seasonal component, and RR to handle the trend and VMD- based components. In other words, applying pre-processing techniques for seasonal data provides accurate forecasting. It is a suitable and alternative tool concerning the use of exogenous variables to forecast load data. Adopting the XGBoost model is a practical approach to dealing with cyclic components. However, it requires more computational effort. Moreover, adoptingVMD instead of MODWT in the second decomposition stage allows better accuracy and stability concerning to the forecasting errors.

Concerning RQ 5 - What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?, pre-processing approaches are able to reduce the forecasting errors and improving the accuracy. The proposed ensemble learning model improves the forecasting accuracy, which spans between 7.45% â 36.94% regarding non-decomposed models. Regarding RQ 6 - What gain is obtained by employing sequential decomposition methods over single decomposed methods for time series forecasting?, it was notable that when decomposition methods are used, there is an improvement in accuracy. The degradation of forecasting performance occurs in a smaller degree when comparing dual decomposed models to single and non-decomposed models. Alongside this, using time series pre-processing allows the use of heterogeneous dual decomposed ensemble learning models and reduces forecasting errors compared to homogeneous dual decomposed ensemble models. To answer RQ 1.3, RQ 5, and RQ 6 the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

    1. Case Study 4‌

      In this subsection, the results of three experiments are presented for case study detailed in subsection 4.4.

      Subsection 5.4.1 presents a comparison of the proposed framework considering different experimental settings. Subsections 5.4.2 and 5.4.3 detail the comparisons of the proposed framework with some ML, statistical models and ANNs, respectively. Finally, subsection 5.4.4 describes the analysis regarding the DM test and graphical analysis. In Tables 37 up to 40, the best results are presented in bold according to each performance criteria. Finally, Figures 64 and 65 illustrate the results of wind power with respect to the observed values, Figures 66 and 67 depict the scatterplot of the forecasted and observed wind power, and Figures 68 and 69 are used to evaluate the stability of the developed model.‌


      1. Comparisons of proposed ensemble model according to dif- ferent experimental scenarios

        In this subsection, the proposed framework, which comprises a combination of bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods, is evaluated according to different experimental settings. The first considers the use of MBB samples of different sizes, that is, 30, 50, and 100, and the second is the use of two aggregation strategies, which are the arithmetic average and weighted average through the MOO. Moreover, a comparison with the use of a single stacking ensemble learning model was conducted. Table 37 shows the performance measures.

        When comparing the number of adopted bootstrap samples, for the data from two wind farms, the use of 100 samples seems the most adequate to consider in the bagging strategy. The best forecasting results can be achieved in 71.87% of the cases when considering the metrics RMSE, MAE, MAPE, and U2. Specifically, this setting is suitable for wind power in three forecasting windows, that is, 10, 30, and 120minutes-ahead. Moreover, the use of 30 and 50 samples achieved the best results in 9.38% and 18.75% of the cases, respectively. Usually, when 50 samples are adopted, better results are found for wind power forecasting 60-minutes-ahead in terms of all performance measures.

        For the aggregation strategy employed to obtain the wind power for the considered forecasting horizons, independent of the bagging sample number, the weighted aggregation provides better forecasting results in 87.50% of the comparisons with the arithmetic average for both datasets in terms of the RMSE, MAE, MAPE, and U2. For dataset 1, in terms of the MAPE, there is an improvement that spans the intervals 0.34%â0.62%, 0.33%â0.97%, 0.60%â0.79%, and 1.19%â2.02% for 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead,

        respectively. For dataset 2, in terms of the RMSE, the improvement lies within intervals of 0.06%â 0.35%, 0.10%â0.71%, 0.77%â1.09%, and 0.80%â1.56% for 10, 30, 60, and 120-

        minutes-ahead, respectively. The model accuracy is considered excellent when RRMSE

        <10%, good if 10%< RRMSE <20%, fair if 20%<RRMSE<30%, and poor if RRMSE > 30% (DESPOTOVIC et al., 2016). In this respect, in both datasets and all forecasting windows, despite the high MAPE observed, according to the RRMSE, the proposed model achieved a good forecasting accuracy. The major factor related to a high MAPE is the high variability of the test set, which is approximately 45% in terms of the coefficient of variation. Second, MAPE is sensitive to extreme observations, that is, outliers errors can lead to high MAPE values.

        In the use of the weighted average, defining the weights for the MBB samples through the MOO is an efficient strategy to obtain an efficient forecasting model, since the MOO allows dealing with the trade-off between bias variances while assigning different weights for the sample from the bagging ensemble learning method (RIBEIRO et al., 2020b). For samples that allow forecasting results similar to the observed value, larger weights are assigned. By contrast, in other samples that are less important, minor weights are assigned to the composition of the wind power, as observed by Ribeiro et al. (2020), Ribeiro and Reynoso-Meza (2021).

        With respect to the investigation of the stacking and bagging ensemble learning methods and the integration feasibility regarding a single stacking ensemble, Table 37 shows that the combination of these two competitive ensembles can provide better wind power forecasting in terms of accuracy regarding the single stacking ensemble learning model for all adopted forecasting performance criteria. Indeed, in the evaluation of WDF1, the improvement in MAE achieved by the proposed framework regarding the stacking ensemble learning model is 4.59%, 11.48%, 14.49%, and 11.87% for 10, 30, 60, and 120- minutes-ahead, respectively. In addition, for WDF2, the improvements in U2 are 8.34%, 13.72%, 14.88%, and 11.84% for wind power forecasting 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead, respectively.

        Considering the aforementioned comparisons, as pointed out by Bergmeir et al. (2016) who showed that bagging combined with ETS outperforms a single ETS, it can be seen that the integration of bagging and stacking ensemble methods performs better than single stacking in the wind power forecasting task. According to the discussed by

        Petropoulos et al. (2018), the successful use of bagging is achieved since it deals with three sources of uncertainty: data uncertainty, model uncertainty, and parameter diversity. In this study, these uncertainty sources were handled by integrating bagging with stacking ensemble learning and MOO for a weight assignment.

        Achieving a balance between the accuracy and efficiency of the ensemble model is an important aspect of data modeling. Indeed, as pointed out previously, according to the results presented in Table 37, increasing the number of MBB samples also increases the forecasting accuracy in most cases. Notably, if the forecasting horizon increases, the improvement of the forecasts in terms of MAPE reduction, for example, increases. Every improvement is important. According to Maldonado et al. (2019), a reduction of 1% in the forecast error can reduce the operational cost of the electric sector by US$ 10 million.

        By contrast, when the number of samples increases, the forecasting framework becomes more complex. In this context, as pointed out by Li et al. (2020b), complex forecasting models (in our case, models with several base models) have higher computational costs, which leads to an efficiency reduction in terms of the model training time (seconds). In this respect, regarding the implementation of the proposed forecasting model in the company system, two questions must be considered to deal with the trade-off between balance and efficiency. The first one is related to the importance of the forecasting accuracy in the real-time decision-making process for the renewable energy sector. Second, it should be considered whether the accuracy improvement compensates for the greater computational cost to support the decisions involved in preventive maintenance, electricity market clearing, and reload sharing.‌


      2. Comparisons of proposed ensemble, stacking base models, and artificial neural networks

        In this subsection, the integration of bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods is compared with the base models adopted in the stacking layer-0 and XGBoost models. Moreover, comparisons of proposed model with some ANNs such as ANFIS, CNN, ELM, GRU, LSTM, and RNN are presented.

        In the context of wind power forecasting 10-minutes-ahead, according to the results presented in Table 38, the proposed ensemble learning model outperforms the compared base models with respect to adopted performance measures for both datasets. Considering the data from WDF1, the improvement ranges 8.19%â17.16%, 2.47%â13.84%, 6.37%â24.71%, and 7.51%â16.85% for RMSE, MAE, MAPE, and U2, respectively. When WDF2 was evaluated independently of the performance measure according to the results presented in Table 39, similar results were achieved. Considering the 30-minutes-ahead approach for both datasets, XGBoost has the worst results compared with the proposed

        model, whereas the SVR has the most similar results in terms of the MAPE.

        Concerning the third forecasting horizon, that is, wind power forecasting, the proposed 60-minutes-ahead forecasting model has an average improvement over the base models of 8.08%, 7.47%, 7.58%, and 7.90% for RMSE, MAE, MAPE, and U2, respectively, in WDF1. However, the improvements were 8.21%, 7.57%, 7.72%, and 8.05% in terms of RMSE, MAE, MAPE, and U2, respectively for WDF2. Regarding the horizon of the 120-minutes-ahead approach, similar improvements are observed, but with less magnitude. It is clear that the proposed ensemble learning model outperforms its base models in terms of forecasting accuracy regarding the presented performance measures.

        It is worth mentioning that the presented improvements of the proposed bagging combined with the stacking ensemble learning model are not achieved by the base models. They fail to achieve satisfactory forecasting results owing to the non-stationarity and complexity of wind power (SILVA et al., 2021). Indeed, the proposed model was able to learn the data behavior because by using several forecasting base models, each one with a different learning structure, they learn distinct features of the wind power, and when the meta-learner uses their predictions to provide the final wind forecast, the results can be more similar to the observed values, and better forecasting measures are then obtained.

        Compared to the proposed ensemble learning model, the single models LSTM and CNN models achieved the most similar forecasting accuracy in terms of MAE for the first forecasting horizon regarding other compared ANNs. Alongside that, for the remaining time windows, ELM and ANFIS reached the best results between the ANNs in terms of RRMSE, however, worst than the proposed model. Alongside this, the mean RRMSE for both datasets achieved by the proposed model is 0.1363, and for GRU, LSTM, RNN, CNN, ELM, and ANFIS was 0.1911, 0.1841, 0.2119, 0.171, 0.1709, and 0.1663, respectively.

        The aforementioned results indicate that proposed ensemble improves the RRMSE in 28.68%, 25.95%, 35.68%, 20.29%, 20.25%, and 18.04%, respectively. The ranking of ANNs with the most similar performance to worst regarding the proposed model is ANFIS, ELM, CNN, LSTM, GRU, and RNN. The presented comparisons further indicate that the single forecasting models cannot provide satisfactorily forecasting results for wind power generation compared with ensemble learning models, mainly owing to the nonlinearities of the wind energy. In addition, ensemble learning models can achieve the most reliable and accurate results and outperforming some types of ANNs, as observed in Zhang et al. (2021) and Li et al. (2022).

      3. Comparisons of proposed ensemble and statistical models‌

        In this subsection, the performance of the proposed bagging stacking ensemble learning model is compared with statistical methods. The selection of statistical methods hyperparameters is automated according to the definitions from forecast (HYNDMAN et al., 2021) package using the Akaike Information Criterion. Considering the results presented in Table 40, the proposed method succeeds in improving the forecasts obtained by several statistical methods such as ARIMA, TBATS, THETA, and persistence (or NaÃ¯ve) models for wind power recorded every 10 minutes. From a broader perspective, whereas all statistical methods obtained a MAPE of greater than 20% for wind power forecasting 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead, the proposed method can achieve errors of lower than 20% for the first three forecasting windows, and up to 1.25% greater than 20% for 120-minutes-ahead.

        Compared to the proposed ensemble model with ARIMA modeling, the improve- ments in RMSE were 8.71%, 24.82%, 30.74%, and 35.20% for wind power forecasting 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead, respectively. For WDF2, the improvement in RMSE was similar to the data from WDF1. concerning the comparison with the TBATS approach, the improvement of MAE ranged between 2.11%â2.26%, 21.47%â21.62%, 28.77%â29.17%, and

        32.50%â32.88% for wind power forecasting 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead, respectively, in both datasets.

        Concerning the results of the THETA model regarding the efficient bagging stacking ensemble model, the proposed approach is more effective in obtaining forecasting for the four time windows. Indeed, the improvement in the U2 criterion, for example, is 8.09%, 24.28%, 30.80%, and 35.67% for 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes ahead, respectively. It can also be seen that the same occurs for dataset 2. Compared with other statistical methods, the persistence model has more difficulty in achieving results similar to the observed values since forecasting the observed value of lag 1. For the aforementioned comparisons, it is possible to observe that the ARIMA, TBATS, THETA, and persistence methods can provide satisfactory forecasting results for the first forecasting horizon but fail when larger forecasting horizons are considered. While the proposed forecasting model achieved a good forecasting accuracy in terms of the RRMSE, the compared statistical models exhibited a poor performance because they reached RRMSE > 30%.

        The aforementioned findings reinforce the experimental results found by Awajan et al. (2018), Ribeiro et al. (2020), and Massaoudi et al. (2021), who verified that using ML models integrated with bagging ensemble or stacking ensemble learning models can provide more accurate results for a time series forecasting than statistical methods.

        Ensemble learning methods can lead to a better forecasting accuracy because they deal with the nonlinearity, non-stationarity, and intermittent behavior of wind energy. This is because there is an approximation of the Std of the predicted values of the observed data. Subsequently, these results occur because the use of MOO helps to achieve a better prediction accuracy and more excellent stability of the residues simultaneously by dealing with the trade-off between the bias-variance paradigms.

      5. Conclusions‌

        In this study, an efficient forecasting model was proposed. Bagging and stacking ensemble learning models were integrated to achieve wind power forecasting 10, 30, 60, and 120-minutes-ahead for two wind farms located at SÃ£o SebastiÃ£o do Alto and Rio Verde cities, Bahia, Brazil. Wind power production was recorded every 10 minutes in each WDF. The bagging ensemble was used for resampling (30, 50, or 100 samples) the residual component obtained from the STL, using MBB. Each new sample was trained and fitted using the stacking ensemble learning models. The forecasting of the samples was grouped through arithmetic averages and weighted averages to generate the final forecasting models. To enhance the forecasting accuracy and stability simultaneously, MOO was employed to define the weights used in the aggregation of the bootstrap samples. The MAE, U2, RMSE, RRMSE, MAPE, and IP criteria were adopted to evaluate the performance of the compared. Moreover, the DM hypothesis test was employed to verify the presence of a statistical difference between the errors of the compared models.

        Regarding RQ 1.4 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform multi-step wind power generation forecasting?, it was possible to observe that the bagging combined with stacking ensemble learning and MOO can achieve better results than single stacking and statistical models. The results of this case study addressing RQ 7 - What improvement is reached by combining bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods against the single stacking and statistical models? found that stacking combined

        with a bagging ensemble improves the forecasting accuracy by 7.63% in terms of the errors in the single stacking ensemble learning model. Alongside this, notably, the use of a weighted average for the arithmetic average can provide better accuracy in terms of the MAE, U2, RMSE, and MAPE in 87.50% of the comparisons for all forecasting horizons. Compared with statistical models and ANNs, the proposed forecasting model improves the forecasting accuracy in terms of the RMSE by 25.64% and 20.4%, respectively. Concerning the number of bootstrap samples, better forecasting results regarding the performance measures were achieved in 71.88% of the comparisons when 100 bootstrap samples were considered in the ensemble learning composition, followed by 50 and 30. Therefore, the findings of this case study show that the integration of two ensemble strategies can provide accurate forecasting results in the field of wind energy and can help the decision makers to provide preventive maintenance, electricity market clearing, and reload sharing. To answer RQ 1.4 and RQ 7, the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

        Despite satisfactory results in terms of the forecasting accuracy presented in this study, this research has certain limitations, such as the selection of base models that compose the stacking ensemble. Moreover, the proposed model has a complex structure in terms of base models compared to statistical methods and higher computational costs in terms of training time.


        Chapter 6‌


        Conclusions and Future Works



        This thesis aimed at the proposition of cooperative and competitive ensemble learning models to perform time series forecasting. The proposed methods were evaluated considering the time series related to agribusiness, epidemiology, electric energy demand, and renewable energy. In the agribusiness field, commodity prices in particular are usually volatile and suffer the influence of exogenous factors. In turn, epidemiology time series related to the incidence of diseases have the features of nonlinearity, the absence of the trends, and are non-stationary. Electric energy demand has a seasonal and non-stationary behavior due to speed changes in the pattern of the consumers. Alongside this, renewable energy, specifically wind energy, is usually highly fluctuating due to the intermittent behavior of wind speed. Therefore, to deal with the features mentioned earlier, this thesis has focused on developing ensemble learning methods to perform time series forecasting and improve forecasting accuracy. Initially, in chapter 1 the contextualization, motivation, objectives, justifications, and contributions of the thesis are introduced. In chapter 2 the theoretical background necessary for the development of the proposed approaches is presented. In chapter 3 the related works are presented, and in chapter 4 the proposed forecasting models are presented as four case studies, and the contributions to the area of application are described. Finally, in chapter 5 the results and conclusion remarks for each case study are detailed

        Regarding the first problem tackled in this thesis, the subsection 5.1 deals with the evaluation of three ensemble learning methods called bagging, boosting, and stacking for agricultural commodity price forecasting. The soybean and wheat commodities were considered. Based on the literature review related to economic analysis, exogenous factors were identified and considered price drivers. Considering RQ 1.1 -What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform price forecasting in agribusiness time series?, the findings suggest that to forecast one-month-ahead, three models can be adopted as follows: XGBoost and LASSO-KNN-XGBoost-SVR stacking ensemble learning to forecast soybean prices, and RF to forecast wheat prices. In both cases, the BC (Î» = 0) is applied to predictors and exogenous variables. The results regarding the test set ensure that the

        ensemble approaches perform better than single models, especially the XGBoost model, to forecast agricultural commodities in the short term. In addition, the approaches based on boosting for ensemble generation proved to be robust for the commodity price forecasting one-month-ahead.

        In addition, the conducted experiments verified that the stacking ensemble accuracy is linked with the diversity of the base models and not with the number of members of the layer-0. For the answer to RQ 2 -What are the appropriate price drivers to use as exogenous factors in the forecasting structure of agricultural commodities?, it was found that the exogenous factors, the interaction between commodity prices in the domestic market, prices in the external market, and exchange rate play a vital role in the price direction of considered commodities. From a broader perspective, this first case study showed that the evaluated ensemble learning methods in the presence of correct exogenous factors achieve better accuracy than single models for time series forecasting. To answer RQ 1.1 and RQ 2, specific objectives (a) and (b) were achieved.

        Concerning the second case study covered in subsection 5.2, a cooperative ensemble learning model was proposed to forecast the meningitis incidence one, two, or three months ahead in four PR, MG, SP, and RJ states, Brazil. The developed forecasting model is composed of the pre-processing technique EEMD, a heterogeneous ensemble learning model of components aggregated with weights through MOO. According to the empirical findings of this case study, regarding RQ 1.2 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform the meningitis incidence forecasting?, it was concluded that the ensemble learning model based on MOO and HTE models could be adopted as a promising tool for forecasting epidemiological time series, especially the number of meningitis cases time series. In other words, the combination of EEMD, HTE, and the WI strategy for result aggregation with weights selected by NSGA-II TOPSIS allows the enhancement of the performance of the models for the adopted time series.

        In terms of RQ 3 - Considering pre-processing methods in the composition of an ensemble learning model, what is the better choice between the heterogeneous and homogeneous ensemble for time series forecasting?, the use of HTE models for components allows the improvement of the framework accuracy in relation to the use of a homogeneous ensemble of components. For the answer of RQ 4 - What is the proper choice between weighted integration through MOO and direct integration when time series pre-processing is used in the cooperative ensembles?, it was found that the use of the WI strategy to combine the components is better than the use of the DI strategy when optimization is employed to find the set of weights. It allows the proposed approach to reach better accuracy and stability (lower Std of the errors) than the compared models. Finally, for RQ 5 What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?, it was observed

        that employing signal decomposition improves the final results compared to not applying decomposition. Also, in 89.17% of the cases, there is a statistical difference between the errors of the EEMD-HTE-MOO framework and the compared structures. To answer RQ 1.2, RQ 3, RQ 4, and RQ 5, the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

        In subsection 5.3 an ensemble learning model comprised of dual decomposition and heterogeneous ensemble of components was proposed to deal with seasonal time series related to electric energy demand. To deal with seasonal and trend components, the STL decomposition was used to obtain the daily seasonality, trend, and residual components. Since the residual subseries has a nonlinear behavior, it was decomposed using VMD pre-processing. The model COAâXGBoost was used to deal with the seasonal behavior, while RR was used for the remaining components. The forecasts were obtained from DI aggregation. This case study used twenty time series associated with the AEMO across the five Australian regions. The proposed framework was evaluated considering the load forecasting half-hour, half-day, and one-day-ahead. Moreover, comparisons between the proposed model and results from the literature were also performed.

        According to the results of this case study for RQ 1.3 -What is the most suitable cooperative ensemble learning structure to perform electric energy load forecasting?, it was observed that the most suitable ensemble learning model to forecast load energy is composed of the STL and VMD decomposition, where the COAâXGBoost is the better choice to deal with the seasonal component, and RR to handle the trend and VMD- based components. In other words, applying pre-processing techniques for seasonal data provides accurate forecasting. It is a suitable and alternative tool concerning the use of exogenous variables to forecast load data. Adopting the XGBoost model is a practical approach to dealing with cyclic components. However, it requires more computational effort. Moreover, adoptingVMD instead of MODWT in the second decomposition stage allows better accuracy and stability concerning to the forecasting errors.

        Concerning RQ 5 - What is the improvement achieved by employing time series pre-processing methods through decomposition techniques over non-decomposed and single models?, pre-processing approaches are able to reduce the forecasting errors and improving the accuracy. The proposed ensemble learning model improves the forecasting accuracy, which spans between 7.45% â 36.94% regarding non-decomposed models. Regarding RQ 6 - What gain is obtained by employing sequential decomposition methods over single decomposed methods for time series forecasting?, it was notable that when decomposition methods are used, there is an improvement in accuracy. The degradation of forecasting performance occurs in a smaller degree when comparing dual decomposed models to single and non-decomposed models. Alongside this, using time series pre-processing allows the use of heterogeneous dual decomposed ensemble learning models and reduces forecasting errors compared to homogeneous dual decomposed ensemble models. To answer RQ 1.3,

        RQ 5, and RQ 6 the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

        Motivated by the increasing use of renewable energy worldwide, subsection 5.4 addressed the improvement of forecasting model accuracy in the context of wind power generation. This study evaluated the cooperative ensemble learning model that combines bagging and stacking methods applied to time series forecasting with very short-term (10 and 30-minutes-ahead) and short-term (60 and 120-minutes-ahead) evaluations of wind power generation. In this respect, two questions were addressed. The first is about the forecasting approach used to handle the samples obtained by the bootstrap method from bagging. In this case, the stacking ensemble was used. The second is regarding the combining method used in the aggregation stage. In this context, the use of weighted and arithmetic averages were compared as aggregation methods. In this respect, the MOO was employed to tune the weights of the weighted average, aiming to enhance the forecasting accuracy and stability simultaneously. The suggested model has been implemented on two wind power datasets gathered from a wind farm in Bahia, Brazil.

        Regarding RQ 1.4 - What is the most suitable ensemble learning structure to perform multi-step wind power generation forecasting?, it was possible to observe that the bagging combined with stacking ensemble learning and MOO can achieve better results than single stacking and statistical models. The results of this case study addressing RQ 7 - What improvement is reached by combining bagging and stacking ensemble learning methods against the single stacking and statistical models? found that stacking combined with a bagging ensemble improves the forecasting accuracy by 7.63% in terms of the errors in the single stacking ensemble learning model. Alongside this, notably, the use of a weighted average for the arithmetic average can provide better accuracy in terms of the MAE, U2, RMSE, and MAPE in 87.50% of the comparisons for all forecasting horizons. Compared with statistical models and ANNs, the proposed forecasting model improves the forecasting accuracy in terms of the RMSE by 25.64% and 20.4%, respectively. Concerning the number of bootstrap samples, better forecasting results regarding the performance measures were achieved in 71.88% of the comparisons when 100 bootstrap samples were considered in the ensemble learning composition, followed by 50 and 30. Therefore, the findings of this case study show that the integration of two ensemble strategies can provide accurate forecasting results in the field of wind energy and can help the decision makers to provide preventive maintenance, electricity market clearing, and reload sharing. To answer RQ 1 and RQ 7, the specific objectives (a) to (e) were achieved.

        Although the proposed forecasting models have achieved satisfactory results regard- ing the forecasting accuracy, the proposed ensemble learning models have some limitations. Firstly, the first case study highlighted the use of only agricultural commodities. However, the prices related to energy, metal, and livestock commodities should be considered. More- over, feature selection methods to choose the best set of predictors are encouraged. Next,

        in the second case study, the proposed framework was applied to four states with the highest meningitis incidence in Brazil in 2018. Notwithstanding, it could apply to other states and countries. Also, climatic effects, demographic factors, and general politics were not considered by the model. Inherent in the last three case studies, the computational cost is the major limitation. Each forecasting model deals with several subseries and different forecasting methods in its composition, which can increase the processing time. As pointed out by Makridakis et al. (2020b), which analyzed the results of the M4 competition, the improvement achieved by the models based on ML also increases the computation time. In this respect, for practical purposes, one may question whether the extent of the improvement compensates for the more significant computational cost involved. In this context, notably,the limitation of this research is minimized if the computational expenses do not compromise the decision-making process. Also, since new samples are available, the training process must be re-conducted to obtain new forecasting.

        From a broader perspective, the results and contributions presented in this thesis lead to several findings. The first one is that ensemble methods allow the forecasting users to deal with different features of real time series in various fields of application such as economy, epidemiology, and engineering. The use of ensemble methods allows coping with the dilemma of selecting a single approach to solve complex forecasting tasks. Furthermore, notably, when pre-processing techniques are employed to obtain a cooperative ensemble model, different forecasting models, i.e., the use of a heterogeneous model, is encouraged to handle the subseries. The diversity achieved through this allows the forecasting model to reach accurate results. Finally, it was verified that using a weighted average through MOO is an effective way of tuning ensemble weights, which makes the forecasting model more accurate and stable simultaneously. Therefore, through the several comparisons performed in this thesis across four cases studies in a range of applications, it is possible to conclude that using ensemble learning methods for time series forecasting is a helpful tool for developing efficient forecasting models. From a broader perspective, through the analysis of empirical findings detailed in this thesis, the hypothesis that ensemble learning methods can improve the accuracy of the forecasting models in one and multi-step-ahead forecasting time windows is supported and should not be rejected.

        The research on time series analysis and forecasting is an attractive topic that supports the decision-making process. In this sense, developing highly accurate forecasting models is needed. Concerning this, through the analysis of the proposed forecasting models, some opportunities for future research can be identified, but are not limited to the following:


        • Using feature selection techniques based on evolutionary algorithms to filter a suitable set of exogenous factors related to the agricultural commodities of case study 1;

        • Decomposing the commodity prices using pre-processing techniques to extract additional features of the data;

        • Defining the forecasting models for the subseries using an automatic process based on optimization;

        • Combining the clustering and time series pre-processing methods to group subseries with similar features and using forecasting models to handle it.

        • Adopting the VMD pre-processing for data decomposition and bootstrapping the residuals component of the time series;

        • Developing probabilistic forecasting models in terms of forecasting intervals.

Appendix B‌



Additional Tables for Case Study 2




Table B1 presents the control hyperparameters obtained by GS during CV process, for each component obtained by EEMD as well as for models that not considers signal decomposition. Alongside, the GS is performed only for tunnable parameters of each model contained in caret package. Between parentheses, for each algorithm are present the parameters used on one to three-months-ahead forecast, respectively. In addition, for GBM model, the parameters shrinkage and minimum number of terminal node size are defined as 0.1 and 10, respectively. The train function from the caret package in R software was used in the training process. In this respect, using the argument tuneLenght, the number of elements of the search space was defined for the hyperparameters GS. In that definition, it was taking into account that a lower value for tuneLenght can be not sufficient to lead to accurate forecasting results, a higher tuneLenght can increase the training time.

In the next Table B3 presents the weights assigned for each model adopted in the signal reconstruction, in which M1 is the model EEMD-MOO-BRNN, M2 is the model EEMD-MOO-CR, M3 is the model EEMD-MOO-GBM, M4 is the model EEMD-MOO- PLS and M5 is the model EEMD-MOO-QRF. Additionally, after the weight assigned for each component of proposed model, the models employed for each component are presented.

Appendix C‌‌


Additional Table for Case Study 3




The hyperparameters of the proposed and compared models were defined as described in the next. For MODWT six levels of decomposition were adopted (five details and one approximation component), and the âDaubletâ 2 (âdb2â) mother wavelet was chosen through GS by minimization of Shannon-Entropy criterion (GAO; YAN, 2011). Also, for VMD, the number of components was defined as 6. In the context of dual decomposition approaches, the models were composed of six components (seasonality, trend, and four components related to the approach employed in the second stage). For the proposed model, Table C1 presents the hyperparameters of COA-XGBoost adopted to train and predict the seasonal component. Besides, the ELM (number of neurons, activation function, and weights initialization), SVR (with radial basis function kernel, sigma, and cost), and RR (regularization - Î») hyperparameters were chosen by automatic GS in caret package (KUHN, 2008). For the RR model, in NSW-Autumn, for Mode1 and Mode3, as well as in QLD-Spring, Mode4 the regularization is defined as 1E-4, and for remain components and VIC region, as 1E-3. The train function from the caret package in R software was used in the training process. In this respect, using the argument tuneLenght, the number of elements of the search space was defined for the hyperparameters GS. In that definition, it was taking into account that a lower value for tuneLenght can be not sufficient to lead to accurate forecasting results, a higher tuneLenght can increase the training time.

Appendix D‌‌


Additional Table for Case Study 4




Table D1 presents hyperparameters of each method. The hyperparameters tuning of each ML model was conducted by GS during the time series cross-validation according to the definitions of caret package (KUHN, 2008) by minimization of RMSE considering the training set. The base-leaners hyperparameters search space was defined automatically. The train function from the caret package in R software was used in the training process. In this respect, using the argument tuneLenght, the number of elements of the search space was defined. In that definition, it was taking into account that a lower value for tuneLenght can be not sufficient to lead to accurate forecasting results, a higher tuneLenght can increase the training time. In the same way for base-learners models, the hyperparameters of ELM and ANFIS neural networks were defined. For LSTM, RNN, GRU, and CNN methods, the hyperparameters were defined by GS, taking into account that higher values for epochs and hidden layers can lead to overfitting and higher computational cost, while lower values can be insufficient to achieve satisfactory results in terms of accuracy. For the statistical methods, the selection is automated according to the definitions from forecast (HYNDMAN et al., 2021) package using the Akaike Information Criterion.
